1. d4 e6 2. Nf3 ({I frequently met} 2. c4 {with} Bb4+ {, heading for an accelerated Bogo-Indian.}) 2... f5 {I have also played this move, but with different ideas.} 3. g3 Nf6 4. Bg2 g6 $5 {This came as a surprise. I remember that the late grandmaster Theodor Ghitescu, who was my trainer a long time ago, used to define a "patzer" as a "...g7-g6 and ...e7-e6 player". This is just a joke, of course, since there are many systems where these two moves fit together well, but Ghitescu had in mind such cases when this combination of plans creates chronic weaknesses. Black switches to a system used by Botvinnik in his first match with Tal in a moment when things had won astray for him and he badly needed to win. In fact, this strong need to achieve a certain result is familiar to me when I play the Leningrad Dutch. I remember that when asked how come I play such a risky opening, I automatically answered: "I play it when I need to win. When I absolutely need to draw, too!" I will not embark on a longer philosophical discussion here, but the essence is that it is an opening you can rely on under certain circumstances, depending also on the mood. The Muzychuk sisters had the Leningrad Dutch in their repertoire more than a decade ago, when they used to represent Slovenia. I knew that they were using the 7...e6 system frequently, and I associated this with the fact that the outstanding Leningrad expert Malaniuk, also a Ukranian player also tried it in several games.} ({In recent years, I have played} 4... Be7 5. O-O O-O 6. c4 (6. Nbd2 Ne4 {The same knight jump as below.} 7. b3 d5 8. Bb2 Nc6 9. c4 Bd7 10. Ne1 Be8 11. Ndf3 Bf6 12. e3 g5 13. Nd3 {Psakhis, L (2461) -Marin, M (2521) Wch Seniors 50 29th 2019 (4) 1/2-1/2}) 6... Ne4 {The so-called Alekhine system.} (6... d6 {leads to the Iljin Zhenevsky system.}) 7. Nfd2 d5 8. e3 c6 9. b3 Nd7 10. Ba3 b6 11. Bxe7 Qxe7 12. Qc2 Bb7 13. Nf3 Rac8 14. Nbd2 c5 15. Qb2 g5 16. Rac1 Qg7 17. Rfd1 g4 18. Ne1 cxd4 19. exd4 f4 {Lavrinenkov,V (2306) -Marin,M (2524) Bayern-chI Bank Hofmann 23rd 2019 (7) 1/2-1/2 with strong initiative.}) 5. c4 Bg7 6. Nc3 O-O 7. O-O d6 {Botvinnik reached this position via a normal Leningrad Dutch move order.} 8. Re1 Ne4 9. Qc2 Nxc3 10. Qxc3 Nc6 (10... e5 $1 {is better.}) 11. Bg5 (11. b4 $1 {is more problematic.} e5 12. b5 $14 Nxd4 13. Nxd4 exd4 14. Qa3 Qe7 15. Bd2 $14 {[%cal Ge2e3] followed by e2-e3 soon, with considerable advance in development for the pawn.}) 11... Qe8 {Following the game until the end is interesting, just to get a picture of the way things could go Black's way in the long run.} 12. Qd2 e5 13. dxe5 dxe5 14. Bh6 Qe7 15. Bxg7 Kxg7 16. Qc3 Qf6 17. Rad1 Be6 18. h4 h6 19. b4 {It seems as if White did not do anything wrong yet, but,  she did not do anything special, either. It is not Nurgyul's fault the position after the opening is simply comfortable for Black. Anna has played very well and will continue doing so.} e4 20. Nd4 Rae8 21. Nxe6+ Rxe6 22. Rd7+ Rf7 23. Rxf7+ Kxf7 24. Qe3 g5 25. hxg5 Qxg5 26. Qxg5 (26. f4 exf3 27. Qxg5 hxg5 28. Bxf3 {is a more restrictive move order, transposing to the game.}) 26... hxg5 {Despite mass simplifications, White has micro problems. Even after the long diagonal opens, the knight will be a bit more versatile than the bishop.} 27. f3 exf3 (27... Nd4 28. fxe4 fxe4 $15 {maintains Black's space advantage.}) 28. Bxf3 Kf6 29. Kf2 $2 (29. b5 Nd4 30. Kf2 (30. Bxb7 Rxe2 31. Rxe2 Nxe2+ 32. Kf2 Nc3 33. Ke3 Ke5 34. a3 Na4 $15) 30... Nxf3 31. Kxf3 Re4 32. Rc1 $15) (29. Bd5 Re3 (29... Rd6 30. b5 Na5 31. e4 fxe4 32. Bxe4 c6 $11) 30. Kf2 Ra3 31. Bxc6 bxc6 32. Rh1 Kg7 33. Rd1 $11) 29... Nxb4 $17 30. Bxb7 Rb6 31. Bf3 Nxa2 32. g4 fxg4 33. Bxg4 a5 34. Ra1 Rb2 35. Bd7 Ke5 36. Rg1 Kd6 37. Rd1+ Ke7 38. Bg4 a4 39. Rd7+ Kf6 40. Rxc7 Nc3 41. Ra7 Rb4 42. Ra6+ Ke5 43. Bf3 Rxc4 44. Ra5+ Kf6 45. Ra6+ Ke7 46. Ra7+ Kd6 47. Ra6+ Kc7 48. Ra5 g4 49. Bd5 Nxd5 50. Rxd5 Kb6 51. Kg3 a3 52. Rd1 Kc5 53. Rb1 Ra4 54. Rc1+ Rc4 55. Rb1 Re4 56. Kf2 Kc4 57. Rb8 Kc3 58. Ra8 Kb3 59. Rb8+ Rb4 60. Ra8 a2 61. Kg3 Ra4 62. Rb8+ Kc4 63. Rc8+ Kd5 0-1

