1. d4 e6 2. c4 f5 3. g3 Nf6 4. Bg2 g6 5. Nf3 Bg7 6. O-O O-O 7. b3 d6 8. Bb2 Qe7 ({As explained in the database,} 8... Nc6 $1 {is the right move here.}) 9. Re1 (9. Nc3 Nc6 10. d5 $14) 9... Nc6 10. Nc3 Ne4 11. Qd3 Nxc3 12. Bxc3 e5 13. e4 f4 14. d5 Nd8 {Black has achieved a comfortable King's Indian version. This is one of the main reasons one plays the Dutch!} 15. b4 g5 16. c5 Nf7 17. Rac1 g4 18. Nd2 (18. Nh4 Bf6 $5 19. Nf5 Bxf5 20. exf5 Bg5 21. Rc2 Nh6 22. Be4 Qf6) 18... Ng5 19. Nc4 fxg3 (19... Bd7 $1 {was indicated by Knaak after the game.} 20. Na5 fxg3 21. fxg3 Nf3+ 22. Bxf3 Rxf3 23. Qe2 Raf8) 20. fxg3 (20. hxg3 Nf3+ 21. Bxf3 gxf3 $17) 20... Bh6 21. cxd6 $6 (21. Bd2 $13) 21... cxd6 22. Bd2 Bd7 23. Bxg5 $6 (23. Ne3 Nf3+ 24. Bxf3 gxf3 $15) 23... Bxg5 24. Ne3 Qd8 $17 {Taking advantage of White's earlier inaccuracies.} 25. Kh1 Qb6 26. Nc4 Qa6 27. Rc3 (27. Rb1 Rac8 $19) 27... Rac8 28. Qc2 (28. a4 Kg7 $3 {is the winning move, evacuating the king from the back rank, in order to enable a tactical trick. Now, ...Bxa4 is a threat since in a similar line as above, the bishop would be defended on h6.} ({During the game I relied on} 28... Bxa4 {wins} 29. h4 $3 ({I had calculated only} 29. Ra1 Bc2 $19) 29... Bh6 30. Ra1 $1 Bc2 31. Rxa6 Bxd3 32. Rxd6 b5 33. Rxh6 bxc4 $15) 29. b5 Qxa4 30. Nxd6 Qa5 $3 31. Nxc8 Rxc8 $19 {White cannot connect his rooks and cannot take on c8, either, because that would be without a check.}) 28... Ba4 (28... h5 $1 29. Rf1 Rxf1+ 30. Bxf1 b5 31. Na5 Rf8 32. Bg2 Qb6 $19) 29. Qe2 h5 30. Ra3 (30. Rf1 $15) 30... Qxc4 $19 31. Qxc4 Rxc4 32. Rxa4 a6 (32... Be3 $19) 33. Bf1 (33. Rf1 Rxf1+ (33... Bd2 $19) 34. Bxf1 Rxe4 $19) 33... Rc2 34. b5 a5 35. Kg1 (35. Rxa5 Bd2 $19) 35... Bd8 {My opponent exclaimed here in German: "What is this?", obviously meaning that it was the time to resign. Which he kindly did.} 0-1

