1. d4 e6 { As mentioned above, this is a flexible move. If White does not play 2.e4, we will go for 2.. .f5, but we will not commit ourselves completely. Only if White uses the standard, neutral, move order, should we switch to the Leningrad Dutch. I could say that we secretly hope for the Leningrad, but are ready to choose different setups if required. I also believe that this way, we prevent our repertoire from being too monotone and we can develop a wider positional understanding of several Dutch schemes. } ( { There is nothing wrong with } 1... f5 { , of course. But White can try to take us out of the standard schemes in several ways. } 2. c4 $5 ( 2. Bg5 $5 { and } ) ( 2. Nc3 $5 { are quite popular. } ) 2... Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 { and now } 4. Bg5 { is quite a dangerous fashionable system. } ) 2. Nf3 { This is the start of the neutral and classical development I was talking about, but not before White plays the main move g2-g3. } ( 2. g3 { is a common answer to our first move, too, and can induce some differences in our plan. } 2... f5 3. Bg2 Nf6 4. c4 { I used to play the Dutch Defence as a teenager and knew that White usually does not hurry with c2.c4. The reason obviously is } ( { I have explained in the database that after having spent a tempo on ...e7-e6, I wish to meet } 4. Nh3 Be7 { followed by ...d7-d6 and ... e6-e5, in order to restrict the edged knight as soon as possible. This setup is known as the Iljin Zhenevsky system. } ) ( 4. Nf3 { transposes back to the "neutral" main lines. } ) 4... Bb4+ { and I followed the classical fashion by making it our repertoire choice. } ( 4... g6 5. Nc3 { transposes to a position mentioned below, which I prefer to avoid. } ) ) ( 2. c4 f5 ( { Some of my opponents usually refrain from 2.c4 in avoidance of } 2... Bb4+ ) 3. Nc3 Nf6 { Against this move order, I have chosen ...Bb4 almost whenever possible. } 4. g3 ( { The only exceptions are } 4. e3 b6 { and } ) ( 4. a3 g6 { After White has spent a tempo on a2-a3, there is no risk involved in switching to the Leningrad setup. } ) 4... Bb4 ( { One of the things I do not like after } 4... g6 { is } 5. Bg2 Bg7 6. d5 $5 ) ) 2... f5 3. g3 ( 3. h3 { is not really dangerous. } 3... Nf6 4. g4 d5 ) ( 3. Bg5 { is also inoffensive due to } 3... Be7 ) ( 3. Bf4 { is more challenging. Since Black needs to fight against the f4-bishop as soon possible, I have chosen } 3... Nf6 4. e3 Be7 { followed by ...0-0 and ...d7-d6, fully in the spirit of the Iljin Zhenevsky system. } ) 3... Nf6 4. Bg2 g6 { Finally no counterindication! } 5. O-O Bg7 6. c4 ( 6. Nbd2 { , } ) ( 6. b3 { and } ) ( 6. b4 { induce some differences with respect to the similar lines in the genuine Leningrad Dutch. Since ...e7-e6 is an early commitment, Black cannot use the normal plans, but at the same time, the move itself is useful. Therefore, he can switch to different, quite original, setups. } ) 6... O-O 7. Nc3 ( { The same discussion as above goes for } 7. b3 { and } ) ( 7. b4 ) 7... d6 { Here we are, in the main tabiya of the Botvinnik/Muzychuk Leningrad! If we compare this position with those arising after 7...Qe8, 7...c6 or 7...Nc6 in the usual Dutch, we may think that Black has wasted a tempo. His main plan is advancing his pawn to e5, is it not? Things are not that crystal clear. First of all, in all those main lines, White can play 8.d6, switching to a different structure and forcing Black to abandon his initial dreams. Secondly, ...e7-e6 can be useful in several moments, especially if Black plays ...Ne4, when after the exchange, he could consolidate the central pawn with ...d6-d5. In a conclusion, I would remind you that in Dresden I played this system a few times, without full preparation, achieving 2,5 out of 3. After working on this article, I am ready to do it frequently in the future. I hope that you will enjoy the opening yourself! } *
