1. d4 e6 2. Nf3 f5 3. g3 Nf6 4. Bg2 g6 { Since White has chosen a natural, but not immediately threatening setup, now is a good moment to switch to the Leningrad system. } ( { The main problem in the Iljin Zhenevsky system is that after } 4... Be7 5. O-O O-O 6. c4 d6 7. Nc3 Qe8 8. Re1 { , Black cannot stop e2-e4: } 8... Qg6 9. e4 fxe4 10. Nxe4 $14 Nxe4 11. Rxe4 Qxe4 $2 12. Nh4 $18 { , trapping the queen. } ) ( 4... d5 { is of course fine, but this is an entirely different system! } ) 5. O-O Bg7 6. Nbd2 { The plan of preparing a quick opening of the centre is known in the normal Dutch lines. In our position, it is obvious that Black will not be in time for organizing... e6-e5, but the same applies in the positions where he plays ...d7-d6 instead of ...e7-e6. } ( 6. b3 { is examined in Line 2. } ) ( 6. b4 { is the subject of Line 3 } ) 6... O-O 7. Re1 ( 7. c3 { is a half-waiting move, inviting Black to define his intentions. } 7... a5 $5 { Since White is not threatening anything yet, this is a constructive continuation. } ( 7... Nc6 { is also interesting and if } 8. Re1 { then } 8... d5 ) 8. a4 ( 8. Qc2 d5 9. Ne5 { Vasilevich,T (2400) -Schubert,T (2374) BL2-Ost 0506 2005 (3.3) 1-0 } 9... b6 10. Ndf3 Ne4 11. h4 c5 12. Bf4 Ba6 13. Rad1 Nd7 { [%cal Gd7f6] Planning ...Ndf6-g4. } 14. Nxd7 Qxd7 15. Ne5 Qe8 16. Rfe1 cxd4 17. cxd4 Rc8 18. Qb3 Qb5 19. Qa3 Qb4 $11 { Black's activity compensates for the weakness on e5. } ) 8... b6 $14 9. Ne5 ( 9. b4 axb4 10. cxb4 b5 $11 ) 9... d5 10. Ndf3 c5 $11 ) 7... d5 { We can state that Black has an extra tempo with respect to the lines where he plays ...d7-d6 instead of ...e7-e6. The pawn on e6 is useful by consolidating the centre. Black does not need the square on e6 for his bishop as he can develop it in different ways. } 8. c4 ( 8. Ne5 a5 $14 { Waiting for White to play Ndf3 before playing ...Ne4. This way, White will have two knights competing for one square. } ( 8... Nbd7 9. Ndf3 c5 10. c3 Ne4 11. Nxd7 Bxd7 12. Ne5 { Bryndin,A (2148) -Filippov,I RUS-chT U18 Orsk 2002 1-0 } 12... Rc8 13. Be3 b6 $11 ) ( 8... c5 9. dxc5 Ne4 10. Nd3 Qe7 11. c4 Nxd2 12. Bxd2 dxc4 13. Nf4 e5 14. Nd5 Qf7 15. Qa4 Bd7 16. Qxc4 Be6 17. e4 Nc6 18. Rad1 Rad8 19. f3 Nd4 20. Be3 Bxd5 21. exd5 Qxd5 22. Qxd5+ Rxd5 $11 ) ( 8... Ne4 ) 9. c3 ( 9. Ndf3 Ne4 10. c3 c5 $11 ) ( 9. a4 c5 10. dxc5 Qe7 11. Nd3 Rd8 12. Nf3 Ne4 13. Be3 e5 ) 9... c5 10. dxc5 Nc6 11. Ndf3 Qe7 12. Be3 Ne4 $13 ) 8... Ne4 ( 8... Nc6 $5 { is another possible move order. } 9. e3 Ne4 10. a3 a5 11. b3 g5 12. Bb2 g4 13. Ne5 Nxe5 14. dxe5 Nxd2 15. Qxd2 { Richter,M (2517) -Vallejo Pons,F (2684) Wch Rapid Berlin 2015 (1) 0-1 } 15... dxc4 16. Qxd8 ( 16. Qc3 Qd3 $11 ) 16... Rxd8 17. bxc4 Bd7 $11 ) 9. Qc2 Nc6 10. e3 a5 { This makes part of Black's plans of expansion. } ( { But so does } 10... g5 $11 ) 11. a3 ( 11. b3 $6 { runs into } 11... g5 { , causing serious problems. } 12. Ba3 { Other natural moves are likely to cause quick disaster. } ( 12. a3 $2 g4 13. Nh4 Nxf2 $1 14. Kxf2 f4 $19 ) ( 12. Bb2 $2 Nb4 13. Qb1 g4 $1 14. Nxe4 gxf3 $19 ) 12... Nb4 13. Bxb4 axb4 14. Ne5 Qe7 $15 ) 11... a4 $11 { After reaching a queenside blockade, Black is not worse for sure. } 12. Nb1 $6 { Asking too much from the position. Did White hope to win the pawn on a4? } 12... Na5 13. Nfd2 ( 13. cxd5 Nb3 $1 14. Ra2 Qxd5 15. Nc3 Qd7 16. Nxe4 fxe4 17. Qxe4 e5 18. Nxe5 Bxe5 19. Qxe5 Qf7 $19 { Attacking f2 and threatening to win material with ...Nxc1. } ) 13... c5 $17 14. cxd5 cxd4 15. Nxe4 fxe4 16. Qxe4 Nb3 17. dxe6 Re8 18. e7 Rxe7 19. Qd5+ Be6 20. Qxd8+ Rxd8 21. exd4 Bf6 22. Nc3 Nxa1 23. d5 Bf5 { Arnaudov,P (2471) -Anton Guijarro,D (2673) EU-Cup Online Gr-I rapid 2021 (7.1) 0-1 } *
