1. d4 e6 2. Nf3 f5 ( { Since I will later refer to certain Queen's Indian structures, now is the moment to explain which Tabiya I had in mind. } 2... Nf6 3. c4 b6 4. g3 Bb7 5. Bg2 Be7 6. O-O O-O 7. Nc3 Ne4 8. Qc2 Nxc3 9. Qxc3 f5 10. b3 Bf6 { One of Kortschnoj's favourite systems, yielding him a few memorable wins, for instance, two against Polugaevsky and one against Miles. } ) 3. g3 Nf6 4. Bg2 g6 5. O-O Bg7 6. b3 { In the normal Leningrad Dutch, this way of developing is aimed at causing Black problems with carrying out ...e7-e5. Since in our system Black has spent a tempo with his e-pawn already, it is likely that he has to change plans a bit. } 6... O-O ( 6... b6 { may be premature due to } 7. Ba3 $5 ) 7. Bb2 { The move order at this stage can induce important nuances. } ( 7. Nbd2 { takes e4 under control, inhibiting ...b7-b6 in view of Ne5, but this move is an important commitment. } 7... a5 $14 { With the knight on d2, this is just natural. Black creates the potential threat ...a5-a4 but also clears the square on a7 for the rook. This move is new, but it will soon transpose to a position rehearsed in practice already. } 8. Bb2 b6 9. c4 ( 9. Ne5 { is onoffensive due to } 9... Ra7 { Black intends to proceed with ...d7-d6 and ...c7-c5, opening the rook's communication with the rest of the board. } 10. e4 fxe4 11. Nxe4 Nxe4 12. Bxe4 a4 13. Rb1 a3 14. Ba1 d5 15. Bg2 Bxe5 16. dxe5 c5 $11 ) 9... Bb7 { This position was met already in practice. } 10. Rc1 ( 10. a3 Na6 $5 11. Qc2 Qe7 12. Rad1 d6 13. Qb1 Rae8 14. Ba1 c5 15. Bc3 Qc7 16. Qb2 Nb8 $11 { Bindrich,F (2594) -Vallejo Pons,F (2684) Wch Blitz 9th 2015 (20) 0-1 } ) 10... Na6 11. a3 Qe7 12. e3 d6 13. Qe2 c5 14. Rfd1 Rad8 $11 { Black has good control in the centre and is well regrouped. } 15. Nb1 Ne4 16. Nc3 Nxc3 17. Bxc3 e5 18. dxe5 dxe5 $11 19. Rxd8 Rxd8 20. Rd1 $2 Rxd1+ 21. Qxd1 e4 22. Bxg7 exf3 $19 { Radjabov,T (2765) -Vachier Lagrave,M (2758) Carlsen Inv Prelim rapid 2021 (8) 0-1 } ) ( 7. c4 { transposes to Line 4. } ) 7... b6 { Due to White's insufficient control over e4, this is possible. The move ... e7-e6 fits well into the Queen's Indian hybrid. We will see quite a bit of it in later lines, but against the white king's fianchetto, the idea is slightly unusual, of course. } 8. c4 ( 8. Ne5 Ne4 { is fine for Black. } 9. f3 ( { Chellenging Black in the centre with } 9. Nd2 Bb7 10. Nxe4 Bxe4 11. Bxe4 fxe4 { is likely to leave the e5-knight in an uncomfortable situation. } 12. f3 d6 13. Ng4 Nc6 14. fxe4 Rxf1+ 15. Kxf1 Qg5 16. Nf2 Rf8 17. c3 e5 $17 ) ( 9. c4 Bb7 10. Qc2 d6 11. Nd3 Nd7 $11 ) 9... Nd6 10. c4 ( 10. Nd3 Bb7 11. c4 Nf7 12. e3 { Bottenberg,F-Nozicka,V (2018) W-ch WS/H/604 email 2017 1-0 } 12... c5 $11 ) ( 10. f4 Bb7 11. Bxb7 Nxb7 12. c4 c5 $11 ) 10... Bb7 11. Nc3 ( 11. e3 Nf7 12. Nxf7 Rxf7 13. Nc3 d5 $11 { With the white pawn on f3, Black can safely switch to this type of structure. } ) 11... f4 $1 { In the Leningrad Dutch, Black has to be always ready for this pawn sacrifice. True, with the knight on d6, there are some specific aspects involved. } 12. Bh3 ( 12. gxf4 Nf5 13. Qd2 d6 $15 ) 12... Nf5 13. Bxf5 Rxf5 14. Qd2 c5 15. gxf4 cxd4 16. Nb5 Qh4 17. Nd3 Rh5 18. Rf2 Nc6 19. Nd6 Rb8 $11 ) ( 8. Nfd2 { more or less forces } 8... d5 { However, Black does not have problems after switching to a different structure, since the knight retreats to d2 implies a considerable waste of time. } 9. c4 Ne4 $5 ( 9... Bb7 10. Nc3 Nbd7 11. Rc1 c5 12. cxd5 exd5 13. dxc5 Nxc5 $14 { Artemiev,V (2660) -Anton Guijarro,D (2626) Lake Sevan Martuni 2015 (3) 1/2-1/2 } ) ( 9... Na6 10. Nc3 Bb7 11. Rc1 Ne4 12. Nf3 Qe7 13. Ne5 Rad8 14. cxd5 Nxc3 15. Bxc3 Bxe5 16. dxe5 Bxd5 $11 ) 10. Nxe4 ( 10. Nc3 Bxd4 $13 ) ( 10. e3 c5 $11 ) 10... dxe4 11. f3 c5 12. fxe4 Bb7 13. exf5 Bxg2 14. Kxg2 Rxf5 15. Rxf5 gxf5 16. e3 Nc6 17. Qf3 Qe8 18. Na3 Rd8 $11 { In these lines, White's delay in development is an issue. } ) 8... Bb7 9. Nc3 { We have reached a typical (or maybe not so typical) hybrid between the Owen, the Leningrad Dutch and the Queen's Indian. We will have the surprise that coming from a slightly different move order, there are several games of strong grandmasters from this position. } 9... Ne4 { The typical Queen's Indian knight jump. } ( 9... a5 { is also possible. } 10. Qc2 Na6 11. a3 Qe7 12. Rad1 d6 13. Rfe1 Rad8 14. Ng5 Bxg2 15. Kxg2 e5 16. e4 f4 $13 { Sasikiran,K (2639) -Vallejo Pons,F (2684) Wch Rapid Berlin 2015 (14) 1/2-1/2 } ) 10. Nxe4 ( 10. Rc1 d6 11. Qd3 Nd7 12. Nd2 d5 { For reasons familiar to us, this move is good, but not forced. } ( 12... Nxd2 13. Qxd2 Bxg2 14. Kxg2 Qe7 15. e4 f4 $11 ) 13. Nf3 c6 14. e3 Qe7 15. Ne2 a5 ( 15... g5 $11 ) 16. Qc2 Rfc8 { Black is perfectly regrouped. } 17. Rfd1 a4 ( 17... b5 $11 ) 18. Ne1 axb3 19. axb3 c5 $11 ( 19... Ra2 { only wastes time. } 20. Ra1 Rca8 21. Rxa2 Rxa2 22. Nd3 $14 { Keymer,V (2591) -Lagarde,M (2648) Biel rapid 54th 2021 (1) 0-1 } ) ( 19... g5 $11 ) ) 10... Bxe4 11. Qd2 d6 { It really looks like a Queen's Indian now. } 12. Rad1 ( 12. Ng5 Bxg2 13. Kxg2 ( 13. Nxe6 Qe7 14. Nxg7 Bxf1 15. d5 Qxe2 16. Qc3 Qd3 $19 ) 13... Qe7 14. f4 ( { Preparing e2-e4 requires some time. } 14. Rae1 h6 15. Nf3 Qf7 16. Qd1 { Overdefending the knight in order to allow e2-e4. } 16... Nd7 17. e4 Rae8 $11 { followed by ...g6-g5. } ) 14... h6 15. Nh3 Nd7 16. Rac1 Nf6 { Black does not have any problems. } 17. Nf2 d5 18. Rc2 Rad8 19. c5 Ne4 20. Nxe4 dxe4 21. cxb6 cxb6 22. Rfc1 Rd7 23. Rc8 Kh7 24. R1c6 Rxc8 25. Rxc8 g5 $11 { Perrichon,J-Murey,J (2496) Paris-ch op 2002 (1) 0-1 } ) 12... Qe7 13. Ne1 { This is the most typical way of exchanging the bishops. } 13... Bxg2 $14 { Natural and good. } ( 13... Nd7 $5 14. Bxe4 fxe4 15. Qc2 Nf6 16. Ng2 d5 ( 16... c6 17. d5 cxd5 18. Bxf6 Bxf6 19. cxd5 exd5 20. Rxd5 $16 { Prie,E (2465) -Murey,J (2460) Clichy 1998 (2) 1/2-1/2 } ) 17. cxd5 exd5 18. Qc6 Rad8 19. Rc1 Rf7 $11 ) 14. Nxg2 { White has two main ideas, e2-e4 or d4-d5. The latter only makes sense if it ensures the knight's intrusion into e6. } 14... Nd7 ( 14... Nc6 $5 { is another possible way of developing the knight. } 15. Rfe1 ( 15. d5 Bxb2 16. Qxb2 Nd8 $11 { The white knight does not have access to e6. } 17. dxe6 Nxe6 ) 15... Rae8 16. e4 fxe4 17. Rxe4 Qd7 18. d5 ( 18. Ree1 d5 $11 ) 18... Bxb2 19. Qxb2 ( 19. dxc6 Qxc6 20. Rde1 Be5 21. f4 Bf6 22. Rxe6 Rxe6 23. Rxe6 b5 $11 ) 19... Ne5 20. f4 exd5 21. Re3 Ng4 22. Rxe8 Rxe8 23. Rxd5 ( 23. cxd5 Qb5 $17 ) 23... Qe6 $11 ) 15. Nf4 { Targeting e6. } ( 15. Rfe1 Nf6 $11 ) 15... Nf6 ( 15... Rf7 16. d5 ( 16. Rfe1 Nf6 17. d5 Ne4 18. Qc2 e5 19. Ne6 Bh6 20. Kg2 Ng5 21. Bc1 f4 $11 ) 16... e5 17. Ne6 Nc5 18. Nxg7 Rxg7 19. b4 Ne4 20. Qc2 a5 21. a3 Rf7 22. f3 Nf6 $11 ) ( 15... g5 16. Nh5 Bh8 $13 ) 16. d5 ( 16. f3 g5 17. Nd3 h6 $11 ) 16... Ne4 17. Qc2 Bxb2 18. Qxb2 e5 19. Ne6 Rf7 $11 { followed by either ...Ng5 or ...Nc5 } *

