1. d4 e6 2. Nf3 f5 3. g3 Nf6 4. Bg2 g6 5. O-O Bg7 6. b4 { This is a typical plan in the normal Leningrad Dutch, too. It has similar ideas as b2-b3 but combines them with an early space gain on the queenside. It would be the perfect move if it did not expose the b-pawn at a stage when White is not developed yet. } 6... O-O 7. Bb2 ( 7. c4 { transposes to Line 5. } ) 7... Nc6 $14 { This new move aims at exploiting the pawn's exposure and the relative weakness on c4. } ( { There is no clear refutation of } 7... b6 { , but I am slightly worried by the fact that after } 8. Ne5 Ne4 9. Nd2 Bb7 { , one of Black's plans is based on ...c7-c5. With the pawn on b3, there would be no problem with it, but here it may cause small problems. } ) 8. a4 { The most ambitious continuation. } ( 8. b5 Na5 9. Nbd2 d5 { initiates the fight for the queenside and central light squares. } 10. c4 ( 10. Bc3 c6 11. a4 Ne4 $11 ) 10... a6 11. a4 Nxc4 ( 11... Ne4 12. Qc2 Nxc4 { transposes. } ) 12. Nxc4 dxc4 13. Qc2 Ne4 14. Qxc4 ( 14. bxa6 Rxa6 15. Qxc4 c5 $11 ) 14... Qd5 15. Qxc7 ( 15. Qxd5 exd5 16. Ne5 axb5 17. axb5 Be6 $11 ) 15... axb5 16. axb5 Rxa1 17. Rxa1 Qxb5 18. Ba3 Re8 $11 { Black is well regrouped and quite stable. He could continue with . ..Bd7-c6 soon. } 19. e3 ( 19. Ne5 Bxe5 20. dxe5 Qxe2 $13 ) 19... Bd7 20. Bf1 Qc6 21. Rc1 Qxc7 22. Rxc7 Bc6 23. Bc4 Nc3 $11 ) ( 8. a3 { is passive. } 8... b6 9. Ne5 ( 9. c4 Bb7 10. Nc3 Qe7 11. Qc2 { Preventing ...Ne4. } 11... Nd8 12. Rfd1 Nf7 $11 { With a harmonious regrouping. } ) 9... Nxe5 $1 { Mainly possible because of the weakness on c4. } 10. dxe5 ( 10. Bxa8 Nc4 $1 11. Bc1 c6 $13 ) 10... Ne4 11. Nd2 Bb7 12. c4 Nxd2 13. Qxd2 ( 13. Bxb7 Nxc4 $5 14. Bxa8 Nxb2 15. Qd4 d6 16. Qxb2 Bxe5 17. Qa2 Bxa1 18. Qxe6+ Kg7 19. Bf3 Bf6 ) 13... Bxg2 14. Kxg2 f4 $1 15. gxf4 Qh4 $11 ) 8... Nxb4 { This is the principled move, but Black can play more solidly, too. } ( 8... Ne4 9. Ba3 ( 9. c3 d5 $11 ) ( 9. Nbd2 $6 Nxb4 10. Ba3 $2 Nc3 $19 ) ( 9. b5 Na5 $11 ) 9... Re8 10. c4 d5 11. e3 ( 11. b5 Na5 $11 ) ( 11. cxd5 exd5 12. e3 a5 13. b5 Nb4 14. Qb3 c5 15. bxc6 bxc6 16. Bxb4 Qb6 $11 ) 11... e5 $5 12. cxd5 ( 12. b5 exd4 $11 13. bxc6 dxe3 14. Ra2 exf2+ 15. Raxf2 Nxf2 16. Rxf2 bxc6 $17 ) 12... exd4 $1 13. dxc6 ( 13. exd4 Qxd5 $15 ) 13... dxe3 14. Ra2 exf2+ 15. Raxf2 Nxf2 16. Qxd8 Rxd8 17. Kxf2 bxc6 18. Rc1 a5 $13 ) ( 8... d5 $5 { is also playable. } ) 9. Ba3 c5 10. dxc5 Ne4 11. Bxb4 ( 11. c3 Na6 $13 12. c6 bxc6 $5 13. Bxf8 Qxf8 $15 ) 11... Bxa1 12. Nfd2 { Due to his advance in development, White will get dangerous initiative for the exchange. } 12... a5 13. Ba3 Nxd2 14. Qxd2 Bf6 15. Nc3 Ra6 16. Nb5 Be7 { Preparing ...b7-b6. } ( 16... b6 $2 17. cxb6 $16 ) 17. Rd1 b6 18. c6 ( 18. Nd6 bxc5 19. Bxc5 Qc7 20. Ba3 Bxd6 21. Bxd6 Rxd6 22. Qxd6 Qxd6 ( 22... Qxc2 ) 23. Rxd6 Kf7 $11 { For instance: } 24. c4 ( 24. f4 Ke7 25. Rb6 d5 26. Rb5 Ba6 27. Rxa5 Bxe2 28. Ra7+ Kd6 29. Kf2 Bc4 30. Rxh7 Ra8 $11 ) 24... Ke7 25. Rb6 f4 26. Be4 d6 27. Rb5 Ba6 28. Rxa5 Bxc4 $11 ) 18... dxc6 19. Qe1 Qe8 20. Nd6 ( 20. Nc7 Qf7 21. Bxe7 Qxe7 22. Nxa6 Bxa6 23. Bxc6 Rd8 $11 ) 20... Bxd6 21. Rxd6 b5 22. axb5 cxb5 23. Rxa6 Bxa6 24. Qxa5 Bc8 25. Bxf8 Kxf8 $11 { White's advantage is purely symbolic. I suspect that in a practical game I might choose one of the solid alternatives to ...Nxb4, but these lines after the pawn capture are also interesting and viable for Black. } *

