1. d4 e6 2. Nf3 f5 3. g3 Nf6 4. Bg2 g6 5. O-O Bg7 6. c4 O-O 7. b3 { This move order induces certain differences with respect to 6.b3 followed by 7.Bb2, examined in Line 2. With the c2-square available for the queen, the plan based on ...b7-b6 does not work now. On the other hand, White has not only spent a tempo on a pawn move (c2-c4) , but also deprived his knight of the square on c4. } 7... d6 { Following the main Leningrad Dutch plan. } ( 7... b6 { runs into } 8. Ba3 ( { The simpler } 8. Ne5 { is also good. } 8... Ne4 9. Nd2 Bb7 10. Qc2 d5 11. Bb2 $14 { Black was induced to adopt this structure without White making any concession (such as Nfd2 for instance) . } ) 8... Re8 9. Ne5 Ne4 10. f3 Nd6 11. f4 Ne4 ( { The difference with respect to Line 2 is that } 11... Bb7 { runs into } 12. Bxd6 $1 Bxg2 13. Bxc7 $1 Qxc7 14. Kxg2 $16 ) 12. Nd2 Bb7 ( 12... d5 13. cxd5 exd5 14. Rc1 Bb7 15. Nxe4 dxe4 16. g4 ) 13. Nxe4 fxe4 14. Qc2 $16 d6 15. Bxe4 $1 ) ( { After } 7... Ne4 { , preparing ...b7-b6 as in the line with b2-b4 below, White can play } 8. Nbd2 { , keeping Qc2 in reserve. Black would have problems maintaining his central stability. } ) 8. Bb2 ( 8. Ba3 Nc6 9. Nc3 { transposes to Line 10. } ) ( 8. Nc3 { transposes to Lines 8 to 10. } ) 8... Nc6 ( 8... Qe7 { is a commitment and a waste of time. } 9. Nc3 ( 9. Re1 Nc6 10. Nc3 Ne4 11. Qd3 Nxc3 12. Bxc3 e5 13. e4 f4 14. d5 Nd8 $11 { Knaak-Marin, Dresden 2023. } ) 9... Nc6 10. d5 $1 ( 10. Qc2 $5 e5 $6 11. dxe5 dxe5 12. Nd5 $16 { Now is when the early queen's commitment counts. } ) 10... Ne5 ( 10... Nd8 11. dxe6 Nxe6 12. Nd5 Qf7 13. Qc2 Ne4 14. Nd2 $14 ) ( 10... Ne4 11. dxc6 Nxc3 12. Qd3 Ne4 13. Bxg7 Kxg7 14. Nd4 $16 ) 11. Nd4 ( 11. dxe6 Nxf3+ 12. exf3 Bxe6 13. Re1 Qf7 14. f4 Rab8 15. Nb5 Rfe8 16. Rc1 a6 17. Nc3 b5 { Ushenina,A (2458) -Muzychuk,M (2490) Wch Blitz final (Women) 2012 (13) 1-0 } 18. Nd5 $16 ) 11... exd5 12. cxd5 { Filip,M-Holm Pedersen,S Olympiad-20 Final A 1972 (1) 1-0 } 12... h5 $14 ) 9. d5 { The critical move. } ( 9. Nbd2 { absolves Black of any worries connected with a knight jump to d5, allowing } 9... Qe7 { White cannot stop .. .e6-e5 with Nc4. } 10. Qc2 ( 10. Re1 e5 11. e4 f4 12. d5 Nb4 13. Nf1 { Bommini, M (2158) -Grieve,H (2312) Budapest Vezerkepzo IM 9th 2021 (2) 1/2-1/2 } 13... a5 14. a3 Na6 15. b4 Bg4 $11 ) 10... e5 11. dxe5 dxe5 12. e4 f4 13. c5 ( 13. gxf4 Nh5 14. fxe5 Nf4 15. Kh1 Bg4 16. Ng1 Rad8 $19 { Rodriguez Alvarez,V (2224) -Gonzalez Acosta,B (2467) Barcelona Sants op 19th 2017 (2) 0-1 } ) 13... Ng4 $15 14. Rad1 Be6 15. Qc3 Rad8 16. b4 Nd4 $17 { Duzhakov,I (2316) -Halkias,S (2588) EU-ch 13th Plovdiv 2012 (2) 0-1 } ) ( 9. Nc3 { transposes to Line 8 } ) 9... exd5 10. cxd5 Ne7 { In principle, this structure favours White, but the problem is that he is a bit behind in development. He needs to choose a way of defending d5. } 11. Ng5 ( { The generally desirable } 11. Nc3 { unfortunately loses a pawn to } 11... Nfxd5 $1 ) ( 11. Ne1 g5 { Starting a consistent positional kingside attack. } ( 11... f4 $5 { , clearing the f5-square for the e7-knight is also worth trying. } 12. gxf4 Nf5 13. Nf3 Ne7 14. Ng5 Nf5 15. Nf3 Ne7 16. e3 Nexd5 $13 ) ( 11... c6 12. dxc6 bxc6 13. Nd2 Ba6 14. Rc1 Rc8 15. Nc4 d5 16. Ne5 Ng4 17. N1f3 Qd6 18. Nc4 Bxc4 19. Bxg7 Bxe2 20. Qxe2 Kxg7 { Gumula,D (2150) -Kuziola,M (2100) POL-chT U19 2nd League 2001 (9) 1/2-1/2 } ) 12. Nc3 Qe8 13. Qd2 ( 13. Rc1 Bd7 14. Qd2 Qg6 15. e3 Rae8 $13 ) 13... f4 ( 13... Qg6 14. Nb5 $16 ) 14. Rc1 Bd7 15. gxf4 gxf4 16. Ne4 ( 16. Qxf4 Qh5 { yields Black dangerous initiative. } ) 16... Nxe4 17. Bxe4 Bxb2 18. Qxb2 Bh3 19. Ng2 Rf7 20. Rc3 ( 20. Qc3 Nf5 21. Bxf5 Bxf5 22. Nxf4 Qe4 $36 23. Nh5 Qxe2 24. Nf6+ Rxf6 $5 25. Qxf6 Qg4+ 26. Kh1 Qf3+ $11 ) 20... Bxg2 ( 20... Nf5 21. Bxf5 Bxf5 22. Nxf4 $18 ) 21. Kxg2 Ng6 $11 ) 11... h6 12. Nh3 Bd7 $14 { Continuing to develop and waiting for White to define his intentions. } ( 12... g5 { is premature. } 13. f4 g4 14. Nf2 h5 15. Na3 h4 16. Rc1 hxg3 17. hxg3 Bd7 18. Nc4 $14 { Aura,K (1974) -Alho,S (2074) FIN-chT 1718 2017 (6.8) 1/2-1/2 } ) 13. Na3 ( 13. Nc3 { allows } 13... g5 { when } 14. f4 { can be met with } 14... Ng6 15. Qd2 ( 15. fxg5 Ng4 { One important detail is that White does not have Bxg7 followed by gxh6+. } 16. gxh6 Bxh6 $44 ) 15... Ng4 16. Nd1 Bxb2 17. Qxb2 c5 18. dxc6 Qb6+ 19. Kh1 Bxc6 20. fxg5 hxg5 21. Nxg5 Bxg2+ 22. Kxg2 Rae8 $44 { Black is better mobilised, and has excellent play against White's weaknesses. These elements ensure him adequate compensation for the pawn. } ) 13... c5 $5 { With the white knight far from d5, this is a sound decision. } ( 13... g5 14. f4 Ng6 15. fxg5 Ng4 16. Bxg7 Kxg7 17. gxh6+ $18 ) 14. Nc4 ( 14. dxc6 Bxc6 15. Nf4 Qd7 16. Rb1 { Preparing Bxf6. By placing the rook on c1, White would expose himself to a later double attack with ...Bb2. } 16... g5 17. Bxf6 Bxf6 18. Nd5 f4 19. gxf4 { Otherwise, Black would enjoy excellent stability on dark squares. } 19... Nxd5 20. Bxd5+ Kh8 { With the white knight from the kingside, Black has consistent initiative. } 21. Bxc6 bxc6 22. fxg5 Be5 23. f3 Rg8 24. Kh1 Rxg5 25. Rf2 d5 26. f4 Rf8 $13 ) 14... b5 $1 15. Nxd6 $1 Qb6 16. e4 $1 { Otherwise, White loses material. } 16... fxe4 17. Nxe4 Nxe4 18. Bxg7 Kxg7 19. Re1 $1 { The point behind White's previous play. He will win a pawn, but the knight on h3 will remain a problem. } 19... g5 20. Rxe4 Rae8 21. Qd2 Ng6 $44 { Black is well regrouped and has a mobile queenside majority. White will face problems activating his knight. } *
