1. d4 e6 2. Nf3 f5 3. g3 Nf6 4. Bg2 g6 5. O-O Bg7 6. c4 O-O 7. b4 { This move has the same plusses and minuses as 6.b4 in Line 3. White tries to combine the ideas behind b2-b3 with a massive space gain. On the other hand, the pawn on b4 may be vulnerable in the early phase. } 7... Ne4 { Deviating from the plan recommended against 7.b3 in the previous line, since this would simply yield White an extra tempo for his queenside attack. The last move prepares ... b7-b6. } 8. Bb2 ( { The point is that } 8. Nbd2 { , recommended after 7.b3 Ne4, runs into } 8... Nc6 { with a double attack. } ) 8... b6 9. Nbd2 ( 9. Ne5 d6 10. Nd3 Bb7 11. Qb3 { Johansson,V (2167) -Dalmau,A (2090) Nordic-ch (Women) 2003 (3) 1-0 } 11... a5 { The typical reaction with the white pawn on b4. } ( 11... Nd7 $5 ) 12. b5 ( 12. a3 Nd7 $11 ) 12... a4 { Gaining queenside space and creating the potential threat .. .a4-a3. True, the pawn may also become vulnerable. } 13. Qc2 Qe7 14. e3 c5 { Not leaving White the time for consolidating in order to attack the daring pawn on a4. } 15. dxc5 ( 15. bxc6 Nxc6 16. Nd2 Na5 $11 ) 15... dxc5 16. a3 Bxb2 17. Qxb2 Rd8 18. Ne5 Qg7 19. Ra2 Nd7 20. Nc6 Bxc6 21. bxc6 Ne5 22. Bxe4 ( 22. Qxb6 $2 Rdb8 $19 ) ( 22. Qc2 Nxc6 23. Bxe4 fxe4 24. Qxe4 Na5 25. Nd2 Qf6 { [%cal Ga8a7,Ga7d7] followed by ...Ra7-d7, if allowed. } ) 22... fxe4 23. Qxb6 Rac8 24. Qxc5 Rxc6 25. Qa5 Nf3+ 26. Kg2 Rcd6 $44 ) ( 9. Nc3 Bb7 10. Rc1 Qe7 11. a3 a5 12. b5 { The position is only partly blocked. White can organize c4-c5, but Black will be in time with his counterplay. } 12... d6 13. Nxe4 Bxe4 14. a4 Nd7 15. Ba3 Rad8 16. e3 e5 17. Qb3 Kh8 18. c5 bxc5 19. dxc5 Nxc5 20. Bxc5 dxc5 21. Ne1 Bxg2 22. Nxg2 f4 23. exf4 Rd4 $13 ) 9... Bb7 10. Qc2 Qe7 $14 { One of the moments when the pawn is exposed on b4. When playing the game quoted in the next comment, I remembered that I had analyzed this move, but for some reason, decided to improvise. } ( 10... Nxd2 11. Qxd2 d6 ( 11... Qe7 12. Rfd1 a5 $6 13. b5 Be4 $6 14. Rac1 a4 $5 15. d5 $1 Bxb2 16. Qxb2 $18 { Vogel,R (2471) -Marin,M (2437) UKA Invitational Uhlmann 2023 (4.2) 1/2-1/2 } ) 12. d5 Bxb2 13. Qxb2 e5 14. Qd2 f4 { Cheparinov,I (2189) -De la Riva Aguado,O (2462) Montpellier op 7th 2000 (2) 0-1 } 15. e3 g5 16. Bh3 $16 ) 11. a3 ( 11. a4 { does not prevent } 11... Qxb4 $1 12. Ba3 Qc3 $15 13. Qxc3 Nxc3 14. Bxf8 Nxe2+ 15. Kh1 Kxf8 16. Nb3 Nc6 $19 ) ( 11. Ne1 Qxb4 ( 11... Nc6 12. Nxe4 Nxb4 13. Qb1 Bxe4 14. Bxe4 fxe4 15. Qxe4 c5 16. Nf3 Rac8 $11 ) 12. Nxe4 Bxe4 13. Bxe4 fxe4 14. a3 Qa5 15. Qxe4 Nc6 16. Nd3 Qf5 $11 ) 11... Nxd2 12. Qxd2 d6 ( 12... Be4 { is likely to waste a tempo, but is playable anyway. } 13. Ne1 Bxg2 14. Nxg2 d6 15. c5 Nd7 16. Nf4 Nf6 17. d5 Nxd5 18. Nxd5 exd5 19. Qxd5+ Qf7 20. Qxf7+ Rxf7 21. Bxg7 Kxg7 22. cxd6 cxd6 { The endgame is less bad than it looks. Black should hold a draw. } 23. Rfd1 Rd7 24. Rac1 Re8 25. e3 d5 26. h4 Kf6 27. Kg2 Ke5 28. Rc6 Re6 29. Rc8 Ree7 30. h5 Kf6 $11 ) 13. d5 ( 13. Ne1 Bxg2 14. Nxg2 Nd7 { yields Black an extra tempo with respect to the similar line above. } 15. Rae1 Nf6 16. f3 e5 17. d5 a5 18. b5 Qd7 ( 18... Rf7 $17 { [%cal Ga8f8] } ) 19. e4 fxe4 20. fxe4 Qh3 21. Qg5 Bh6 22. Qh4 Qxh4 23. Nxh4 Ng4 $17 { Cuenca Jimenez,J (2541) -Vallejo Pons,F (2713) ESP-ch rapid 2016 (3) 0-1 } ) 13... Bxb2 14. Qxb2 e5 15. Qd2 Nd7 16. Ng5 { The typical idea of the intrusion to e6. } 16... Nf6 17. Ne6 Rfe8 { [%cal Gb7c8] Threatening ... Bc8. } 18. f4 { White needs to free his knight. } 18... e4 19. Nd4 Bc8 20. e3 Bd7 21. Rfc1 a5 22. Bf1 { White has some space advantage, but Black is well regrouped and should not have any problems. } 22... Ra7 $5 { The start of a manoeuvre used by Petrosian in a game against Karpov. } 23. Be2 ( 23. c5 bxc5 24. bxc5 dxc5 25. Nb3 Rd8 26. Bc4 Kg7 27. Qc3 ( 27. Nxa5 Rda8 ) 27... a4 28. Na5 Rb8 $11 ) 23... Rea8 24. Qb2 ( 24. b5 Kf7 25. h3 h5 26. Kf2 Rg8 27. Rg1 Raa8 28. Raf1 Rg7 29. Ke1 Rag8 $11 { [%cal Gg6g5] The threat ...g6-g5 offers Black enough play. If White blocks with h3-h4 at any time it is an obvious draw. } ) 24... Qg7 25. Kh1 h6 26. Rg1 Kh7 $11 *
