1. d4 e6 2. Nf3 f5 3. g3 Nf6 4. Bg2 g6 5. O-O Bg7 6. c4 O-O 7. Nc3 { This is the classical main tabiya. If the game starts with the usual Leningrad Dutch move order, Black's next move will be 7...e6, transposing. } 7... d6 8. b4 { We are familiar with the ideas behind this resolute pawn advance. In this position, Black does not have the plan based on the queen's fianchetto anymore, so he should react at once in order to avoid falling into a passive position. } ( 8. Rb1 { prepares b2-b4 under improved circumstances, but offers Black a free tempo. } 8... a5 $5 9. a3 Qe8 10. Re1 ( 10. b4 { De Verdier,M (2225) -Knudsen,J (1980) Copenhagen Challenge 2008 (8) 1-0 } 10... axb4 11. axb4 e5 $11 ) 10... e5 11. e4 Nc6 12. dxe5 dxe5 13. Nd5 fxe4 14. Nxf6+ ( 14. Nxc7 Qf7 15. Nxa8 exf3 16. Bxf3 Bf5 ) 14... Bxf6 15. Ng5 Bxg5 16. Bxg5 Qf7 17. Qd5 Be6 18. Qc5 Nd4 19. Qxe5 Qxf2+ 20. Kh1 Rf5 21. Qxe4 Rxg5 22. Rf1 Qc2 23. Qxd4 Qxc4 $11 ) ( 8. Bg5 { allows White to reveal one of the merits behind ...e7-e6. } 8... h6 9. Bxf6 Qxf6 { Not available in other systems. } 10. e4 Nc6 ( 10... fxe4 11. Nxe4 Qf7 12. Qd2 Nc6 { followed by either ...e6-e5 or ...Ne7-f5 looks also playable. } ) 11. exf5 { The critical continuation. } ( 11. d5 Ne5 { is completely fine for Black. The pawn on c4 is hanging now. } 12. Nxe5 Qxe5 13. exf5 exf5 14. Re1 Qf6 15. Nb5 Rf7 16. Re8+ Kh7 17. Qd2 a6 18. Nc3 Rf8 19. Rae1 Bd7 20. R8e7 Rad8 21. h4 Rfe8 $15 { Li,C (2687) -Nepomniachtchi,I (2718) RUS-CHN Summit 8th Rapid 2012 (6) 1/2-1/2 } ) 11... gxf5 ( 11... exf5 $6 12. Nd5 Qf7 13. Re1 { causes Black problems with his development. } 13... Kh7 14. b4 Be6 15. Nxc7 Qxc7 16. Rxe6 Nd8 17. Re2 Qxc4 18. Rc1 Qxb4 19. Re7 $16 { Czerwonski,A (2414) -Malaniuk,V (2570) Rowy Jantar op 2000 (3) 1/2-1/2 } ) 12. d5 { Dorfman, J (2580) -Meulders,R (2330) Brussels zt 1993 (1) 1-0 } ( 12. Nb5 Rf7 13. d5 Ne5 14. Nxe5 dxe5 15. d6 cxd6 16. Nxd6 Rf8 { is unclear, but fine for Black. } ) 12... Nd4 13. Nxd4 Qxd4 14. Rc1 $5 { Overdefending c3, in order to avoid having double pawns. } ( 14. dxe6 Bxe6 15. Bxb7 Rab8 16. Bd5 Bxd5 17. Nxd5 Rxb2 $11 ) ( 14. Qxd4 Bxd4 15. Nb5 Bb6 $11 ) 14... Qxd1 15. Rfxd1 e5 16. c5 { Black has the means for neutralizing White's initiative. } 16... Rf7 17. cxd6 cxd6 18. Nb5 Bf8 19. Nc7 Rb8 20. Ne6 Bd7 21. Rc4 ( 21. Rc7 $2 Bxe6 $19 ) 21... Kh7 22. Rdc1 Kg6 23. Rc7 Bg7 $11 ) ( 8. Qb3 { is examined in Line 7. } ) ( 8. b3 { is the subject of Lines 8 to 10. } ) ( { For } 8. Qc2 { , see Lines 11 to 15. } ) ( 8. Re1 { is the most challenging continuation and is examined in Lines 16 to 18. } ) 8... e5 $1 { This is the way of taking advantage of the nuances induced by White's previous move. After 8. b3, the same plan would not work so well, because White could gain a tempo with 10.Ba3 after the exchange on e5. } 9. dxe5 dxe5 10. Qxd8 { The most challenging move order. White forces the rook to move on a vulnerable square. } ( 10. Nxe5 Qxd1 11. Nxd1 ( 11. Rxd1 $2 Ne4 12. Nxe4 Bxe5 $19 ) 11... Ng4 12. f4 Nxe5 13. fxe5 Nd7 $11 ) 10... Rxd8 11. Nxe5 { Otherwise, Black would be just fine. } ( 11. e4 Nc6 12. b5 Nd4 $11 13. Nxe5 $2 Nxe4 $19 ) 11... Ne4 12. Nxe4 fxe4 ( { The idea behind the queen exchange is that } 12... Bxe5 $2 { runs into } 13. Bg5 $18 ) 13. Bb2 ( 13. f4 exf3 14. Nxf3 Bxa1 15. Bg5 Bd4+ 16. e3 Bxe3+ 17. Bxe3 Be6 18. Bg5 Nc6 19. Bxd8 Rxd8 $11 ) 13... Re8 14. Rad1 $1 { Completing the development and defending the knight indirectly. } ( 14. Rfd1 $6 { is worse, because in a line below the rook is useful on f1. } 14... Kf8 $1 15. Bxe4 Bxe5 16. Bxe5 Rxe5 17. Rd8+ Re8 18. Rxc8 Rxc8 19. Bxb7 Nd7 20. Rd1 Ke7 $15 ) ( 14. f4 { does not cause Black any special problems. } 14... exf3 15. Rxf3 Nc6 ( 15... Bxe5 $5 16. Re3 Nd7 17. Rd1 Re7 18. Bh3 Kf7 19. Rf1+ Bf6 20. Ref3 Kg8 21. Bxf6 Nxf6 22. Bxc8 Rxc8 23. Rxf6 Rxe2 $11 ) 16. Nd3 Bxb2 17. Nxb2 Nxb4 $11 ) 14... Na6 { Attacking b4 and reinforcing the threat ...Bxe5. Play becomes very concrete now. } ( 14... Bxe5 $2 15. Bxe5 Rxe5 16. Rd8+ Kf7 17. Rxc8 $18 ) ( 14... Kf8 $2 { does not work with the rook on f1. } 15. f4 $18 ) 15. b5 ( 15. a3 Bxe5 $19 { After } 16. Bxe5 Rxe5 17. Rd8+ Kf7 { the bishop on c8 is defended. } ) 15... Nc5 { The knight on e5 is in danger, but White can maintain some temporary initiative. One of Black's important ideas on the way to complete the development is ...a7-a6.White } 16. f4 { Bringing the last reserves into play. White has several alternatives leading to interesting play but not to an advantage. } ( 16. Rd5 Na4 17. Ba1 ( 17. Bd4 Nb6 18. Bxb6 axb6 19. Nd7 Rxa2 $15 ) 17... Nb6 18. Bxe4 ( 18. Rd4 Rxe5 19. Rd8+ Kf7 20. Bxe5 Bxe5 21. Bxe4 Ke7 22. Rg8 Kf7 23. Rd8 Ke7 24. Rfd1 Nxc4 25. Rg8 Nd6 $15 ) ( 18. Rc5 Na4 { leads to a repetition. } ) 18... Nxd5 19. Bxd5+ Be6 20. f4 { White maintains an active position and has two pawns for the exchange. His second rank is a bit weak, though and Blacki has at least two ways of activating his rooks. } ( 20. Bxb7 Rad8 21. f4 Rd2 $11 ) 20... c6 ( 20... Bxd5 21. cxd5 b6 22. Rc1 a6 $13 ) 21. bxc6 Bxd5 22. cxd5 bxc6 23. dxc6 Rac8 24. Rd1 ( 24. Rc1 Re6 $11 ) 24... Bxe5 25. Bxe5 Rxc6 26. Rd7 h5 27. Rxa7 Ree6 28. Kf2 Ra6 29. Rb7 Rxa2 30. Kf3 Rea6 $11 { The kingside is safe and the black rooks are active. White's advantage is purely optical. } ) ( 16. Bd4 $6 Rxe5 $1 17. Bxe5 Bxe5 18. Rd8+ Kf7 19. Bh3 ( 19. f3 Ke7 20. Rg8 b6 $19 ) 19... Bxh3 20. Rxa8 Bxf1 21. Kxf1 a6 $15 { As announced. } ) ( 16. Ba3 $5 Rxe5 17. f4 exf3 18. Rd8+ Kf7 19. Bxf3 ( 19. Rxf3+ Bf6 20. Rh8 Kg7 21. Rxf6 Kxf6 22. Bb2 Na4 23. Ba1 Nb6 24. c5 Be6 $15 ) 19... Ke7 20. Rfd1 Kf7 { Unpinning the knight } 21. Rf1 Ke7 22. Rd5 Rxd5 23. Bxd5 Bd4+ 24. Kg2 a6 25. Rd1 axb5 26. Bb4 Rxa2 27. Rxd4 b6 $11 ) 16... exf3 17. Rxf3 a6 $1 { The only move yielding Black adequate play. } ( 17... Bxe5 $2 18. Re3 Nd7 19. Bd5+ $40 ) 18. Ra3 $5 ( 18. Re3 axb5 19. cxb5 Be6 20. Nd3 Bxb2 21. Nxc5 Bc4 $11 { Schleef, H-Probstfeld,B Blitz-22069-G2 2020 1/2-1/2 } ) ( 18. b6 cxb6 19. Re3 Be6 $11 ) 18... Bxe5 $1 { With the pawn on a6 already, this move is good. } 19. Re3 Nd7 20. Bd5+ Kf8 ( 20... Kg7 $2 21. Bxb7 Bxb7 22. Rxd7+ $16 ) 21. Rf1+ Kg7 22. Rf7+ Kh6 23. g4 { The most constructive way of continuing the attack. } 23... Bxb2 ( 23... axb5 $2 { is premature. } 24. Rh3+ Kg5 25. Bc1+ ) 24. Rxe8 Nf6 25. Rh8 axb5 ( 25... Nxd5 26. Rhxh7+ Kg5 27. cxd5 { With the pawn on a7, this would be bad for Black, but here he has: } 27... axb5 $13 28. Rf8 $6 Ba3 29. Rg8 Bd6 $15 30. Rhh8 $2 Rxa2 $19 ) 26. h4 g5 27. Rxc7 Rxa2 28. Rhxc8 Bd4+ 29. Kf1 ( 29. Kg2 Rxe2+ ) 29... gxh4 $11 *
