1. d4 e6 2. Nf3 f5 3. g3 Nf6 4. Bg2 g6 5. O-O Bg7 6. c4 O-O 7. Nc3 d6 8. Qb3 { This slightly exotic way of developing the queen was successfully used by Kortschnoj in a series of games featuring other Leningrad Dutch systems. White puts pressure on b7 and prepares a discovered check with c4-c5+ if Black advances his e-pawn. I must admit that I am a bit puzzled by this move, but since it develops a piece, it cannot be that bad. } 8... Nc6 { Taking advantage of the queen's exposure in a different way than in the later lines with 8.Qc2. } 9. Rd1 { Preventing ...e6-e5. } ( 9. d5 { runs into } 9... Na5 { True, this is only the start of interesting complications. } 10. Qa4 ( 10. Qb4 $6 c5 $1 11. dxc6 { Otherwise ...e6-e5. } 11... bxc6 $15 { The White queen is misplaced and c4 is hanging a bit.. } ) 10... b6 { A slightly unusual queenside structure. } ( 10... c5 $6 { Kobryn,T (1986) -Blittkowsky,R W-ch WS/O/351 email 2010 0-1 } 11. dxe6 Bxe6 12. Ng5 $16 ) 11. b4 $1 ( 11. dxe6 Bxe6 12. Nd4 Bd7 13. Qc2 c5 $1 { An interesting exchange sacrifice. } 14. Bxa8 { Otherwise, ...Bc6. } 14... cxd4 15. Bd5+ $1 { Obviously the only move. } 15... Kh8 16. Nb1 Nxd5 17. cxd5 Qa8 $44 { After taking on d5, Black will have obvious compensation. } ) ( 11. Ng5 e5 12. e4 f4 $13 13. gxf4 exf4 14. Bxf4 Ng4 15. Nh3 Ne5 $15 ) 11... Ne4 $1 { The tension is increasing with every move. } ( 11... Nxc4 $2 12. Qc6 Ba6 13. Ng5 $16 ) 12. Nxe4 fxe4 13. Bg5 Qd7 14. Qxd7 Bxd7 15. Nd2 Bxa1 16. Rxa1 Nb7 17. dxe6 Bxe6 18. Nxe4 { White has good compensation for the exchange, but Black can maintain approximate equality. } 18... Rab8 19. Bh6 ( 19. Rc1 Kg7 20. Bd2 h6 21. Bc3+ Kf7 $13 ) 19... c5 $5 { Turning c4 into a permanent weakness. } 20. Bxf8 Kxf8 21. bxc5 Nxc5 22. Nxd6 Rd8 23. Ne4 Nxe4 24. Bxe4 Bxc4 25. e3 b5 $44 { The queenside majority and the control over the d-file ensures Black full compensation for the pawn. } ) 9... Qe8 { Not only reiterating the positional threat in the centre but also putting an eye on b5 and a4. If given a tempo for free, Black might also consider ...Ne4. } ( 9... Ne4 { is premature, since it allows } 10. Be3 { , without fearing ...Ng4. Black is not ready to open the centre yet. } 10... Nxc3 11. Qxc3 Qe7 { Martins,D (2427) -Rodriguez Amezqueta,C (2063) ESP-chT CECLUB Div1 2019 (2.3) 1-0 } 12. b4 $14 ) 10. a4 ( 10. d5 Na5 { reveals one of the ideas behind ...Qe8, since Qa4 is not working now. } ( 10... Nd8 11. dxe6 Nxe6 { is also possible. } ) 11. Qc2 ( 11. Qb5 Qxb5 12. Nxb5 Ne8 13. Na3 e5 14. b4 e4 15. Nd4 c5 16. dxc6 Nxc6 $11 ) 11... Nxc4 12. dxe6 Bxe6 13. Ng5 c6 14. b3 Nb6 15. Rxd6 Bd5 { Black has stabilised and White's initiative is temporary. } 16. Ba3 Qe7 17. Qc1 { Defending the bishop. } 17... Bxg2 18. Kxg2 c5 $1 { Provoking the opening of the c-file. } 19. Bxc5 Rfc8 20. b4 Nfd7 21. Re6 Qd8 $11 { with mutual chances. } ) 10... h6 $5 { Still preparing ...e6-e5, by preventing a later Ng5. } ( 10... Ne4 11. a5 $16 { yields White annoying space advantage. } 11... Nxc3 12. bxc3 e5 13. c5+ Kh8 ( 13... Qf7 14. Qxf7+ Rxf7 15. Ng5 Re7 16. Bd5+ $18 ) 14. cxd6 cxd6 15. Ba3 e4 16. Bxd6 exf3 17. Bxf8 Bxf8 18. Bxf3 $16 ) ( 10... a5 11. Bd2 ( 11. Nb5 Qe7 12. Be3 ) 11... Qe7 12. d5 Nd8 13. Ng5 e5 14. c5 { Carnevale,R (2279) -Pereverzev,R (2322) WS MN/056 email 2010 0-1 } 14... h6 ) ( 10... e5 $2 11. dxe5 dxe5 12. Nd5 Rf7 13. Ng5 $16 Rd7 14. Nxf6+ Bxf6 15. Rxd7 Bxd7 16. Bd5+ Kg7 17. Nf7 Be6 18. Nd6 $16 Qb8 ( 18... cxd6 19. Qxb7+ $18 ) 19. Bxe6 cxd6 20. Bd5 $16 ) 11. a5 e5 12. c5+ ( 12. d5 Nd8 13. e4 fxe4 14. Nd2 e3 15. fxe3 Nf7 $11 ) 12... Qf7 13. Qxf7+ Rxf7 $11 *
