1. d4 e6 2. Nf3 f5 3. g3 Nf6 4. Bg2 g6 5. O-O Bg7 6. c4 O-O 7. Nc3 d6 8. b3 { A flexible move, aiming at completing the development harmoniously. } 8... Nc6 { In view of the relative weakness of the long diagonal, now is a good moment to develop the knight on this square, preparing ...e6-e5. } 9. Bb2 ( 9. Qc2 { transposes to Line 14. } ) ( 9. d5 $2 { runs into } 9... Ne4 ) ( 9. Ba3 { is examined in Line 9. } ) 9... e5 { There is no contraindication to this planned move. } 10. dxe5 ( 10. d5 { Does not make much sense after developing the bishop to b3. } 10... Ne7 11. e4 f4 $5 ( 11... Nxe4 12. Nxe4 fxe4 13. Nd2 e3 14. fxe3 Nf5 $11 ) 12. gxf4 $6 Nh5 $1 { The typical pawn sacrifice, ensuring Black the control over f4. } 13. fxe5 Bg4 14. h3 ( 14. e6 Nf4 $17 ) 14... Bxf3 15. Bxf3 Nf4 16. Bg2 ( 16. e6 Nexd5 17. Nxd5 Nxh3+ 18. Kg2 Nf4+ 19. Nxf4 Qg5+ 20. Bg4 Rxf4 21. f3 Bxb2 $19 ) 16... Bxe5 $17 { It is inspiring, I believe, to follow the game without further annotations. } 17. Na4 Bxb2 18. Nxb2 g5 19. Nd3 Neg6 20. Nxf4 Rxf4 21. Qd4 Ne5 22. Rad1 Qe7 23. Rc1 Qg7 24. Qe3 Raf8 25. f3 b6 26. b4 Qh6 27. Rc3 Qf6 28. Rfc1 Rf7 29. Ra3 h5 30. c5 g4 31. fxg4 hxg4 32. cxd6 cxd6 33. Rc8+ Kh7 34. hxg4 Rf1+ { Gralka,J (2287) -Jakubiec,A (2542) POL-chT 2st League 2010 (5.13) 0-1 } ) 10... dxe5 11. Qxd8 ( 11. Nd5 e4 { is comfortable for Black. } 12. Nxf6+ Bxf6 13. Qxd8 ( 13. Bxf6 $2 Qxd1 $1 14. Rfxd1 exf3 $19 ) 13... Bxd8 ( 13... Nxd8 14. Bxf6 Rxf6 15. Ne5 Nf7 16. Nxf7 Rxf7 17. Rad1 { Szromba-Kuziola, Polanica Zdroj 2001/EXT 2002 } 17... Bd7 18. f3 exf3 19. exf3 Bc6 $11 ) 14. Nd4 { Boeykens-Vanderwaeren, Belgium 1995/EXT 2001 } 14... Bf6 $11 ) ( 11. e4 { is examined in the next line. } ) 11... Rxd8 12. Rfd1 { This line is aimed to underline Black's slight delay in development. } ( 12. e4 { is very similar to the main game. } 12... Nxe4 13. Nxe4 fxe4 14. Ng5 Nd4 15. Nxe4 c6 16. h3 a5 $1 { Black is stable in the centre  and can start to challenge White on the queenside. } 17. Rfd1 a4 18. Kh1 axb3 19. axb3 Bf5 20. b4 Rxa1 21. Bxa1 b6 22. Bc3 Be6 23. c5 bxc5 24. bxc5 Bd5 25. Nd6 Bxg2+ 26. Kxg2 Ne6 27. Ba5 Rd7 { 1/2-1/2 Pekarek-Knezevic, Namestovo 1987/EXT 97 } 28. Bb4 Bf8 $11 ) ( 12. Nb5 { is inoffensive if answered adequately. } 12... e4 $1 { This active move solves all Black's problems. } ( 12... Ne8 13. e4 ( 13. Ng5 $6 Bf6 14. Bd5+ Kg7 15. Ne6+ $6 Bxe6 16. Bxe6 e4 $19 { e6 } ) 13... a6 { looks like a small concession because is slightly weakens the b6-square. } 14. Nc3 Nf6 15. Rad1 Rxd1 16. Rxd1 fxe4 17. Ng5 Bg4 18. Re1 Nb4 19. Ngxe4 c6 20. Nxf6+ Bxf6 21. Ne4 { Ramya-Muzychuk, Belfort 2005/CBM 107 ext } 21... Be7 $11 ) 13. Ne5 Nxe5 14. Bxe5 ( 14. Nxc7 Ne8 $1 15. Nxa8 Be6 $15 ) 14... Ne8 15. Bxg7 Kxg7 16. Rad1 Be6 17. f3 exf3 18. exf3 c6 19. Nd4 Nc7 20. Rfe1 Kf6 21. f4 a5 $13 ) 12... e4 ( 12... Rxd1+ { partly justifies White's strategy. } 13. Rxd1 e4 14. Ne1 Be6 15. f3 exf3 $6 ( 15... Re8 $1 16. fxe4 $6 Nxe4 ) 16. exf3 Ne8 17. f4 $14 { Ivkov-Menvielle, Havana 1966/MCD } ) 13. Rxd8+ Nxd8 14. Nd4 Nf7 15. Rd1 Bd7 { Black reaches a very harmonious placement of his pieces. } 16. f3 exf3 17. exf3 c6 18. Kf2 Rd8 19. Nde2 b6 20. h3 Be8 21. Rxd8 Nxd8 22. f4 Ne6 23. Ke3 Kf7 24. Nd1 Bf8 $11 { Meduna-Jakubiec, Czechia 2000/EXT 2001 } *
