1. d4 e6 2. Nf3 f5 3. g3 Nf6 4. Bg2 g6 5. O-O Bg7 6. c4 O-O 7. Nc3 d6 8. b3 Nc6 9. Ba3 Ne4 { The most popular move. } ( { The rare } 9... a5 { is also worth examining. } 10. Rc1 Re8 $14 { Preparing ...e6-e5. } 11. d5 { The most challenging move. } ( 11. Qc2 Nb4 12. Qb1 e5 $11 ) 11... Nb4 12. dxe6 Bxe6 13. Nd4 c6 14. Nxe6 Rxe6 15. Qd2 ( 15. Bb2 d5 $11 16. a3 dxc4 $1 17. axb4 axb4 $44 { In fact, WHite should return the piece here. } 18. Na4 c3 19. Nxc3 bxc3 20. Bxc3 Qxd1 21. Rcxd1 Rxe2 { and it is White's turn to look for compensation for the pawn with } 22. b4 Ra3 23. Bxf6 Bxf6 24. Rd7 Re7 25. Rxe7 Bxe7 26. Rb1 $15 ) 15... Qe7 16. e3 Ng4 $5 { Clearing the long diagonal for the bishop and getting ready for ...Nge5-d3 if the opportunity is given. } ( 16... h5 17. Ne2 $1 { puts the rook in an unpleasant position and after } 17... Bh6 18. Nf4 Bxf4 19. gxf4 $14 { the weakness on g6 may tell. } ) 17. Ne2 ( 17. Bb2 h5 $13 18. a3 Na6 19. Ne2 Bxb2 20. Qxb2 h4 21. Nf4 hxg3 22. hxg3 Rf6 $11 ) 17... Bh6 { Threatening to sac on e3. } 18. Nf4 ( 18. Rc3 Nf6 $11 ) 18... Bxf4 19. gxf4 ( 19. exf4 Re2 20. Qd4 Qf6 $13 ) 19... Kf7 { [%cal Ga8g8] Preparing ...Rg8 followed by ...g6-g5. } 20. Rce1 Rg8 ( 20... Nf6 21. Re2 Ne4 22. Bxe4 fxe4 23. Bxb4 axb4 24. Qxb4 g5 $44 ) 21. Bxb4 axb4 22. Qxb4 g5 23. h3 Nh6 $44 ) 10. Qd3 ( 10. Rc1 Nxc3 11. Rxc3 a5 12. e3 { Georgiadis, N (2525) -Gallagher, J (2441) SUI-chT Switzerland 2019 (3.1) 1-0 } 12... Nb4 13. Qb1 e5 $15 ) ( 10. Nxe4 fxe4 11. Nd2 Bxd4 12. Nxe4 Bxa1 13. Qxa1 Qe7 { yields White just normal compensation for the exchange. } ) 10... Nxc3 11. Qxc3 { Black has concluded the first part of his plan but needs to come up with a continuation. } 11... g5 $5 { One of the two most logical continuations. It is my favourite, since it yields Black fluent play. } ( 11... Nxd4 12. Nxd4 c5 13. e3 $14 ) ( 11... e5 12. dxe5 Nxe5 13. Rad1 $14 ) ( 11... Bd7 12. Rad1 Rf7 13. Qd2 Qe7 14. d5 Nd8 15. Ng5 $16 { Ionov-Zysk, Dortmund 1992/CBM 029 } ) ( 11... a5 $14 { also deserves attention. As we will see, the threat ...Nb4 is real, even when it sacrifices a pawn. } 12. Rad1 ( 12. c5 d5 { stabilizes the position to Black's favour, since the bishop on a3 still requires relocating.. } 13. Rad1 ( 13. Bc1 { does not stop } 13... g5 14. Bxg5 Nxd4 $1 15. Qe3 Nxf3+ 16. exf3 Qd7 17. Bf4 Re8 18. Be5 Bxe5 19. Qxe5 Qg7 20. f4 Qxe5 21. fxe5 Bd7 { Threatening ...Bb5, after which the black bishop is not "worse" than White's. } 22. a4 { An obvious structural concession. } 22... Reb8 { Followed by ...b7-b6/b5 soon. } ) 13... h6 { Slowly preparing ...g6-g5. } ( 13... g5 { is a bit premature. } 14. Bc1 Bf6 15. Qe3 h6 16. h4 $14 ) 14. Bc1 Kh7 15. a3 Bd7 { WHite does not have a clear plan adn the position is about equal. } 16. h4 ( 16. b4 axb4 17. axb4 Ra4 18. b5 Na7 $15 ) ( 16. Bf4 g5 17. Bc1 b5 $5 18. h4 g4 19. Ne1 e5 $13 ) 16... Bf6 17. Kh2 ( 17. Qe3 Bg7 $11 ) 17... g5 18. Qe3 Kg6 19. Rh1 Rh8 20. Kg1 Qe7 $11 ) 12... Nb4 13. Rd2 ( 13. Qd2 Qe7 14. Ne1 Ra7 15. f4 b6 16. e3 Rd8 17. Rf2 c5 18. Bb2 Bb7 ) 13... Qe7 14. Bxb4 axb4 15. Qxb4 c5 { Black has excellent compensation for the pawn. For instance: } 16. Qc3 ( 16. dxc5 dxc5 17. Qb5 Qc7 { threatening ...Ra5. } 18. b4 Bc3 $17 ) 16... g5 17. Qc2 e5 18. dxc5 dxc5 19. e4 f4 20. Rfd1 Bf6 21. Ne1 g4 22. a4 f3 23. Bf1 h5 24. h4 Ra6 25. Qc3 Bxh4 26. gxh4 Rg6 $44 ) 12. e3 ( 12. Rad1 g4 13. Ne1 ( 13. Nh4 { places the knight on a passive square, allowing. } 13... Nxd4 14. Rxd4 c5 15. Bxc5 dxc5 16. Rxd8 Bxc3 17. Rd3 Bf6 18. Rfd1 Rb8 19. h3 gxh3 20. Bxh3 b5 21. cxb5 Rxb5 $11 ) 13... Qg5 ( 13... Nxd4 $2 { does not work with the white knight close to the centre. } 14. Rxd4 c5 15. Bxc5 dxc5 16. Rxd8 Bxc3 17. Rxf8+ Kxf8 18. Nd3 Bb4 19. f3 $16 ) 14. c5 d5 15. Bc1 Qh5 16. b4 Bd7 17. Be3 ( 17. b5 Nd8 18. a4 a6 $11 ) 17... Ne7 18. Rd2 Bb5 19. Qa1 a5 20. bxa5 Rxa5 $11 { Maciaga,M (2134) -Lach,P (2105) POL-chT 2nd League 2014 (4.57) 1-0 } ) 12... g4 ( 12... f4 $2 { Behm,S (2225) -Kuziola,M (2296) Pardubice op-A 2005 (4) 1/2-1/2 runs into } 13. exf4 g4 14. Nh4 { and it appears that the pawn on d4 is not so important already, while the knight on h4 sustains f4-f5. } 14... Bxd4 ( 14... Nxd4 15. Qd2 $16 ) 15. Qd2 $16 Qf6 ( 15... Bxa1 $6 16. Rxa1 $18 ) 16. Rad1 Qg7 ( 16... Bd7 17. Bxc6 Bc3 18. Qxc3 Qxc3 19. Bxd7 $18 ) ( 16... Bc3 17. Qe3 Bd7 18. Rd3 $18 ) 17. f5 $16 Bf6 ( 17... exf5 18. Bxc6 Bc3 19. Qd5+ $18 ) ( 17... Bc3 18. Qe3 exf5 19. c5 $40 ) 18. c5 $16 ) 13. Ne1 { The knight is heading for the blockading square on f4. } ( { Against } 13. Nh4 { , Black should choose a slow plan. } 13... Bf6 14. Bb2 Qe7 ( 14... Bxh4 15. gxh4 Qxh4 16. d5 Ne5 17. c5 $16 ) 15. f3 ( 15. h3 gxh3 16. Bxh3 Bxh4 17. gxh4 Kf7 $17 ) 15... Bd7 16. fxg4 fxg4 17. Qd2 Rae8 18. Rae1 Qg7 19. Rf4 Re7 20. Ref1 Ref7 21. Qd1 h5 $11 ) ( 13. Nd2 { is passive in a different way. } 13... e5 $11 14. dxe5 Bxe5 ( 14... Nxe5 15. Qc2 $14 ) 15. Qc1 ( 15. Qc2 Bxa1 16. Rxa1 Qe7 { is safe for Black, since his knight will be stable on e5. } ) 15... a5 ( 15... Bxa1 16. Bd5+ Kg7 17. Qxa1+ Kg6 18. c5 $44 ) 16. Bb2 Qf6 $11 { The knight is far from d3 and f4. } ) 13... f4 $1 { With the knight passive and obstructing the rooks' communication, this works. The curious thing is that the knight is not hanging on h4, but gxf4 does not promise much nevertheless. } ( 13... e5 $2 14. dxe5 Bxe5 ( 14... Nxe5 15. Qc2 a5 16. Rd1 $16 ) 15. Qc1 a5 16. Nd3 $16 ) 14. exf4 { Still the most consistent answer. } ( 14. gxf4 { runs into } 14... Qh4 { Threatening ...Rf6-h6. } 15. f3 ( 15. Bb2 Rf6 16. e4 Rh6 17. Qg3 Bxd4 $11 ) 15... Rxf4 $11 ) 14... Bxd4 15. Qc1 { Another passive move, which is forced this time. } 15... Qf6 { No Rd1 available now. } 16. Rb1 e5 $1 { Black is developing quickly now. } 17. Nc2 exf4 { Play becomes very sharp now. } 18. Bd5+ ( 18. Nxd4 Nxd4 $17 ) ( 18. Bxc6 { is less challenging, since White will not be able to create real threats along the long dark diagonal. } 18... bxc6 19. Nxd4 Qxd4 ( 19... fxg3 $5 20. Qd2 gxh2+ 21. Kxh2 Bb7 22. c5 dxc5 23. Ne2 Ba6 24. Rbe1 Qd6+ 25. Qxd6 cxd6 $13 ) 20. Bb2 Qd3 21. Rd1 Qg6 22. c5 ( 22. Qc3 c5 $15 ) 22... d5 23. Re1 ( 23. Qc3 Bf5 24. Rbc1 Rae8 25. Re1 Be4 $19 ) 23... fxg3 24. fxg3 Ba6 { Preventing Rf1, without which White will not have more than one check on h8. } ( 24... Rf3 25. Re7 Ba6 26. Rg7+ Qxg7 27. Bxg7 Rf1+ 28. Qxf1 Bxf1 29. Bh6 Bd3 30. Re1 Kf7 $11 ) 25. Qc3 Rae8 $11 ) 18... Be6 $1 ( 18... Kh8 19. Bxc6 $18 ) 19. Qxf4 $1 Bxd5 20. Qxg4+ Kh8 21. Nxd4 ( 21. cxd5 Ne5 22. Qh5 Nf3+ 23. Kg2 Bc3 $13 ) 21... Ne5 $1 ( 21... Nxd4 22. cxd5 $18 ) 22. Qd1 ( 22. Qh5 Be4 $44 23. Rbe1 Bf3 24. Qh3 c5 $13 ) ( 22. Qe2 Bf3 23. Qd2 c5 $44 ) 22... Bf3 { The simplest continuation from a practical point of view. } ( 22... Be4 { is also good. } 23. Bb2 ( 23. Rc1 Nd3 $17 ) 23... Bd3 24. f4 ( 24. Ne6 Bxf1 25. Nxf8 Bh3 26. Nd7 Bxd7 27. f4 Rf8 28. Bxe5 dxe5 29. Qxd7 exf4 30. Rf1 Rd8 31. Qg4 Qb6+ $11 ) 24... Bxf1 25. Qxf1 Qg6 26. Re1 ( 26. Qe1 Rxf4 ) 26... Kg8 $13 ) 23. Nxf3 ( 23. Qd2 c5 $44 { transposes above. } ) 23... Nxf3+ 24. Kg2 Qg6 25. Bb2+ Kg8 { The strong knight on f3 ensures Black enough compensation for the pawn. The game may end in a perpetual for instance: } 26. Qd5+ Rf7 27. Qxb7 ( 27. Rbd1 Re8 ) 27... Re8 28. Rbd1 Nh4+ 29. Kh1 Nf3 30. Qd5 Qh6 31. h4 Qg6 32. Rd3 Qg4 33. Kg2 Nxh4+ 34. Kh2 Nf3+ 35. Kg2 $11 *
