1. d4 e6 2. g3 f5 3. Bg2 Nf6 4. Nf3 g6 5. O-O Bg7 6. c4 O-O 7. Nc3 d6 8. Qc2 { This flexible move is the most popular and maybe rightly so. It was Tal's reaction in his famous game with Botvinnik. White prepares e2-e4, while avoiding ...Ne4, but exposes his queen a bit which Black immediately can take advantage of. } 8... Nc6 { This is playable mainly because of the queen's exposure. } 9. d5 ( 9. a3 { , preventing ...Nb4, is passive. } 9... e5 10. dxe5 dxe5 11. Rd1 { As usual in such positions, WHite's initiative is transitory but requires certain accuracy from Black. } 11... Qe8 ( 11... Bd7 12. b4 Qe8 13. b5 Nd8 14. e4 fxe4 15. Ng5 $14 ) 12. Nd5 Rf7 13. Ng5 Rd7 14. Nxf6+ Bxf6 { White is not completely developed but can try to use Black's temporary lack of harmony for stirring up interesting complications. } 15. Bd5+ ( { Another possible move order is } 15. Rxd7 Bxd7 16. Bd5+ Kg7 17. Qd2 Nd4 18. Nxh7 Nxe2+ $1 { Deflecting the queen from the attacking trajectory or else exchanging the important bishop on c1. } 19. Qxe2 Kxh7 20. Bxb7 Rd8 { [%cal Ge5e4] Due to his better development and space advantage, Black has entirely adequate compensation for the pawn. } 21. Bd5 Bc6 22. Bxc6 Qxc6 23. Be3 a5 $44 ) 15... Kh8 16. Ne6 Qe7 { Preventing Nc5 as an answer to ...Nd8. } ( 16... Nd4 17. Nxd4 exd4 18. h4 $14 { Kosteniuk,A (2471) -Muzychuk,A (2535) Kosteniuk-Muzychuk Blitz m 2020 (6) 1/2-1/2 } ) 17. Bh6 Nd8 18. Nxd8 Rxd8 19. Bg2 Rxd1+ 20. Rxd1 { Garcia,J (2439) -Gazik,V (2486) Olympiad-43 Batumi 2018 (2.3) 1/2-1/2 } 20... g5 21. b4 c6 $11 { 2023 } ) ( 9. e4 { is examined in Line 13. } ) ( 9. b3 { is the subject of Line 14. } ) ( { For } 9. Rd1 { see Line 15. } ) 9... Nb4 { Without this gain of time on the way of recycling the knight, Black would be worse. } 10. Qd1 ( 10. Qb3 { is examined in the next line. } ) 10... a5 { The safest continuation, fighting for queenside space. } ( 10... e5 { is likely to cause Black some problems with his errant knight, but play is not entirely clear. } 11. a3 Na6 12. b4 { [%cal Ge2e4] Planning e2-e4. } 12... Qe7 ( 12... h6 13. e4 Nxe4 14. Nxe4 fxe4 15. Nd2 e3 16. fxe3 Rxf1+ 17. Qxf1 Nb8 18. Ne4 $14 a5 19. Bd2 axb4 20. axb4 $14 ) 13. e4 f4 14. Ne1 { This allows Black to develop his kingside counterplay. } ( 14. h3 Nh5 15. Kh2 g5 16. g4 Nf6 $13 ) ( 14. Ra2 $5 { followed by Rc2 on the way to prepare c4-c5 is more flexible. The rook move is also useful for avoiding any problem along the long diagonal, for instance } 14... h6 { Preparing ...g6-g5. } 15. gxf4 Bg4 16. h3 Bxf3 17. Qxf3 exf4 18. Qxf4 Nh5 19. Qe3 Nf4 20. Ne2 $16 ) ( 14. gxf4 Bg4 $44 15. h3 Bxf3 16. Qxf3 exf4 17. Qxf4 Nh5 18. Qe3 Nf4 $15 ) 14... g5 15. Nd3 h5 16. f3 Bh6 17. Bd2 Kh7 18. Qe2 Bd7 19. Kh1 Rf7 $13 { Lerner, K (2545) -Knezevic, M (2430) /Moscow 1991. In spite of the relative passivity of the a6-knight, Black has an impressive kingside position. } ) 11. a3 ( 11. dxe6 Bxe6 { helps Black completing his development. } 12. Ng5 ( 12. Qb3 d5 $11 13. cxd5 Bxd5 14. Nxd5 Qxd5 15. Nd4 Qxb3 16. Nxb3 Ne4 $11 ) ( 12. a3 Nc6 ) ( 12. b3 Ne4 13. Nxe4 fxe4 14. Nd4 Qe7 15. Bb2 Bf7 $11 ) ( 12. Nd4 Bxc4 13. Bxb7 Rb8 $11 ) 12... Bxc4 13. b3 Bf7 14. Bxb7 Rb8 15. Bg2 d5 16. Nxf7 Rxf7 17. a3 Ne4 18. Nxe4 fxe4 19. Rb1 Na2 $11 ) ( 11. Ng5 { is prematurely forcing matters, too. } 11... e5 12. e4 Na6 ( 12... h6 13. Ne6 Bxe6 14. dxe6 c6 15. exf5 gxf5 { and now, in the game Tauber, M (2220) -Zysk, R (2440) /Munich 1993/TD White could have played } 16. Bh3 $16 ) 13. exf5 gxf5 14. Ne6 Bxe6 15. dxe6 c6 16. Bh3 Ne8 17. f4 ( 17. Qh5 Qf6 18. e7 Rf7 { [%cal Gf6g6] followed by ...Qg6. } ) 17... e4 18. Be3 Qe7 19. g4 Qxe6 20. Qe2 Qh6 21. Bg2 Bxc3 22. bxc3 Ng7 23. Kh1 Nc5 24. Rg1 Kh8 $13 ) 11... Na6 12. dxe6 { Now is a better moment for releasing the tension, since the knight is more passive and in certain lines, exposed on a6. In the long term, the weakness induced by a2-a3 may count, though. } ( 12. b4 e5 { With the insertion of ...a7-a5 and a2-a3, Black is doing fine on the queenside already and can block the centre. } 13. Rb1 ( 13. e4 fxe4 14. Ng5 Bg4 15. Qb3 axb4 16. axb4 Nc5 $11 ) 13... h6 14. e4 Nxe4 15. Nxe4 fxe4 16. Nd2 e3 17. fxe3 Rxf1+ 18. Qxf1 axb4 19. axb4 Nb8 $11 20. Ne4 Bf5 21. Rb3 Ra1 $11 ) 12... Nc5 ( 12... Bxe6 { runs into } 13. Nd4 Bxc4 14. Bxb7 ( 14. b3 Bf7 15. Bxb7 c5 16. Ndb5 d5 17. Bxa8 Qxa8 $44 ) 14... Nc5 ( 14... c5 15. Ndb5 d5 16. Bxa8 Qxa8 17. Nd6 $18 ) 15. Bxa8 Qxa8 { Black does not seem to have real compensation for the exchange. } ) 13. Ng5 c6 $14 { Implying a pawn sacrifice, this is the most constructive move, putting a brick in the way of the knight on c3 and the bishop on g2. } ( 13... Rb8 { allows White to maintain some static advantage. } 14. Nf7 Qe7 15. Nd5 Qxe6 16. Ng5 Qd7 17. b4 Nce4 18. Nxe4 Nxe4 19. Be3 Qf7 20. Bd4 Ra8 21. b5 $14 { Brophy,C (2053) -Blittkowsky,R (2007) P-5044 IECC email 2017 1/ 2-1/2 } ) 14. Nf7 Qe7 15. Qxd6 ( 15. Nxd6 Bxe6 16. Be3 Nfd7 ( 16... b6 $5 17. Bxc6 Rad8 18. Bf4 a4 $44 { is also worth trying. Black is stable, while the knight on d6 is permanently hanging. } ) 17. b4 axb4 18. axb4 Rxa1 19. Qxa1 Qxd6 20. bxc5 Qe7 { The simplest. Both double pawns are hanging now. } ( 20... Nxc5 21. Qa3 b6 22. Rb1 { yields White some light initiative. } ) 21. Rb1 Qf6 ) ( 15. Nh6+ Kh8 16. Nf7+ { unfortunately forces a draw by perpetual, but from the opening's point of view, this is not a problem. } ) 15... Qxe6 $1 ( 15... Qxd6 16. Nxd6 Bxe6 17. Be3 $14 ) 16. Nh6+ ( 16. Qxe6 Bxe6 { reveals White's structural problems. The pawn on c4 is not easy to defend. } 17. Nd6 Rfd8 18. Bf4 ( 18. Be3 Rxd6 19. Bxc5 Rdd8 20. Bb6 Re8 $11 21. c5 Bb3 22. e3 Nd7 $17 ) 18... Ne8 19. Nxe8 Rxe8 20. Be3 Bf8 21. Bxc5 ( 21. Rac1 Nb3 22. Rc2 Bxc4 $11 23. Ne4 Bxe2 24. Rxe2 fxe4 25. Rd1 Bc5 $11 ) 21... Bxc5 22. Rac1 Bf8 23. Na4 Rad8 $44 ) ( 16. Qxc5 Qxf7 { is similar to the main line, as Black still has the threat ...Nd7, but ...Be6 adds to it now. } ) 16... Bxh6 17. Qxc5 ( 17. Qxe6+ Bxe6 18. Bxh6 Rfe8 $11 19. Bg5 Kf7 20. Rac1 Nb3 21. Rc2 Bxc4 22. Rd1 Rad8 $11 ) 17... Bg7 { White has a free tempo for parrying ...Nd7, but he cannot do much about it. } 18. Rd1 ( 18. Rb1 Nd7 19. Qe3 Qxc4 $15 ) ( 18. Bf4 Nd7 19. Qd6 Nb6 $11 ) ( 18. Na4 Qxe2 19. Nb6 Nd7 20. Nxd7 Bxd7 21. Bf4 Be6 22. Rac1 Bf7 23. b4 Bb2 $13 ) 18... Nd7 ( 18... Re8 $5 { is a clever way of preparing the knight retreat. } 19. Rb1 Nd7 20. Qe3 Qf7 { The point. } 21. Qf4 Be5 22. Qh4 { White is making efforts to keep his extra pawn. } 22... Nc5 23. Be3 Bf6 24. Bg5 Bg7 ( 24... Bxg5 $2 25. Qxg5 $16 Qxc4 $2 26. Nd5 $18 ) 25. Rd2 ( 25. Be3 Bf6 { is just a move repetition. } ) 25... Ne6 26. Be3 Bf6 $11 ) 19. Qe3 Qxc4 ( 19... Ne5 $5 ) 20. Nd5 { The main idea behind Rd1. However, White does not have enough development in order to maintain his initiative. } 20... Nc5 { [%cal Gc8e6] } 21. Bd2 ( 21. Rb1 Be6 22. b4 ( 22. Nc7 Rad8 $17 ) 22... axb4 23. axb4 Ne4 $11 24. Bxe4 ( 24. Nb6 Qc2 $17 ) 24... Qxe4 25. Qxe4 fxe4 26. Nc7 Ba2 27. Nxa8 Rxa8 $11 ) 21... f4 $3 { An essential intermediate move, weakening the white kingside, clearing the path for the c8-bishop and turning the bishop on d2 passive. } ( 21... cxd5 { is premature. } 22. Rac1 d4 23. Qe7 Qe6 24. Qxc5 Qxe2 25. Bf4 $18 { With decisive advance in development. } ) 22. gxf4 ( 22. Nxf4 Nb3 $15 23. Rac1 ( 23. Rab1 Bf5 $19 ) 23... Nxc1 24. Rxc1 Qf7 $15 ) 22... cxd5 23. Rac1 d4 $1 24. Qe7 ( 24. Rxc4 dxe3 { wins a piece. } ) 24... Qe6 25. Qxc5 Qxe2 $11 { The difference with respect to the similar line above without the intermediate ...f5-f4 is obvious. } 26. Bxa5 Rxf4 27. Rd2 Qe8 $11 *
