1. d4 e6 ( { The position after 15 moves in the main line can also be reached via the following move order: } 1... f5 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 g6 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. O-O O-O 6. c4 d6 7. Nc3 c6 8. d5 e5 9. dxe6 Bxe6 10. b3 Na6 11. Bb2 Nc5 12. Qc2 a5 13. Rad1 Qe7 ) 2. g3 f5 3. Bg2 Nf6 4. Nf3 g6 5. O-O Bg7 6. c4 O-O 7. Nc3 d6 8. Qc2 Nc6 9. d5 Nb4 10. Qb3 { This move forces the immediate knight to retreat but exposes the queen for later. White prefers to waste a move with his queen to doing the same with a2-a3, which also weakens the queenside. } 10... Na6 11. dxe6 Nc5 12. Qc2 { Each side has lost two tempi. From a general point of view, Black's placement of pieces is quite favourable. Indeed, the knight stands well on c5 while the queen has defined its intentions slightly prematurely. However, White can be content, too: he has managed to obtain a structure typical for the aforementioned variation 7...c6 8.d5 e5 9. dxe6 Bxe6, preventing the creation of the mobile tandem of e5- and f5-pawns. } 12... Bxe6 ( 12... c6 { looks rather slow and allows White retain the more pleasant position with } 13. Rd1 Qe7 14. Ng5 ( 14. Bf4 Rd8 15. Ng5 Bxe6 16. Nxe6 Qxe6 17. b3 Nfe4 18. Nxe4 Nxe4 19. Rac1 Rd7 20. f3 Nf6 21. Rd3 Rad8 22. Rcd1 d5 $11 { Kosteniuk,A (2471) -Muzychuk,A (2535) Kosteniuk-Muzychuk Blitz m 2020 (2) 1/2-1/ 2 } ) 14... Bxe6 ( 14... Ng4 $5 15. Bf4 Ne5 16. b3 Nxe6 17. Nxe6 Bxe6 18. Qd2 Nf7 19. Rac1 g5 20. Be3 Kh8 $5 ) 15. Bf4 $14 { Jovanic,O (2435) -Kovacevic,B (2510) / Djakovo CRO 2005 } ) 13. b3 { A sound continuation. } ( 13. Ng5 $5 { is more ambitious but not effective. } 13... Bd7 ( 13... Bxc4 14. Na4 b5 15. Nxc5 dxc5 16. a4 $5 Qe7 17. Bxa8 Rxa8 18. axb5 $18 ) 14. b4 ( 14. b3 a5 15. Bb2 Bc6 $5 16. Nd5 Nxd5 17. cxd5 Bxb2 18. Qxb2 Bd7 19. Nf3 Qf6 $11 { White has more space, but the previous minor pieces exchanges have solved Black's problems of coordination. The knight on c5 is strong and the pawn on f5 slows down the advance of the kingside majority. } ) 14... Nce4 15. Ngxe4 Nxe4 16. Bb2 Qf6 17. Rac1 a5 18. a3 axb4 19. axb4 Nxc3 20. Bxc3 Qxc3 21. Qxc3 Bxc3 22. Rxc3 Ra4 23. Rb1 Bc6 $11 { Magalashvili, D (2488) -Sanikidze, T (2533) TUR-chT2 Konya 2016 (9.3) 1/2-1/2 } ) 13... a5 { A solid move, consolidating the knight on c5. } ( { Black should not rush in to exchange pieces, since this could leave his kingside vulnerable. } 13... Nfe4 14. Bb2 Nxc3 15. Bxc3 Bxc3 16. Qxc3 Ne4 17. Qc2 Qe7 { Cvitan,O (2500) -Bjelajac,M (2440) Belgrade GMA op 1988 0-1 } 18. Nd4 Bd7 19. e3 ) 14. Bb2 c6 15. Rad1 Qe7 { We have reached a tabiya mentioned above. White has completed his development and needs to come up with a concrete plan. } 16. e3 { Consolidating the kingside and clearing the e2-square for the knight. } ( { The necessity of doing the former is revealed after a neutral move such as } 16. a3 { preparing b3-b4. } 16... f4 $5 ( 16... Ng4 $5 { and } ) ( 16... Rae8 $5 { are also good. } ) 17. Nd4 { Controlling f5. } ( 17. gxf4 $6 { yields Black strong initiative. } 17... Bf5 18. Qd2 Nxb3 { We can notice the drawbacks of a2-a3. } 19. Qxd6 Qxd6 20. Rxd6 Rfd8 21. Rxd8+ Rxd8 22. Rd1 Rxd1+ 23. Nxd1 Be6 $15 24. Ne3 Ne4 25. Bxg7 Kxg7 26. Kf1 Nc3 $17 ) ( 17. b4 axb4 18. axb4 Bf5 19. Qc1 Ne6 20. gxf4 Nd7 21. e3 Nb6 22. Nd2 Bd3 $11 ) 17... fxg3 18. hxg3 { Krysztofiak,M (2383) -Wcislo,D (2403) POL-chT 1st League 2017 (4.4) 1-0 } 18... Ng4 19. b4 axb4 20. axb4 Qg5 $1 21. Bf3 ( 21. bxc5 Qh5 22. Nf3 Rxf3 $19 ) 21... Qh5 22. Bxg4 Qxg4 23. bxc5 Bxd4 24. Ne4 Bxb2 25. f3 Qh3 26. Qxb2 Bf5 27. Nf6+ Rxf6 28. Qxf6 Qxg3+ $11 ) ( 16. Ng5 Bd7 17. Qd2 { does not force Black to defend d6 passively. } ( 17. Rfe1 { once again allows } 17... f4 $5 18. gxf4 Nh5 19. e3 Bf5 20. Qd2 ( 20. Qe2 Rae8 { Threatening ...Nxf4. } 21. Qf1 h6 22. Nf3 g5 $15 ) 20... h6 21. Nf3 Nd3 22. Rf1 Nxb2 23. Qxb2 g5 24. fxg5 Bg4 $36 ) ( 17. e3 Be8 18. Ne2 Nh5 19. Bxg7 Nxg7 20. Nf3 g5 21. a3 Bh5 $13 ) 17... h6 ( 17... Ne8 $14 { Fominyh,A (2530) -Knezevic,M (2445) Tatran Cup Stary Smokovec 1990 (3) 1-0 } ) 18. Nf3 ( 18. Nh3 Rfd8 19. Qxd6 Qxd6 20. Rxd6 Be8 21. Rxd8 Rxd8 { Black is more active and the white queenside is less safe than it seems. } 22. Rd1 Rxd1+ 23. Nxd1 a4 24. b4 Nce4 25. a3 Bf7 $11 26. c5 $2 Bb3 27. Ne3 Ne8 28. Bxg7 Kxg7 $17 ) 18... a4 $1 19. b4 ( 19. Qc2 axb3 20. axb3 Be6 $11 ) 19... Nce4 20. Nxe4 Nxe4 21. Qc2 Bxb2 22. Qxb2 Be6 23. Qc1 ( 23. Qc2 b5 24. cxb5 cxb5 25. Nd4 Bc4 $11 ) 23... Qf7 $11 ) 16... Nfe4 { Now is a good moment for occupying this square. Black will decide later where to develop his queen's rook, which may still be useful on a8 due to the possibility of ...a5-a4. } ( 16... Rad8 17. Ne2 Kh8 18. Nf4 Bf7 19. Ng5 Bg8 20. Bc3 a4 21. Bd4 $16 { Esipenko,A (2682) -Dubov,D (2699) Titled Tuesday intern op 9th June blitz 2020 (7) 1-0 } ) 17. Nd4 ( 17. Nxe4 fxe4 18. Bxg7 Kxg7 19. Nd4 Bg4 $11 ) ( 17. Ne2 Bxb2 18. Qxb2 a4 $1 19. Nc3 ( 19. b4 a3 20. Qc2 Na4 $15 ) 19... axb3 20. axb3 Ra6 $13 { In this line and other similar involving ...a5-a4, we notice that the white queenside may turn into a zonal weakness. } ) 17... Bf7 18. Nxe4 ( 18. Nce2 { Kustar,S (2395) -Gazik,I (2380) Leiner op 1996 (6) 1-0 } 18... a4 $11 ) 18... fxe4 { This is another typical structure. White's pawns seem to be more compact, but he has weaknesses on f3 and d3 and the bishop on g2 is passive. } ( 18... Nxe4 19. g4 $14 ) 19. Ba3 ( 19. Bc3 d5 20. cxd5 cxd5 $11 { with perfect stability for Black. } ) 19... a4 $1 20. Bxc5 dxc5 21. Ne2 axb3 22. axb3 Rae8 23. Rd2 g5 24. Bh3 Be6 25. Bxe6+ Qxe6 26. Kg2 Qf5 27. Ng1 Be5 $11 *
