1. d4 e6 2. g3 f5 3. Bg2 Nf6 4. Nf3 g6 5. O-O Bg7 6. c4 O-O 7. Nc3 d6 8. Qc2 Nc6 9. b3 { A flexible move, continuing White's development while also taking measures against ...e6-e5. } 9... Nb4 $1 { This is the most adequate reaction to the last move. Since the queen does not have access to b3 and a4 anymore, White needs to find another square, which is likely to be far from optimal. } ( 9... e5 10. dxe5 dxe5 { runs into } 11. Ba3 Re8 12. Rfd1 $16 ) 10. Qb1 $14 { This aims at preventing the immediate ...e6-e5, but this move causes some queenside congestion. } ( 10. Qd1 { allows } 10... e5 ( { There is no need to play for repetition with } 10... Nc6 { , which actually transposes to Lines 8 to 10. } ) 11. Ba3 a5 12. dxe5 dxe5 13. Nxe5 Ne4 14. Nxe4 fxe4 15. Bb2 ( 15. Qxd8 Rxd8 16. Bb2 Re8 $19 ) 15... Qxd1 16. Raxd1 { The only move avoiding troubles. } ( 16. Rfxd1 Re8 $17 17. a3 Na6 18. f4 exf3 19. exf3 Bxe5 20. Re1 Bxb2 21. Rxe8+ Kf7 22. Rae1 Bxa3 $19 ) 16... Re8 17. a3 Na6 18. f4 exf3 19. exf3 Rxe5 ( 19... Bxe5 20. Rfe1 Bxb2 21. Rxe8+ Kf7 22. Rdd8 $18 ) 20. Rd8+ Kf7 21. Bxe5 Bxe5 22. f4 Bd6 $13 ) ( 10. Qd2 { Unanimously played. } 10... a5 11. Bb2 ( 11. a3 Nc6 12. Bb2 e5 $11 ) 11... Ne4 12. Nxe4 fxe4 { There is no knight retreat to d2. } 13. Ne1 d5 { Black has good development and can look into the future with optimism. } 14. f3 ( 14. e3 b6 15. f3 exf3 16. Nxf3 Bb7 17. Ne5 { Smith, B (2399) -Bernal Varela, N (2266) FICGS class M 000016 email 2018 (1) 1/2-1/2 } 17... Qe7 $11 18. a3 Nc6 19. cxd5 Nxe5 20. dxe5 Rxf1+ 21. Rxf1 Rd8 22. e4 exd5 23. exd5 Bxe5 $11 ) 14... c5 $1 { A natural reaction to the weakening white move. } 15. e3 ( 15. dxc5 e3 $1 16. Qc1 d4 17. f4 g5 18. a3 Nc6 19. Nd3 gxf4 20. Rxf4 e5 $44 { A curious position, featuring Black's huge space advantage. The knight on d3 keeps White's position together. } ) ( 15. fxe4 Rxf1+ 16. Bxf1 dxc4 17. bxc4 cxd4 $11 ) 15... cxd4 16. exd4 { Blees,A (2403) -De Boer,E (2168) Hilversum op 2016 (3) 1/2-1/2 } 16... e5 $1 17. dxe5 dxc4 18. Qe3 cxb3 19. Qxb3+ Kh8 $11 20. Qe3 ( 20. f4 Qb6+ 21. Kh1 Be6 22. Qa3 Rfd8 23. Bxe4 Rac8 $17 ) 20... exf3 21. Bxf3 Be6 $11 ) 10... Qe7 $1 { Preparing ...e6-e5. } ( 10... e5 { does not work so well now. } 11. dxe5 dxe5 12. Nxe5 Ne4 13. Nxe4 Bxe5 ( { The difference is that after } 13... fxe4 14. Bb2 $18 { the bishop is defended. } ) 14. a3 $14 ( 14. Ng5 Qf6 15. a3 Bxa1 16. axb4 $13 ) 14... Bxa1 ( 14... Nc6 15. Ng5 $16 ) 15. Qxa1 fxe4 16. axb4 Bf5 17. Bh6 Rf7 18. h3 $14 ) 11. a3 ( 11. Bb2 e5 12. a3 Nc6 { transposes. } ) 11... Nc6 12. Bb2 e5 13. dxe5 dxe5 14. Nd5 Nxd5 15. cxd5 Nd8 { The knight is heading for the perfect blockading square on d6, but may also sustain ...c7-c6 in the near future.. } 16. Rd1 ( 16. Qc2 c6 $11 17. a4 Re8 18. Ba3 Qf6 19. d6 e4 20. Nd2 Nf7 21. Nc4 Be6 22. Rad1 Bd5 23. Ne3 Qe6 $11 ) 16... Nf7 17. Qc2 Nd6 18. Rac1 Rf7 { [%cal Gf5f4] } 19. e3 b6 20. a4 Bb7 21. b4 Re8 22. b5 g5 $11 { Engines prefer White, but I can see what Black can do, while White's plans are not easy to find. } *
