1. d4 e6 2. g3 f5 3. Bg2 Nf6 4. Nf3 g6 5. O-O Bg7 6. c4 O-O 7. Nc3 d6 8. Qc2 Nc6 9. Rd1 { The most popular and surely the most flexible move. White takes measures against ...e6-e5 without committing himself too much. True, Rad1 would have been more natural, but it would be illegal, of course. } 9... Qe7 10. Rb1 ( { It might look that } 10. a3 { is more effective. Indeed, besides threatening to win space on the queenside, this move takes the b4-square under control in order to make the threat d5 real. However, after } 10... a5 { the weakness of the b3-square invites White to prudence. } 11. Bd2 ( 11. d5 Nd8 12. dxe6 Nxe6 13. Nd5 { is premature because of } 13... Nxd5 14. cxd5 Nc5 { [%cal Ya5a4] when White does not seem to have a favourable way of avoiding the blockade of the queenside. } ) 11... Bd7 12. Be1 Nd8 13. b4 axb4 14. axb4 Nf7 15. Nd2 c6 { [%csl Yd5][%cal Ge6e5] } 16. e3 e5 $13 { Hertneck-Zysk/Budapest (DUTEP) 1990 } ) ( 10. e4 fxe4 11. Nxe4 e5 12. dxe5 ( 12. Nxf6+ Qxf6 13. dxe5 dxe5 { <->f } ) 12... dxe5 $1 13. Bg5 Bf5 $11 { We are familiar with this structure already. } 14. Nh4 Nd4 15. Qa4 { Dekker,A (2152) -Nijboer,F (2495) Spakenburg op 2018 (2) 0-1 } ( 15. Nxf5 gxf5 16. Nxf6+ Bxf6 17. Bxf6 Qxf6 18. Qd2 Rad8 19. Kh1 c6 $36 { [%cal Gh7h5] } ) 15... Bd7 16. Qa5 Bc6 $17 ) ( 10. d5 Nb4 { still works out well for Black. } 11. Qb3 Na6 12. dxe6 Nc5 13. Qc2 Bxe6 14. Nd5 ( 14. b3 a5 15. Bb2 c6 $11 { leaves the rook misplaced on d1. } ) 14... Nxd5 15. cxd5 Bd7 { [%cal Gd7a4] } 16. Bg5 ( 16. Rb1 Rae8 $15 { [%cal Gf5f4,Gd7f5] } ) 16... Bf6 17. Bxf6 Qxf6 18. e3 ( 18. b4 $2 Ba4 $19 ) 18... a5 { Black is stable on the queenside and has a clear plan on the kingside, compensating for White's space advantage. } 19. Nd4 g5 20. Ne2 Rae8 21. Rd4 Re7 22. Rad1 Be8 23. Bf3 Nd7 24. Nc1 ( 24. Qxc7 Ne5 $19 ) 24... Ne5 25. Be2 Ng6 26. Nd3 Qg7 27. Ne1 f4 $17 { Lagunow,A (2341) -Glek,I (2443) Berlin-ch 2023 (2) 1/2-1/2 } ) 10... a5 ( 10... e5 { is premature yet because of } 11. dxe5 dxe5 12. Nd5 $16 Nxd5 13. cxd5 Nd8 14. Be3 Nf7 15. Rbc1 { and Black is not in time to reach his optimal regrouping. } ) ( { The immediate transfer of the knight to f7 with } 10... Nd8 11. b4 Nf7 { leaves White with a huge advantage of space after } 12. b5 $14 { [%cal Yc1a3] } ) 11. a3 Nd8 $5 { [%cal Yd8f7,Ye6e5,Yc7c6] Everything is ready for this manoeuvre now. } ( { The untested pawn sacrifice } 11... a4 $5 { is also worth investigating and, why not, trying out in practice. } 12. Nxa4 ( 12. Be3 Bd7 { more or less defends the pawn indirectly. } 13. Nxa4 Nxd4 14. Nxd4 Bxa4 15. b3 Bd7 16. Bxb7 { White hopes to set up some queenside domination, but Black can react on the kingside. } 16... f4 $3 { weakening the kingside since Bxf4 ...e6-e5 is a fork, and clearing the fifth rank for the queen's rook. } 17. gxf4 Ra5 $44 18. Nc6 Bxc6 19. Bxc6 Nh5 $11 ) 12... e5 13. Nc3 ( 13. d5 Nd4 14. Nxd4 exd4 15. Rxd4 Ng4 { for4ces White to sacrifice on g4 with just reasonable compensation, since after } 16. Rd1 { Black has } 16... f4 $19 { threatening ...Bf5 and creating the premises for a decisive attack. } 17. Bxf4 $6 g5 ) 13... f4 $1 { Threatening ...Bf5. } 14. dxe5 dxe5 15. Nd5 { The only way of maintaining the fight for the initiative on. } ( 15. gxf4 Bf5 16. e4 Bg4 17. Rd3 Nd7 18. Nd5 Qd8 $44 ) ( 15. Ra1 $2 e4 16. Ng5 e3 17. gxf4 Bf5 18. Qb3 exf2+ 19. Kxf2 Ng4+ 20. Kg3 Nd4 $19 ) 15... Nxd5 16. cxd5 Bf5 17. Qc4 $1 Na5 $1 18. d6+ $1 ( 18. Qa2 $2 Bxb1 $17 { attacks the queen. } ) 18... Nxc4 19. dxe7 Rfe8 20. Ng5 c6 21. Ne4 Rxe7 22. b3 Nb6 23. Bb2 { White has stabilised the position, but Black does not have big worries, either. } 23... Nd5 24. Rbc1 Bxe4 $5 25. Bxe4 Nf6 26. Bb1 ( 26. Bg2 e4 27. gxf4 Nd5 28. Bxg7 Kxg7 29. e3 Rxa3 $11 ) ( 26. Rc4 Nxe4 27. Rxe4 fxg3 28. hxg3 Ra5 29. Rd8+ Kf7 30. a4 Rd5 $11 ) 26... Nd5 $5 ( 26... e4 27. Bxf6 Bxf6 28. a4 e3 29. f3 $5 { In this line, the bishop is relatively active on b1, and not passive on g2. I doubt that White has more than a pleasant position, though. } ) 27. Be4 Nf6 $11 ) 12. e4 ( 12. b4 axb4 13. axb4 { is less effective now because the bishop cannot emerge on a3 so soon as in a previously mentioned line. } 13... Nf7 14. Bb2 ( 14. b5 e5 15. dxe5 dxe5 16. Ng5 e4 17. Nxf7 Qxf7 18. Nd5 Be6 $11 { Knezevic,I (2149) -Kovacevic,B (2468) Bosnjaci op 20th 2015 (2) 0-1 } ) 14... c6 ( 14... e5 15. dxe5 dxe5 16. Nd5 Nxd5 17. cxd5 Nd6 $11 ) 15. b5 Bd7 ( 15... e5 $5 ) 16. Ra1 cxb5 ( 16... e5 $11 ) 17. cxb5 ( 17. Nxb5 Bxb5 18. cxb5 d5 $11 ) 17... e5 18. dxe5 dxe5 19. Qc1 Rfc8 20. Ba3 Qe8 21. Qb2 e4 22. Nd4 Be6 $15 { Darbinyan,N (2072) -Muzychuk,A (2364) Wch U16 Girls 2005 (3) 0-1 } ) 12... fxe4 13. Nxe4 Nxe4 14. Qxe4 Nf7 ( 14... e5 15. dxe5 Nf7 $11 ) 15. Bh3 { [%csl Gb7][%cal Yh3c8] Aiming to cause Black problems with the advance of the e-pawn. } 15... Qf6 16. Bd2 e5 { The simplest. } ( 16... d5 $6 { is too ambitious. } 17. Qe2 dxc4 ( 17... Nd6 18. Ne5 dxc4 19. Rbc1 b5 20. b3 { Tal } ) 18. Bf4 Nd6 19. Ng5 Re8 20. Bg2 $36 Ra6 ( 20... Bd7 21. Ne4 Nxe4 22. Bxe4 Bc6 23. Bxc6 $16 { Tal } ) 21. Ne4 Nxe4 22. Bxe4 b5 ( 22... Qf7 23. Qxc4 e5 24. Bd5 Be6 25. dxe5 { Tal } ) 23. b3 cxb3 24. Qxb5 Rf8 25. Qxb3 Rb6 26. Qe3 Rxb1 27. Bxb1 Bb7 28. Ba2 Bd5 29. Bxd5 exd5 30. Bxc7 $16 a4 31. Rd3 Qf5 32. Be5 Bh6 33. Qe2 Rc8 34. Rf3 Qh3 35. Bc7 Bf8 36. Qb5 Qe6 37. Be5 Qc6 38. Qa5 Ra8 39. Qd2 Rc8 40. Kg2 Qd7 41. h4 Qg4 { Tal,M-Botvinnik,M World Championship 23th 1960 (19) 1-0 } ) ( 16... Bd7 17. Qxb7 Nd8 18. Qxa8 Bc6 19. Qxa5 Qxf3 20. d5 Bd4 21. Bg2 $18 { Tal } ) ( { Instead of Botvinnik's over-optimistic move, Tal recommended: } 16... c6 { which has done quite well in ulterior correspondence games: } 17. Qe2 ( 17. Bc3 e5 ( 17... d5 ) 18. Bxc8 Raxc8 19. dxe5 dxe5 { /\Nd6 Tal } ) ( 17. Qf4 { Philpott, J-Jones,D/ENG-chT corr 1993/Corr Nr. 1 } 17... Qxf4 18. Bxf4 e5 19. Bxc8 Raxc8 20. dxe5 dxe5 21. Be3 e4 22. Nd2 Ne5 23. c5 Rce8 $13 ) 17... e5 18. Bxc8 { Hondema, E-Wind,M/NED-ch M corr 1990 } 18... Raxc8 19. dxe5 Nxe5 20. Nxe5 Rce8 $1 { we can feel that the white kingside is left without sufficient defenders, which enables Black maintains equality in spite of his hanging d6- and a5-pawns. } 21. Bc3 Qf5 22. Qf3 Rxe5 $1 23. Qxf5 Rexf5 $11 ) 17. Bxc8 Raxc8 18. Bc3 ( 18. Qxb7 c6 $1 ) ( 18. d5 { Huuskonen,V-Nyman,K/FIN-ch E34 corr 1983 } 18... a4 $1 ) ( 18. Be3 b6 19. c5 bxc5 20. dxc5 Kh8 21. b4 axb4 22. axb4 c6 23. cxd6 Nxd6 24. Rxd6 Qxd6 25. Bc5 Qd5 26. Qxd5 cxd5 27. Bxf8 Rxf8 $13 { Luodonpaeae,M-Nyman,K/FIN-ch E33 corr 1983/Corr Nr. 1 } ) 18... Nh6 19. Rd3 exd4 20. Bxd4 Qf5 21. Re1 Qxe4 22. Rxe4 Rce8 23. Bxg7 Kxg7 24. Rxe8 Rxe8 25. c5 Nf7 26. Rb3 Rb8 27. Nd4 dxc5 28. Ne6+ Kg8 29. Nxc7 { 1/2-1/2 Engqvist,T-Nyman,K/Baltic Sea tt5 corr8691 1986 } *
