1. d4 e6 2. Nf3 f5 3. g3 Nf6 4. Bg2 g6 5. O-O Bg7 6. c4 O-O 7. Nc3 d6 8. Re1 Ne4 9. Qc2 { The most popular reaction. Black is invited to release the tension. } 9... Nxc3 10. Qxc3 { This natural move absolves Black of any problems. } ( 10. bxc3 { is examined in the next line. } ) 10... e5 { The simplest. } ( { In the game that determined me to write this electronic book, Muzychuk preferred } 10... Nc6 { Salimova,N (2409) -Muzychuk, A (2504) FIDE World Cup (Women) 2023 (6.4) 0-1 } ) 11. dxe5 ( 11. e4 fxe4 12. Bg5 Qe8 13. Rxe4 Nc6 14. dxe5 ( 14. d5 Ne7 $11 ) 14... dxe5 $11 ) 11... dxe5 12. Nxe5 { The critical test. } ( 12. e4 Nc6 13. Bg5 Qe8 14. Be3 $2 ( 14. exf5 Bxf5 $11 ) 14... f4 15. Bc5 Rf6 $17 { Bueno Filho,J (2031) -Castro,D (2042) Varginha Mineiro-ch 2019 (6) 1/2-1/2 } ) 12... Nd7 13. f4 Qe7 14. e4 Nxe5 15. fxe5 Bxe5 { The human move, of course. } ( 15... c6 $5 { is typical for correspondence games. } 16. exf5 Rxf5 17. Bf4 g5 18. Bd2 Rxe5 ( 18... h6 19. Qd3 Rxe5 20. Rxe5 Qxe5 21. Qd8+ Kh7 22. Bc3 Qe3+ 23. Kh1 Bh3 24. Qxa8 Bxg2+ 25. Kxg2 Qe2+ 26. Kg1 Qe3+ 27. Kf1 Qf3+ 28. Kg1 { Verfuerth,T (2067) -De Boer,E (1933) Delft Prinsenstad op-B 9th 2016 (3) 1/2-1/2 } ) 19. Qb3 Bg4 { Montgomery, J-Bauer,H W-Cup1Juniors prel email 2008 1/2-1/2 } ) 16. exf5 Rxf5 17. Qb3 Bd7 $5 { Just developing. } ( 17... Bd4+ 18. Be3 $16 ) 18. Bxb7 ( 18. Qxb7 $2 Bd4+ $19 ) ( 18. Be3 Bc6 19. Bxc6 bxc6 20. Rad1 Qf6 21. c5+ Kh8 22. Rd7 Rf8 23. Qc4 Rf2 $11 ) 18... Raf8 $44 { Black is better developed already and has full compensation for the pawn. } *
