1. d4 e6 2. Nf3 f5 3. g3 Nf6 4. Bg2 g6 5. O-O Bg7 6. c4 O-O 7. Nc3 d6 8. Re1 Ne4 9. Qc2 Nxc3 10. bxc3 { White spoils his structure in order to strengthen the defence of the pawn on d4 and clear the bishop's path to a3. In practice, Black has been doing quite badly and this looked like a problematic line since even engines initially think that White has a clear advantage. Patient analysis shows that things are not that clear, though. } 10... e5 11. e4 ( 11. dxe5 dxe5 12. Ba3 { is not too molesting. By releasing the tension, White aborts one of his main ideas (the strengthening of the d4-square) . In the long run, the pawns on c4 and c3 will be weak. } 12... Re8 13. e4 ( 13. Rad1 Qf6 14. e4 f4 $17 { Kolay, A (2208) -Polivanov, A (2452) PNWCC Online blitz JP 12th 2020 (10) 0-1 } ) 13... Nc6 ( 13... f4 $5 14. gxf4 Nc6 { is also interesting. } ) 14. exf5 Bxf5 15. Qb3 e4 ( 15... Na5 $2 16. Qa4 b6 17. Rad1 Qc8 18. Ng5 $18 { Giri,A (2642) -Reinderman,D (2608) NED-ch65 Eindhoven 2010 (9) 1-0 } ) 16. Rad1 Qf6 17. Nd2 ( 17. Nd4 { Hebden, M (2426) -Goodger, M (2011) Nottingham 4NCL op 20th 2018 (3) 1-0 } 17... Rab8 $11 ) 17... Na5 18. Qb5 ( 18. Qb4 Qxc3 $1 ) 18... Re5 19. Bc5 Qc6 ( 19... b6 20. Bd4 $16 ) 20. Qxc6 Nxc6 21. Bd4 Re7 22. Bc5 Re6 23. Bxe4 Bxe4 24. Nxe4 ( 24. Rxe4 Rae8 25. Rxe6 Rxe6 26. Rc1 Bh6 $44 ) 24... Rae8 25. f3 Bxc3 $11 { Williamson, D (2054) -Carr, T (2086) BCCA-Rodford email 2014 [109] 1/2-1/2 } ) 11... Nc6 12. exf5 ( 12. Bg5 { is best met with } 12... Qd7 $1 { Black's lack of coordination is temporary, whil;e the bishop on g5 is unstable. } ( 12... Qe8 13. exf5 Bxf5 14. Qb2 $16 ) 13. exf5 ( 13. dxe5 dxe5 14. Rad1 Qf7 ) 13... Qxf5 14. Qd2 ( 14. Qxf5 Bxf5 15. dxe5 Nxe5 $11 ) 14... Na5 15. c5 { Briem,B (2127) -Jakubiec,A (2448) ISL-chT Kvika 2223 2022 (8.3) 1-0 } 15... Be6 $11 { With good control on light squares and a normal development. } ) ( 12. dxe5 Nxe5 $14 ( 12... dxe5 13. exf5 Bxf5 14. Qb3 { is molesting. } ) 13. Nxe5 Bxe5 14. exf5 ( 14. Bh6 f4 $5 15. Bxf8 Qxf8 { with excellent compensation for the exchange. } ) ( 14. f4 Bg7 15. Be3 fxe4 16. Bxe4 c6 $11 ) 14... Bxf5 15. Qb3 Qf6 16. Re3 ( 16. Bd2 Be4 17. f4 Bxg2 18. Kxg2 Qf7 19. Qxb7 Rab8 20. Qe4 Rb2 21. Re2 Rxd2 22. Rxd2 Bxc3 $11 ) ( 16. Bh6 Bxc3 $1 ) 16... g5 17. c5+ ( 17. Qxb7 Rab8 18. Qd5+ Be6 19. Qd2 Bxc4 $11 ) 17... Be6 18. Qb2 Rae8 19. Qd2 ( 19. Bxb7 Rb8 20. c6 Rf7 $19 ) 19... b6 20. cxd6 Bxd6 21. Rf3 Qg7 22. Qxg5 Rxf3 23. Qxg7+ Kxg7 24. Bxf3 Be5 { Black's superior structure and development ensure him lasting compensation for the pawn. } 25. Bd2 Rd8 26. Be1 b5 27. Rb1 Bc4 28. Rb2 Re8 29. Bd2 a5 30. Bc6 Re6 31. Bxb5 $2 Rb6 32. a4 c6 $17 ) 12... Bxf5 13. Qb3 exd4 $14 { It is strange that this has never been tried in practice. After all, this is why Black has played ...e6-e5, is it not? } ( { In all the games, Black played the passive } 13... Rb8 14. c5+ Kh8 15. cxd6 cxd6 16. dxe5 dxe5 ( 16... Nxe5 17. Nxe5 dxe5 18. Ba3 $14 { Petriashvili, N (2441) -Srijit, P (2317) Wch U18 Mumbai 2019 (3) 1-0 } ) 17. Ba3 Re8 18. Rad1 Qf6 19. Nd2 $16 { Gukesh, D (2578) -Sengupta, D (2527) FIDE World Cup AICF Qual rapid 2021 (7) 1/2-1/2 } ) ( 13... Na5 $14 { also makes sense, since the pawn on c4 is weak. White seems to maintain an edge, though. } 14. Qa4 ( 14. Qa3 b6 { is playable for Black. } 15. dxe5 dxe5 16. Bg5 Qd6 17. c5 Qxc5 18. Qxc5 bxc5 19. Nxe5 Rae8 20. Bd5+ Be6 21. Bxe6+ Rxe6 ) ( 14. Qb4 { allows } 14... c5 $5 15. dxc5 dxc5 16. Qxc5 Rc8 17. Qd5+ Qxd5 18. cxd5 Rxc3 { leaves Black balancing over the precipice. } 19. Bb2 e4 20. Ng5 Nc4 21. Bxc3 Bxc3 22. Nxe4 Bxa1 23. Rxa1 Kg7 $14 { Black may be able to draw here since his king is potentially more active than White's and the pawn on d5 can be blocked by the knight. } ) 14... b6 15. dxe5 Qd7 16. Qxd7 Bxd7 { The pawns on c4 and c3 are hanging (the latter indirectly) , but White maintains the initiative } 17. Ng5 Bc6 18. Ne6 Bxe5 $5 19. Nxf8 Bxc3 20. Bh6 Bxg2 21. Kxg2 Rxf8 22. Bxf8 Kxf8 23. c5 $1 ( 23. Rac1 Bxe1 24. Rxe1 Nxc4 $11 ) 23... bxc5 24. Kf3 Nc6 25. Rac1 Bxe1 26. Rxe1 Kf7 ) 14. Bg5 ( 14. Qxb7 Bd7 15. Nxd4 Bxd4 16. cxd4 Rb8 17. Qa6 Qf6 { In view of the possible ...Nb4 and Black has very good counterplay. } 18. Be3 ( 18. Bf4 g5 $5 19. Be3 Nxd4 20. Bd5+ Kh8 21. Qxa7 Nc2 22. Rab1 Rbe8 23. Rf1 Bh3 $11 ) 18... Nb4 $1 ( 18... Nxd4 $2 19. Bd5+ Kh8 20. Qxa7 Nc2 21. Rab1 Rbe8 22. Rf1 Bh3 23. Bh6 $18 ) 19. Qxa7 Nc2 20. Rf1 ( 20. Reb1 Nxe3 21. fxe3 Qf2+ 22. Kh1 Rxb1+ 23. Rxb1 Qc2 24. Rg1 Qxc4 $11 ) 20... Nxa1 21. Rxa1 Rb2 22. Rf1 ( 22. Qxc7 Rxf2 $11 ) 22... Bf5 $11 ) 14... Qd7 15. Nxd4 Nxd4 16. cxd4 Rae8 $1 { Just completing the development. What will be, will be. } ( 16... Bh3 17. c5+ Kh8 18. Bxh3 Qxh3 19. cxd6 $16 ) 17. Qxb7 ( 17. Rxe8 Rxe8 18. Qxb7 c5 $11 ) ( 17. c5+ Kh8 18. Qxb7 Bxd4 $11 ) 17... c5 18. Qd5+ ( 18. Qxd7 Bxd7 $11 ) 18... Kh8 19. dxc5 ( 19. Be3 Be6 20. Qc6 Qxc6 21. Bxc6 Rc8 $11 { The central pawns are hanging. } ) 19... Bxa1 20. Rxa1 dxc5 21. Qxc5 { White has two pawns for the exchange and the black king is exposed in the long run. However, the black rooks have many open files and the white king will also turn a bit unsafe after ...Be4. } 21... Qg7 22. Rc1 Be4 23. Be3 Rc8 24. Qb4 Bxg2 25. Kxg2 Qd7 $11 *
