1. d4 e6 2. c4 f5 3. g3 Nf6 4. Bg2 Bb4+ { If we do not intend to play the stonewall or the Iljin Zhenevsky systems, this maintains our system coherent. } ( 4... g6 5. Nc3 { transposes to a position we have decided to avoid. } ) 5. Nd2 { In the Bogo Indian, this is a challenging move if Black does not have his ideas clear. White intends to get the two bishops without weakening his queenside structure. However, the last move is better combined with the light-squared bishop's development to e2 or d3. On g2, the bishop is far from some important queenside light squares. } ( 5. Bd2 { is examined in the next line. } ) ( 5. Nc3 { transposes to Line 38 or 39. } ) 5... a5 $5 { Black immediately starts fighting for the light squares. The idea is to meet a2-a3 with ...Bxd2 followed by ...a5-a4. } 6. Nf3 ( { It is interesting to check what can happen if White plays } 6. a3 { at once. } 6... Bxd2+ ( 6... Be7 7. e4 $14 ) 7. Bxd2 d6 ( 7... a4 $6 { is premature due to } 8. e3 $1 { followed by Ne2-c3, endangering the pawn. } ) 8. b4 ( 8. Nf3 a4 { is likely to transpose to the main line. } ) ( 8. e3 { only weakens the light squares without bringing in any benefit. } 8... O-O 9. Ne2 Ne4 10. Bc1 a4 $11 ) 8... e5 9. b5 ( 9. Bc3 Qe7 $11 ) ( 9. bxa5 exd4 10. Nf3 Nc6 $11 ) 9... O-O 10. Qc2 Qe7 11. Nh3 { White needs to stay flexible. } ( 11. Nf3 $6 e4 $11 ) 11... h6 { Restricting the edged knight. } 12. O-O Nbd7 13. Bc3 Nb6 14. Bb2 Re8 15. a4 Rb8 $5 { Waiting for White to commit himself and preparing ... Be6, ...Qf7.. } ( 15... e4 { threatening ...d6-d5 can be met with } 16. d5 $1 Nbd7 17. f3 Nc5 18. Ra3 $14 { with perfect white coordination. } ) 16. Rac1 ( 16. Ra3 Be6 $11 ) ( 16. Rfc1 e4 $1 17. d5 Nbd7 18. f3 Nc5 19. Ra3 Bd7 $11 { With the rook on c1, things are not the same. } ) 16... e4 17. d5 Nbd7 18. f3 Nc5 $11 ) 6... O-O 7. O-O a4 { With the white bishop on d3, this would endanger the daring pawn, but now it faces White with certain practical problems. } 8. a3 ( 8. Nb1 $14 Qe8 { Preparing to defend the pawn on a4. The move is also typical for this structure in general. } 9. Nc3 ( 9. a3 Be7 10. Nc3 d6 { leads to an improved version of the Iljin Zhenevsky system. } 11. Re1 Ne4 12. Nb5 Qd8 { followed by ...c7-c6. } ) 9... Bxc3 10. bxc3 d6 11. Ba3 Nbd7 12. c5 ( 12. Rb1 b6 $11 ) ( 12. Nd2 e5 $11 ) ( 12. Qc2 b6 $11 ) 12... dxc5 13. dxc5 c6 $13 ) ( 8. Qc2 d6 9. Nb1 Qe8 10. a3 Ba5 $11 ) 8... Bxd2 9. Bxd2 d6 { This position has been rehearsed in a series of correspondence games. } 10. Rc1 { Getting ready for either c4-c5 or 4-d5, depending on the circumstances. } ( 10. Qc2 Bd7 11. Rac1 Qe8 12. Rfe1 Nc6 13. Bc3 ( 13. d5 exd5 14. cxd5 Nxd5 15. Qc4 Ne7 16. Bg5 Ra5 17. b4 axb3 18. Qxb3 Rb5 19. Qa2 c6 20. a4 Ra5 21. e4 fxe4 22. Rxe4 Qf7 23. Qd2 Raa8 24. Bxe7 Nxe7 25. Qxd6 Nd5 $11 ) 13... e5 14. dxe5 dxe5 15. Red1 e4 16. Nd4 Nxd4 17. Bxd4 Bc6 { Black is very stable. } 18. Qc3 Rf7 19. Rd2 Nd7 20. Rcd1 b6 21. c5 b5 22. f4 exf3 $11 { Teichmann,C (2386) -Siigur,J (2411) VW-Cup3 final email 2014 1/2-1/2 } 23. exf3 f4 $11 ) 10... Qe8 { This was played in the only over-the-board game which was also the only one Black lost! It is my favourite move, though. } ( { In correspondence games, Black has always played } 10... Nc6 { and achieved a draw. } 11. d5 { This pawn sacrifice is the best chance for getting some initiative. } ( { Static play is likely to be comfortable for Black. } 11. c5 d5 12. Bf4 h6 13. h4 Bd7 { [%cal Gd7e8,Ge8h5] followed by ...Be8-h5. } ) 11... exd5 12. cxd5 Nxd5 13. b4 Nce7 14. Bg5 ( 14. Nd4 h6 15. b5 Bd7 16. Rc4 Nb6 17. Rc2 { Aupi Royo,J (2371) -Siigur,J (2411) VW-Cup3 final email 2014 1/2-1/2 } 17... Nbd5 $11 ) 14... Nf6 15. Qd3 d5 16. b5 c6 { Van Tienhoven,R (2417) -Siigur,J (2411) VW-Cup3 final email 2014 1/2-1/2 With mutual chances. } ) 11. Bc3 ( 11. Re1 Nc6 12. d5 Nd8 $11 ) 11... Ne4 12. Nd2 Nxc3 13. Rxc3 e5 $11 ( 13... Nc6 $2 14. d5 Nd8 15. c5 $16 { Janjgava,L (2470) -Palos,O (2350) Belgrade GMA op 1988 1-0 } ) *
