1. d4 e6 2. c4 f5 3. g3 Nf6 4. Bg2 Bb4+ 5. Bd2 { In the Bogo Indian, this way of parrying the check is best suited for the king's fianchetto setup. } 5... Bxd2+ ( { Black could also think of } 5... Be7 6. Nf3 O-O 7. O-O d5 { , transposing to the Stonewall structure, since the bishop is not especially well placed on d2. However, we can keep our repertoire compact by sticking to the plan based on .. .d7-d6 and ...e6-e5. } ) 6. Qxd2 { The same as in the Bogoindian, this is the most consistent way of re-capturing. } ( { On short term, White's dveelopment after } 6. Nxd2 { is faster but of lower quality. } 6... O-O 7. Ngf3 d6 8. O-O Nc6 9. Qc2 { White has to develop his queen anyway, so the talk about the speed of development ends here. } 9... e5 $11 10. d5 ( 10. dxe5 dxe5 11. Rad1 Qe7 $15 ) 10... Ne7 11. e4 f4 $5 ( 11... h6 $11 { preparing ...fxe4 without fearing Ng5 is also good. } ) 12. gxf4 ( 12. c5 h6 13. Rac1 g5 $13 ) 12... Ng6 13. fxe5 dxe5 14. Qc3 Qe7 15. c5 Nh5 $44 ) 6... O-O 7. Nc3 ( { Nothing essentially is changed by } 7. Nf3 d6 8. O-O Nc6 9. d5 Ne5 10. Na3 ( 10. Nxe5 dxe5 11. Nc3 e4 $11 ) 10... Nxf3+ 11. exf3 e5 $11 ) 7... d6 8. Nf3 ( 8. Nh3 { does not seem much to the point. Black can gain space in the centre effortlessly and the white knight will not reach e6 easily. } 8... e5 9. O-O { Munoz Galvez, J (2304) -Gaona Ballesteros, A (1443) COL-chT Santa Marta 2022 (4.1) 1-0 } 9... h6 $5 { Keeping the knight passive on h3. } 10. Rfd1 Qe7 11. Rac1 ( 11. dxe5 dxe5 12. Nd5 Nxd5 13. cxd5 Nd7 14. Rac1 Nf6 15. Qc2 Rf7 $11 { With the knight passive, White cannot claim an advantage due to his pressure on c7. } ) 11... Nc6 12. dxe5 ( 12. Nd5 Qf7 $11 ) 12... dxe5 13. Nd5 Qf7 14. b4 Nd8 $11 ) 8... Nc6 { Following the classical rules, according to which the queen should be the last (or among the last) pieces to develop. } ( 8... Qe7 { is examined in Line 22. } ) ( 8... Qe8 $6 { is more passive. } 9. O-O e5 10. dxe5 dxe5 11. Nd5 Na6 12. Nxf6+ Rxf6 13. e4 ( 13. Qd5+ Re6 14. Rad1 c6 15. Qa5 $16 ) 13... f4 14. Qc3 Re6 15. Rad1 Nc5 ( 15... c6 16. c5 $16 ) 16. Rfe1 $16 ) 9. O-O ( 9. d5 Ne5 10. b3 Nxf3+ 11. exf3 e5 $11 ) ( 9. Rd1 { is examined in the next line. } ) 9... e5 { Black has carried out his first part of the plan. } 10. d5 { Usually a concession in the Dutch Defence, this is the only challenging move now. } ( 10. Rad1 e4 11. Ng5 h6 12. Nh3 Ne7 13. d5 ( 13. f3 c6 ) 13... Ng6 ( 13... a6 14. f3 b5 ) 14. f3 exf3 15. exf3 f4 16. Nxf4 Nxf4 17. Qxf4 Nxd5 18. Qd2 Nxc3 19. Qxc3 Qf6 $11 { Broniek, M (2274) -Bernal Varela, N (2418) FICGS class SM 000021 email 2018 (1) 1/2-1/2 } ) ( 10. dxe5 dxe5 11. Qxd8 Rxd8 12. e4 fxe4 13. Ng5 Nd4 14. Ngxe4 Nxe4 15. Bxe4 c6 $11 16. Rfe1 Bg4 17. Kg2 Rf8 18. h3 Bh5 19. g4 Bf7 20. b3 h5 21. Rad1 Rad8 22. f3 h4 23. Rd2 $2 Nxf3 $1 { Sundararajan,K (2435) -Nisipeanu,L (2670) Pardubice op rap 24th rapid 2013 (3) 0-1 } ) 10... Ne7 11. Ng5 ( 11. e4 { can be met in several ways. } 11... f4 $14 ( 11... Nxe4 $14 12. Nxe4 fxe4 13. Ng5 h6 14. Nxe4 b6 15. b4 a5 16. a3 axb4 17. axb4 Bd7 $11 ) ( 11... fxe4 12. Ng5 h6 $14 ) 12. gxf4 Ng6 13. fxe5 dxe5 14. Ne1 Nh5 $44 ) 11... Ng6 12. Ne6 Bxe6 13. dxe6 Qc8 $14 ( { The seemingly solid } 13... c6 $2 { in fact creates an additional weakness. } 14. Rad1 Ne8 15. e4 f4 16. c5 Qe7 17. cxd6 Qxe6 18. d7 $2 ( 18. Na4 $1 b6 19. d7 Nf6 20. Qd6 $16 ) 18... Nf6 $2 ( 18... Nc7 19. Na4 Qe7 $11 20. Qd6 Qxd6 21. Rxd6 Nb5 22. Rd3 b6 23. Bh3 Nd4 $11 ) 19. d8 $2 ( 19. Na4 $1 { either transpsoes above, or maintains White's advantage after } 19... Qe7 20. Qd6 $16 ) 19... Raxd8 20. Qxd8 Rxd8 21. Rxd8+ Kf7 $17 22. Rfd1 Qe7 23. R1d6 Qc7 24. Bh3 Ke7 25. Rd2 Qxd8 26. Rxd8 Kxd8 $19 { Villegas,P (2288) -Nisipeanu,L (2670) Pardubice op rap 24th rapid 2013 (1) 0-1 } ) 14. e4 f4 15. Bh3 Qe8 16. Rfe1 ( 16. Nd5 $2 Nxe4 17. Qe2 Ng5 $17 ) ( 16. Qd3 Ne7 $5 { Preparing . ..Qh5. } 17. Nd5 Nfxd5 18. cxd5 Qh5 19. Bg2 f3 20. Bh1 Rf6 $13 { The bishop is passive on h1. } ) 16... Rd8 ( 16... Ne7 $2 17. Nd5 Nfxd5 18. cxd5 Qh5 19. Bg2 f3 20. Bf1 $18 ) 17. Rad1 c6 18. Qc2 ( { In the event of } 18. b4 { Black has a clear plan of regrouping in order to grab the e6-pawn: } 18... Qe7 ( 18... Ne7 19. Qe2 h6 20. c5 $14 ) 19. b5 Rfe8 ) 18... Ne7 { Clearing the path for the queen. } ( 18... Qe7 19. Qb3 $16 ) 19. Rd2 ( 19. Qe2 h6 20. Rd2 Nh7 $13 ) 19... Qh5 20. Bg2 Qg4 21. Qb3 Qxe6 22. Qxb7 Rd7 23. Qb3 c5 $11 *
