1. d4 e6 2. c4 f5 3. g3 Nf6 4. Bg2 Bb4+ 5. Bd2 Bxd2+ 6. Qxd2 O-O 7. Nc3 d6 8. Nf3 Nc6 9. Rd1 $5 { This move prevents ...e6-e5, forcing Black to make some commitment. } 9... Ne4 { Aiming at taking advantage of the fact that Rd1 is not that useful on short term, while the white king is still one tempo away from getting castled. } ( 9... Qe7 { is playable, but tends to lead to positions where White maintains some edge. } 10. O-O ( 10. d5 Ne5 11. Nxe5 dxe5 12. d6 Qxd6 13. Qxd6 cxd6 14. Rxd6 Kf7 15. O-O Ke7 16. c5 Bd7 17. Rfd1 Rac8 18. b4 e4 19. f3 exf3 20. Bxf3 Bc6 $11 ) 10... e5 11. dxe5 ( 11. Nd5 Nxd5 12. cxd5 Nxd4 13. Nxd4 exd4 14. Rfe1 $14 { Collett,P-Svenn,G (2385) SWE-chT 9596 1995 0-1 } 14... Qf6 15. Qxd4 b6 { Black's position is anything but easy to crack. } ) 11... dxe5 12. Nd5 Qd6 13. Qc2 $14 ( 13. Qc3 e4 14. Ng5 { Kanep,M (2523) -Neiksans,A (2481) Keres Memorial 2010 (3) 1/2-1/2 } 14... Nxd5 15. cxd5 Ne5 $11 ) 13... e4 14. c5 $1 { With the white queen on c3 as in the line above, this would run into ...Nxd5. } 14... Qd8 15. Nb6 Qe7 16. Nxa8 exf3 17. exf3 Be6 18. Nxc7 Qxc7 19. Rfe1 Qf7 20. b3 Re8 21. f4 a5 22. Re2 $14 { Black is stable, but a bit passive. } ) 10. Qc2 ( 10. Nxe4 fxe4 11. Ng5 d5 12. O-O Ne7 $14 { The knight is in principle heading for f5, but is also getting closer to d5, for the event of ...dxc4. } ( 12... h6 13. Nh3 Qd6 14. Nf4 Rd8 15. e3 Bd7 16. f3 dxc4 { Moracchini,F (2311) -Lepelletier,B (2444) FRA-chT1 France 2002 (9.4) 1/2-1/2 } 17. Qc3 b5 18. fxe4 $16 ) 13. b3 ( 13. f3 h6 14. Nh3 exf3 15. Rxf3 Rxf3 16. Bxf3 dxc4 $11 { Due to the weakness on e3, the pawn on c4 will be not easy to retrieve. } 17. Qc1 Nf5 18. Kf2 Nd6 19. e4 e5 20. dxe5 Bxh3 21. exd6 cxd6 22. Qxc4+ Kh8 23. e5 Qb6+ 24. Qd4 Qxd4+ 25. Rxd4 dxe5 26. Ra4 a5 27. b4 Rf8 $11 28. bxa5 $2 Bd7 $1 29. Re4 Bc6 30. Re3 e4 $19 ) ( 13. Nh3 c6 14. f3 exf3 15. Rxf3 Rxf3 16. exf3 dxc4 $11 ) 13... Nf5 14. Nh3 Qe7 15. f3 exf3 16. Rxf3 ( 16. exf3 c5 $13 ) ( 16. Bxf3 c6 17. Bg4 e5 $11 ) 16... Bd7 17. Nf4 c6 18. Bh3 { WHite seems to be more active, but Black is well regrouped and his structure is more solid. White has micro problems on e3 and d4, preventing him from fully enjoying the perspective of an ending against a bad bishop. } 18... dxc4 ( 18... b6 $5 { is a neutral move, preparing ...c6-c5 at a later stage. The next move would be ... Rad8 or ...Rae8. } 19. Bxf5 Rxf5 20. Nd3 Rxf3 21. exf3 dxc4 22. bxc4 Be8 $11 { The bishop is not that bad and White has certain weaknesses. } 23. Kg2 Rd8 24. Qb2 Qf6 25. Ne5 c5 $13 ) ( 18... Rae8 19. Bxf5 { forces } 19... Rxf5 { but even with a tempo down with respect to a similar line here, Black is OK after } 20. Nd3 Rxf3 21. exf3 dxc4 22. bxc4 b6 ) 19. bxc4 Rae8 20. Nd3 Nxd4 21. Rxf8+ Rxf8 22. Ne5 c5 23. e3 Ba4 24. exd4 Bxd1 25. Qxd1 Kh8 $13 ) 10... Nxc3 11. Qxc3 Qf6 12. b4 { Zemlyanskii,I (2237) -Moskalenko,A (2482) Cheliabinsk Lozovatsky Memorial-A 2023 (5) 1/2-1/2 The only challenging move. } ( 12. O-O e5 13. b4 e4 14. Ne1 Bd7 15. f3 exf3 16. Bxf3 Rae8 17. b5 Nd8 18. Qa5 c6 19. Ng2 g5 $13 ) 12... Ne7 $5 13. O-O b6 { It has been a long time since we have not seen this move. } 14. Nd2 Rb8 15. f4 ( 15. Qa3 Bb7 $5 16. Qxa7 Bxg2 17. Kxg2 Rfc8 18. Nf3 Ra8 19. Qb7 Rxa2 $11 ) ( 15. e4 f4 16. Nf3 Bb7 17. Rfe1 Ng6 $13 ) 15... Bb7 16. e4 fxe4 17. Nxe4 Bxe4 18. Bxe4 c5 { White has more space and a seemingly active bishop, but it turns out that he is also hanging. } 19. Qd3 d5 20. cxd5 ( 20. Bg2 b5 $5 ) ( 20. Bxh7+ Kh8 { threatening ...g7-g6 forces White to make some efforts on the way of getting compensation for the lost bishop. } 21. cxd5 exd5 22. dxc5 bxc5 23. bxc5 Rb2 24. Rfe1 g6 25. Bxg6 Nxg6 $13 ) 20... exd5 21. Bg2 c4 $5 { An ambitious move. } ( 21... Qxd4+ { is the simplest way to an equal ending. } 22. Qxd4 cxd4 23. Rxd4 Rfd8 24. Rc1 Rbc8 25. Rdd1 Kf7 26. Kf2 a5 27. a3 axb4 28. axb4 Rxc1 29. Rxc1 Ra8 $11 ) 22. Qe2 Rbd8 $13 { Planning ...Nf5, but also ...Nc6. } 23. b5 ( 23. g4 $6 Nc6 24. a3 b5 25. f5 Kh8 $15 ) 23... Nf5 24. Rfe1 Qf7 25. Qf3 Qd7 26. a4 Qd6 27. Re5 Qb4 28. Bh3 ( 28. Rxd5 Kh8 $15 { White is hanging already. } ) 28... Nd6 29. Qxd5+ Kh8 $44 *
