1. d4 e6 2. c4 f5 3. g3 Nf6 4. Bg2 Bb4+ 5. Bd2 Bxd2+ 6. Qxd2 O-O 7. Nc3 d6 8. Nf3 Qe7 { Abstractly speaking, this ensures the advance in the centre but prematurely exposes the queen. Concretely, things may not be that clear here. I recommend considering this move order, too. } 9. O-O e5 ( { Known since 1948, } 9... c6 { came into the limelight a dozen years ago. } 10. Rfe1 $1 d5 11. e3 Nbd7 { Giri,A (2690) -Carlsen,M (2815) Amber-rapid 20th 2011 (4) 0-1 My first feeling when annotating this game long time ago was that everything what Black has done is wrong. Switching to the Stonewall after spending time carrying out the undesirable exchange on d2 is not everything. He also wasted a tempo with his d-pawn. But at that time, engines agreed with Black's play, so my comments were relatively mild then. Nowadays, engines are as horrified as myself at the first impact. To summarize things, in the past nobody would seriously think of playing such a system. Then the engines thought it was OK and people blindly went in for it. After a while, other engines laughed at the old ones. Which will be the next step?! As deeply sorry as I might be, I do not grasp the whole depth of modern chess, nor the meaning of "progress", so I prefer to stick to the traditional plans. } ) 10. dxe5 $1 { The critical move. } ( 10. Rad1 e4 11. Ne1 c6 { Preparing to meet f2-f3 with ...d6-d5. } 12. d5 cxd5 13. Nxd5 Nxd5 14. Qxd5+ Be6 15. Qxd6 Qxd6 16. Rxd6 Bxc4 $11 ) 10... dxe5 11. Nd5 $1 { Now is when the queen is exposed on e7. } ( 11. Rfd1 c6 $14 12. e4 fxe4 13. Ng5 Bg4 14. Qd6 Qxd6 15. Rxd6 e3 16. f3 Bf5 17. Re1 Na6 18. Rxe3 h6 19. Nge4 Nxe4 20. Nxe4 Rad8 $11 ) 11... Qd6 12. Nxf6+ ( { The untested } 12. Qa5 $14 { strongly comes into account. } 12... Nxd5 13. Qxd5+ ( 13. cxd5 e4 14. Nd4 c6 $11 ) 13... Qxd5 14. cxd5 { This looks a bit molesting at first sight. But as it frequently happens in the Dutch Defence, things get better as the game advances. Black's main trump is his strong centre, with the possibility of restricting the enemy bishop. } 14... Nd7 15. Rfd1 $5 { This move, defending the d5-pawn in advance, is the most challenging. } ( 15. Rfc1 { faces Black with fewer problems. } 15... e4 16. Nd4 Nf6 17. Rxc7 Nxd5 18. Rc5 { Provoking the weakening of the c6-square. } 18... Rd8 19. e3 b6 20. Rc2 g6 21. Bf1 { Now we understand why White preferred Rfc1 over Rac1. } 21... Kf8 22. a3 Rd6 { [%cal Gc8d7, Gf8e7] Preparing ...Bd7 followed by ..Ke7. } 23. Nb5 Rd7 24. Bc4 Nf6 { With his king far from the main battlefield, White does not have an obvious way of maintaining his initiative. The black king will soon take an active part to the fight. } ) 15... e4 16. Nd4 Nf6 17. Nb5 { This is the difference. } 17... c6 18. dxc6 bxc6 19. Nc3 ( 19. Nd6 Rd8 20. Rac1 Be6 21. b3 Rd7 $11 ) 19... Be6 { White has a somewhat better structure. However, Black needs just one tempo to consolidate with ...Nd5 or ...Rad8, so White has to act at once. } 20. f3 Rad8 { The most restrictive move order. The other rook may be useful on f8 still. } ( 20... exf3 21. Bxf3 $14 ) ( 20... Rfd8 21. Kf2 $5 Bd5 $5 ) 21. fxe4 ( { The point is that } 21. Kf2 { is comfortably met with } 21... Nd5 22. fxe4 fxe4+ ) ( 21. Rac1 exf3 22. Bxf3 c5 $11 ) 21... Nxe4 22. Nxe4 fxe4 23. Bxe4 ( 23. b3 e3 $5 24. Bxc6 Rd2 $44 ) 23... Rxd1+ 24. Rxd1 Bxa2 25. Bxc6 Rb8 { White has several ways of maintaining an extra pawn, but due the few pawns left on board and Black's normal coordination, the most probable result is a draw.. } 26. Rd2 ( 26. Ra1 Bc4 27. b3 Rxb3 28. Ra4 Be6 29. Rxa7 Kf8 $11 ) ( 26. Bf3 Rxb2 27. Rd8+ Kf7 28. Rd7+ Kf6 29. Rxa7 Be6 $11 ) 26... Kf8 27. Kf2 Be6 28. Bf3 a5 $11 ) 12... Rxf6 13. Qxd6 ( 13. Qc3 Nc6 $11 ) 13... cxd6 14. Rfd1 Nc6 15. Rd2 { White's position looks more pleasant due to the obvious pressure along the d-file. However, everything else is fine for Black. He can shut off the enemy bishop with ...e5-e4 at the right time and the white knight needs some time to get into the fight. Besides, the queenside configuration offers Black ideas for a blockade. } 15... a5 $14 ( 15... Be6 16. b3 Rd8 17. Rad1 $14 { Magerramov,E (2560) -Laketic,G (2440) Cheliabinsk-A 1991 1-0 } ) 16. Rad1 ( 16. Rc1 Kf8 17. Ne1 ( 17. Ng5 { only results in weakening the white kingside a bit. } 17... Rg6 18. h4 h6 19. Nf3 Rf6 20. Ne1 g5 21. hxg5 hxg5 22. Nc2 f4 $11 { Here is a line illustrating the differences induced by the opening of the h-file with respect to a similar line below. } 23. Na3 Bg4 24. Nb5 Rd8 25. Nc3 Nd4 26. Bxb7 $2 f3 $19 ) 17... Ke7 ( 17... g5 18. Nc2 f4 19. Na3 Bg4 20. Nb5 Rd8 21. Nc3 Nd4 22. Bxb7 $16 f3 23. e3 $18 ) 18. Nc2 Be6 19. Ne3 e4 20. g4 ( 20. Nd5+ Bxd5 21. cxd5 Ne5 22. Rc7+ Kf8 23. Rxb7 Rf7 24. Rxf7+ Kxf7 25. Rc2 a4 $44 ) 20... g6 21. gxf5 gxf5 22. Nd5+ Bxd5 23. cxd5 Ne5 24. Rc7+ Nd7 25. Rxb7 Rc8 $44 { In this and the previous line, the knight is stronger than the bishop and the rooks have enough room for generating counterplay. } ) 16... a4 17. Rxd6 Rxd6 18. Rxd6 Kf8 19. Rd2 Ke7 $44 { Black has rid himself of the weak pawn and centralized his king. He also maintains all his other trumps, while on the queenside he has even made progress. Abstractly, this is similar to the positions where Black sacrifices an exchange on a8 in the lines with Nc3, ...Bb4 above. } 20. Ne1 Na5 21. Rd5 e4 22. g4 Be6 23. Rb5 g6 24. gxf5 gxf5 $11 25. Bh3 ( 25. b3 $6 Bd7 26. Rb6 Bc6 { [%cal Ge7d6,Gd6c5] Threatening ...Kd6-c5. } 27. bxa4 Rd8 28. Rb1 Rd2 $15 ) 25... Nxc4 26. Rxb7+ ( 26. Bxf5 $2 Nd6 $19 ) 26... Kf6 27. Ng2 Nd6 28. Rb6 ( 28. Rxh7 Bxa2 29. Rd7 Nc4 30. Rb7 Bb3 ) 28... Ke5 $44 *
