1. d4 e6 2. g3 f5 3. Bg2 Nf6 4. Nh3 { This way of developing the knight is typical for the Dutch Defence. The f4-square is simply too inviting! Known since around 1850, this move has been used by such dogmatics as Steinitz and Tarrasch. (The good doctor from Nuerenberg apparently knew that the knight is not always misplaced on the edge of the board) . In the Leningrad system, this setup was introduced in Carlsbad 1923 by Bogoljubov. Alekhine apparently liked the idea and used it a few rounds later, too, but after a few more days, Bogoljubov himself had the same position with black! } 4... Be7 $5 { This is one of the situations when we should give up our secret hope of switching to the Leningrad system. Black should continue along the Iljin Zhenevsky setup, in which Black is ready to isolate the knight with . ..e6-e5 quicker. } ( { After } 4... g6 { , ...e7-e6 is a premature commitment, delaying ...e5. } ) 5. O-O O-O 6. c4 d6 7. Nc3 { This natural move does not face Black with serious problems. } ( 7. Nf4 { is not dangerous, either } 7... e5 8. dxe5 dxe5 9. Nd5 Nxd5 10. cxd5 Bd6 { Black has achieved a solid position in the centre and is not without chances on the kingside. } 11. Nd2 Nd7 12. Nc4 b6 $5 { Before anything, I prefer to secure the queenside and complete the development. } ( { The resolute } 12... f4 { is entirely playable, though. } 13. e3 fxg3 14. hxg3 Nf6 { Makhnev,D (2480) -Azarov,S (2604) Ville d'Orsay online Blitz 2021 (5) 1-0 } ) 13. Qc2 ( 13. Bd2 a5 14. Rc1 Ba6 15. Nxd6 cxd6 16. b4 axb4 17. Bxb4 Nc5 18. a4 Qd7 $11 ) 13... Qe7 14. Bd2 Ba6 $11 ) ( { The more consistent } 7. b3 { is examined in Lines 24 and 25. } ) ( 7. b4 { trying to improve over 7.b3, examined later, actually exposes the pawn on b4. } 7... e5 8. Bb2 ( 8. dxe5 dxe5 $11 ) 8... Nc6 $14 ( 8... Ng4 $2 { Kessler,A (2167) -Zill,C (2278) GER-ch 82nd Bonn 2011 (9) 0-1 } 9. Nc3 $16 ) 9. b5 ( 9. dxe5 dxe5 10. b5 Qxd1 11. Rxd1 Na5 12. Nd2 e4 13. Nf4 a6 14. a4 g5 15. Nd5 Nxd5 16. cxd5 Rd8 $13 ) 9... Nxd4 10. Bxd4 exd4 11. Qxd4 $6 Ne4 $15 ) 7... e5 8. dxe5 ( { In the event of } 8. b3 { , the only thing Black should avoid is blocking the centre with ...e5-e4, since this would make the f4-square available for the knight. } 8... c6 9. Bb2 Na6 10. a3 Qe8 11. b4 Nc7 $11 ) 8... dxe5 { We should say a few words about the difference between this type of position and those with the bishop on g7. Having the bishop in fianchetto is good for many things, of course. It could turn very active after ...e5-e4 and it could make the pawn sacrifice ...f5-f4 effective after e2-e4. Things are much simpler here. The bishop is suddenly active! More concrete details in later moments. } 9. Qxd8 ( 9. Qb3 c6 10. Ng5 Na6 $14 11. c5+ Kh8 12. Nf7+ Rxf7 13. Qxf7 Nxc5 { Suddenly, the white queen is in danger. One important detail is that the bishop on e7 defends the knight on c5. } 14. Rd1 ( 14. Qc4 Be6 15. Qh4 Ng4 16. Qh3 e4 $15 ) 14... Qc7 15. Qc4 f4 $5 ( 15... Be6 $44 16. Qh4 Ng4 $2 17. Bg5 $16 ) 16. Nb1 ( 16. e3 fxg3 17. hxg3 Bg4 18. Re1 $6 e4 $17 ) 16... Be6 17. Qc2 { Black is better developed,  and his minor pieces are harmoniously placed. He has good compensation for the exchange and several good moves at his disposal. } 17... Bf7 ( 17... a5 $5 ) ( 17... Nd5 $5 ) 18. gxf4 exf4 19. b4 Ne6 20. Bb2 Bxb4 21. Nd2 Bc5 22. Nf3 Bg6 $44 { Steinke,R (2389) -Nemec,Z (2335) SM-2014-0-00310 0-1 } ) ( 9. Nd5 h6 $14 { leaves the knight on h3 out of play. } ) 9... Bxd8 { Another typical aspect of this system. After ...c7-c6, the bishop could go to c7, consolidating the centre, or further to b6 or a5. } 10. e4 ( 10. b3 c6 11. Ba3 Re8 12. e4 $6 Nxe4 $1 ( 12... fxe4 13. Ng5 $14 ) 13. Nxe4 fxe4 { The bishop on d8 prevents Ng5. } 14. Rae1 ( 14. Rfe1 Bf5 $17 ) 14... Na6 ( 14... Bf5 15. f3 $44 ) 15. Rxe4 Bf5 { White's rooks are in danger. } 16. Re3 Bb6 17. Rf3 Bg4 18. Rc3 e4 $17 ) 10... c6 11. exf5 Bxf5 12. Re1 Nbd7 13. Ng5 Ba5 14. Bd2 Rae8 $11 { Goryachkina, A (2593) -Hoang, T (2404) EU-Cup Online Final (Women) rapid 2020 (8.2) 1/2-1/2 We can notice Black's harmonious development. } *
