1. d4 e6 2. g3 f5 3. Bg2 Nf6 4. Nh3 Be7 5. O-O O-O 6. c4 d6 7. b3 { This flexible move takes measures against ...e6-e5. } 7... c6 { It appears that Black should still prepare the advance in the centre. } ( 7... e5 $6 8. Bb2 $14 e4 ( 8... Ng4 $6 9. Qd2 $16 ) ( 8... Nc6 9. dxe5 dxe5 10. Qxd8 Bxd8 11. Bxc6 bxc6 12. Bxe5 $16 ) ( 8... Nbd7 9. Ng5 $16 ) 9. Nc3 d5 ( 9... c6 10. d5 Nbd7 11. f3 $16 { Postny, E (2605) -Amin, B (2690) C'Chartres Blitz op 2020 (9) 1-0 } ) 10. Nxd5 Nxd5 11. cxd5 Nd7 12. f3 Nf6 13. fxe4 fxe4 14. Qc2 Qxd5 15. Qxc7 Bd6 16. Qc4 Be6 17. Qxd5 Bxd5 18. Nf2 $14 ) ( { The typical regrouping } 7... Qe8 8. Bb2 Bd8 9. Nc3 e5 { may run into } 10. Ba3 $5 Be7 11. Qd2 $14 ) 8. Bb2 Qc7 9. Nd2 { This is by far the most popular continuation. Its main idea must be connected with the invasion of the d6-square at a later moment, while also with keeping the long diagonal open. } ( 9. Nc3 e5 10. Qd2 ( 10. e4 Na6 $11 ) ( 10. e3 a5 11. Rc1 Na6 12. Qd2 Bd7 { is similar to the main line. } ) 10... Na6 11. Rac1 Bd7 12. Rfd1 Rae8 ( 12... Rad8 $2 { Felice, A (2372) -Arnold, G (2406) WS MN/004 email 2005 0-1 causes some piece congestion, allowing an elegant combination. } 13. Nd5 $1 cxd5 14. cxd5 Qb8 15. dxe5 $16 dxe5 16. d6 $16 ) 13. e3 Qc8 { Both sides are perfectly regrouped... if we do not count the edged knight. } 14. f4 ( 14. a3 $2 f4 $17 ) 14... exd4 $1 ( 14... e4 15. Nf2 { followed by d4-d5. If Black blocks the queenside with ...c6-c5, White still maintains some chances in view of the possible plans on either wing: a2-a3 followed by b3-b4 and h2-h3 followed by g3-g4. Black might be fine, but the position would remain one-sided. } ) 15. exd4 Bd8 { Black continues regrouping harmoniously. } 16. Nf2 { Over defending e4. } ( 16. Ng5 h6 17. Nf3 Ne4 $11 ) 16... Re7 17. Ba3 Qb8 $11 { followed by ...R8e8. } ) 9... e5 10. Qc2 ( 10. e4 { is the most popular move, but } 10... Na6 { maintains Black's flexibility. } 11. dxe5 ( 11. Re1 Nb4 12. Bc3 Nd3 13. Re3 exd4 14. Bxd4 Ne5 15. exf5 Bxf5 $11 16. Bxe5 $2 dxe5 17. Ne4 Rad8 $17 ) 11... dxe5 12. Qe2 f4 $1 { A familiar move. } 13. gxf4 Bg4 $5 ( 13... exf4 $5 14. e5 Ng4 15. Nf3 Nc5 16. Rfe1 Ne6 $15 { Gochelashvili,D (2331) -Poluljahov,A (2516) Maikop op 2004 (7) 0-1 } ) 14. f3 ( 14. Nf3 exf4 $17 ) 14... Bxh3 15. Bxh3 Nh5 $15 16. Bxe5 Nxf4 $1 17. Bxc7 Nxe2+ 18. Kf2 Nd4 19. Be5 Rad8 $17 { White's weaknesses and the misplaced knight are more important than his extra pawn. The bishop on h3 is not such a good piece, either. } ) ( 10. c5 e4 $1 11. cxd6 Bxd6 { offers Black excellent stability on light squares. } 12. Nc4 Na6 13. Qc1 ( 13. f3 exf3 14. Bxf3 Nb4 $11 ) ( 13. Nxd6 Qxd6 14. Qc1 Be6 $11 { Anderson,C-Hey,B USA-ch S02002 email 2020 0-1 } ) 13... Be7 14. f3 Nb4 15. Nf2 exf3 16. Bxf3 ( 16. exf3 f4 $15 ) 16... Be6 17. a3 Nbd5 $15 { Pert,N (2562) -Pert,R (2440) GBR-ch 102nd 2015 (11) 1/2-1/2 } ) 10... Na6 $14 { It is curious that this developing move is a novelty. Black defends the queen and gets ready for ...e5-e4 followed by ...d6-d5. } ( 10... e4 $2 11. f3 $16 ) ( 10... Ng4 $2 11. e4 f4 12. c5 ( 12. gxf4 exf4 13. Nf3 $16 ) 12... fxg3 13. hxg3 dxc5 { Topalov,V (2460) -Ulybin,M (2585) Ibercaja op Zaragoza 1992 1/2-1/2 } 14. dxe5 Nd7 15. f4 Ne3 16. Qc3 Nxf1 17. Bxf1 b5 18. f5 $18 ) ( 10... a5 $14 { is another new move examined in the next line. } ) 11. dxe5 ( 11. a3 { wastes a tempo, allowing Black to stabilize with } 11... e4 $1 12. b4 ( 12. f3 d5 $15 ) 12... d5 $15 ) 11... dxe5 12. a3 { The only way of questioning Black's novelty. This move is the reason why I gave an alternative to ...Na6, even if things seem to be OK for Black here, too. } 12... h6 { Isolating the h3-knight. } ( 12... Nc5 13. b4 Nce4 14. Nxe4 Nxe4 15. Rad1 ( 15. Bxe4 fxe4 $17 ) 15... Bf6 16. f4 $14 ) 13. b4 Be6 14. c5 { This is the main plan connected with Nbd2. } ( 14. e4 $2 fxe4 15. Nxe4 Nxe4 16. Qxe4 Qc8 $17 ) ( 14. Rad1 Rad8 15. c5 Nb8 16. Nf3 Rxd1 17. Rxd1 Nbd7 18. Nh4 Nd5 19. Bxd5 { White starts to play for the dark squares. } 19... cxd5 20. Ng6 Re8 21. f4 e4 22. Nxe7+ Rxe7 { Things would be fantastic for White if he had the knight closer to d4. Since the knight will need some time to get back into play, Black will be able to organize his counterplay. } 23. Rc1 { [%cal Rd7b6] } 23... Qc6 24. Nf2 a5 25. Nd1 axb4 26. axb4 Qb5 27. Qd2 Nb8 28. Ne3 Nc6 29. Nc2 d4 $1 { Preventing the blockade just in time. } 30. Nxd4 Nxd4 31. Bxd4 e3 32. Bxe3 Bc4 33. Kf2 Re4 $44 { White's extra pawns do not really count. } ) 14... Nd5 ( 14... Rad8 15. Nc4 $16 ) 15. Nc4 Bf6 16. Rfe1 { A cunning move, preparing a later bishop's manoeuvre. } ( 16. e4 $6 fxe4 17. Kh1 ( 17. Qxe4 Qc8 18. Nd6 Qd7 $19 ) 17... b6 $11 ) ( 16. Rad1 b6 $11 ) ( 16. Rac1 Rad8 ) 16... e4 $1 { Now is the time for this move. } ( 16... b6 $2 { runs into } 17. e4 $1 fxe4 18. Qxe4 $16 Qc8 $2 19. Bf1 $3 Bxh3 20. Bd3 $18 ) 17. Bxf6 Rxf6 18. f3 exf3 ( 18... b6 { also tends to lead to unclear play. } 19. cxb6 axb6 20. fxe4 fxe4 21. Qxe4 b5 22. Na5 Re8 23. Nf2 Qb6 24. e3 c5 $13 ) 19. exf3 f4 20. g4 { Keeping the kingside solid, but providing Black with a good square on e3. Besides, the knight on h3 is still passive. } 20... Qd8 21. Nd6 Nac7 22. Nxb7 ( 22. Qe4 Qd7 23. Bf1 Raf8 24. Bd3 g5 $11 ) 22... Ne3 23. Qe4 ( 23. Rxe3 $2 Qd4 $17 ) ( 23. Qb2 Qd7 24. Nd6 Ncd5 $44 ) 23... Qd2 $5 ( 23... Qd7 24. Nxf4 Nxg2 25. Nxg2 Nb5 $44 ) 24. Nxf4 Ncd5 $13 *
