1. d4 e6 2. Nf3 f5 3. Bf4 { This setup enjoys some popularity lately, even at a high level and even against the normal Dutch move order 1.d4 f5 2.Nf3 Nf6 3.Bf4. } 3... Nf6 4. e3 Be7 { Black needs to organise his central break as soon as possible, in order to question the enemy bishop's activity. } ( 4... g6 { spends a tempo, delaying Black's main plan. } ) ( 4... b6 { is also time consoming. } 5. Be2 Bb7 6. O-O Be7 7. c4 O-O 8. Nc3 Ne4 ( { The tempting } 8... Nh5 { is not constructive. } 9. h3 Nxf4 10. exf4 Bf6 11. Re1 { After the opening of the e-file, Black's centre is a bit rigid. } ) 9. Nxe4 Bxe4 10. Nd2 Bb7 11. h3 d6 12. Rc1 Nd7 13. b4 e5 14. Bh2 ) 5. c4 { In this line, we will see the reason why White should delay (and in practice usually delays) the queenside development. } ( 5. Be2 { is examined in Line 32. } ) ( { For } 5. Bd3 { see Line 33. } ) 5... O-O 6. Nc3 Ne4 $1 { The most effective reaction. } ( { Even with the loss of one tempo, the Nimzo-Indian like } 6... Bb4 { is playable, since Bc1-f4 is not a constructive move from the point of view of the fight for the light squares. } 7. Bd3 { Ohanyan, E (2444) -Amin, B (2691) Olympic Esports Prelims blitz 2023 (4.4) 0-1 } ( 7. Rc1 $14 { may be better. } ) 7... Bxc3+ 8. bxc3 b6 9. O-O Bb7 10. Nd2 d6 $11 ) 7. Nxe4 ( 7. Qc2 Nxc3 8. Qxc3 g5 ( 8... b6 9. O-O-O Bb7 10. h4 d6 $13 ) 9. Bg3 f4 10. Bd3 { Poppe,T (1696) -Zimmermann,F (1606) Mecklenburg VP LL2 Ost 1314 2013 (4.4) 1-0 } 10... Nc6 $1 { Black should not be in a hurry to take the bishop, which would open the h-file for White's attack. It is good to know that the bishop is passive there. } 11. O-O-O d6 12. exf4 gxf4 13. Qd2 e5 14. dxe5 Nxe5 15. Nxe5 dxe5 $13 ) 7... fxe4 8. Nd2 d5 ( { The immediate exchange sacrifice is also possible: } 8... Rxf4 $5 9. exf4 d5 10. cxd5 exd5 11. Bb5 { Preventing ... Nc6. } 11... Bf6 12. Nb3 a6 { The bishop cannot maintain the control over c6. } 13. Be2 Nc6 14. O-O Qd6 15. g3 a5 16. a4 Nb4 17. f3 e3 $44 ) 9. Bg3 $14 { The safest. } ( 9. Qc2 $2 { Nagy,G (2484) -Lopez,J (2411) BEL-chT 1920 2019 (6.2) 1-0 } 9... Rxf4 $1 10. exf4 Nc6 { is troublesome for White. } 11. Qc3 ( 11. cxd5 exd5 12. Qc3 Bf6 13. Nb3 a5 14. a4 Be7 15. O-O-O Bg4 $19 { retrieving the exchange after ...Bb4 and maintaining a huge positional advantage. } ) 11... Bf6 12. Nb3 Nxd4 13. Nxd4 c5 $19 ) ( 9. Be2 Rxf4 $14 10. exf4 Nc6 { The main idea in these lines is that the pawn on d4 is a chronical weakness. } 11. Nb3 Bb4+ 12. Kf1 a5 13. a4 Qf6 14. g3 b6 15. cxd5 exd5 16. Kg2 Bd6 17. Rc1 Nb4 $44 ) 9... c5 $1 { Making use of Black's advance in development. } 10. dxc5 Na6 11. Be2 Nxc5 12. O-O b6 13. cxd5 exd5 14. b4 ( 14. Nb1 Bf6 15. Nc3 Bxc3 16. bxc3 Ba6 $11 ) ( 14. Nb3 Ba6 $11 ) 14... Nd3 15. Qb3 Kh8 16. Bxd3 exd3 17. Qxd3 Bxb4 18. Nf3 a5 ( 18... Bf5 19. Qb3 Bc5 20. Nd4 Qd7 { [%cal Gf5e4] } 21. Nxf5 ( 21. Rfd1 Be4 $11 ) 21... Rxf5 22. Rad1 Re8 $11 ) 19. Rfd1 Ba6 20. Qxd5 Qxd5 21. Rxd5 Bc4 22. Rd7 Rad8 23. Rxd8 Rxd8 $44 { Black is very active and the pawn on a2 is a permanent target. } 24. h3 ( 24. Bc7 Rd7 25. Bxb6 Bc3 26. Rc1 Bb2 27. Re1 Bc3 28. Rb1 Bxa2 29. Rc1 a4 $44 ) 24... a4 25. Bc7 Rc8 26. Bxb6 a3 $44 *
