1. d4 e6 2. Nf3 f5 3. Bf4 Nf6 4. e3 Be7 5. Be2 { A solid, even though not very active, move. } 5... O-O 6. O-O d6 7. c4 { The only way of fighting for an advantage. } ( 7. Nbd2 Nc6 8. h3 Qe8 9. c3 Kh8 $5 10. b4 Rg8 { with adequate counterplay. } ) ( 7. Re1 { is a time waste. } 7... Nc6 8. c4 Ne4 9. d5 Nb4 10. a3 Na6 11. dxe6 g5 12. Bg3 f4 13. exf4 gxf4 ) 7... Ne4 { With the bishop on e2, the best reaction. Black threatens ...g7-g5. } 8. h3 ( 8. Nfd2 g5 $1 9. Nxe4 ( 9. Bg3 Nxg3 10. hxg3 g4 { Preventing g3-g4, which may offer White some play. } 11. Nc3 Bf6 12. Qc2 Nc6 $11 ) 9... gxf4 10. Ned2 Bg5 11. exf4 Bxf4 12. Nc3 Kh8 ( 12... e5 $15 ) 13. Nb3 Rg8 14. g3 Bg5 15. f4 Bf6 16. Re1 Rg7 17. Kh1 a5 18. a4 Nc6 19. Bf1 Nb4 20. Qe2 Bd7 21. Bg2 c6 22. Rad1 Qf8 23. c5 { Brusila,H (2237) -Arppi,H (2323) FIN-ch58 email 2007 1/2-1/2 } 23... b6 $15 ) 8... Nc6 { Preparing ...Bf6. } 9. Bh2 ( 9. d5 { is not too effective with the bishop on f4 and without a king's fianchetto. White gives up the possibility of using his bishop for breaking with c4-c5 and the weakening of the light squares is not a problem for Black anymore. } 9... Nb4 10. a3 Na6 11. dxe6 ( 11. b4 e5 12. Bh2 Nb8 13. Nfd2 Nxd2 14. Nxd2 Nd7 15. Nb3 Nf6 16. c5 Qe8 17. Rc1 Qf7 18. Bc4 g5 $13 19. Bxe5 dxe5 20. d6 Be6 $11 ) 11... Nac5 12. Nd4 Bf6 13. Nd2 Bxd4 14. exd4 Nxe6 15. Be3 Nxd2 16. Bxd2 f4 $5 ( 16... Nxd4 17. Bh5 { followed by Bc3 yields WHite consistent compensation for the pawn. } ) 17. Bg4 ( 17. Bc3 Ng5 $17 ) 17... Qg5 18. Bc3 f3 19. Bxf3 Nf4 20. Kh2 Qh4 21. Bg4 ( 21. d5 Bxh3 22. gxh3 Qxh3+ 23. Kg1 Rf5 $19 ) 21... Bxg4 22. Qxg4 Qxg4 23. hxg4 Rae8 24. Rae1 Nd3 25. Rxe8 Rxe8 26. Kg3 Re2 $44 ) 9... Bf6 10. Ne1 ( 10. Nbd2 Nxd2 11. Qxd2 e5 $11 ) 10... e5 11. f3 Ng5 12. d5 Ne7 13. Nc3 Ng6 $11 { Black has regrouped harmoniously and is ready for a positional attack. } 14. f4 $6 exf4 15. exf4 Bxc3 16. bxc3 Ne4 $15 { Ushenina, A (2416) -Osmak, I (2438) Microsoft Leogaming (Women) blitz 2020 (14) 1/2-1/2 } *
