1. d4 e6 2. c4 f5 3. Nc3 { By taking the control over the important squares on e4 and d5 at an early stage, White declares his aggressive intentions. The only drawback of this move order is allowing ...Bb4, reducing his influence over the centre. As much as I would want to keep the game within Leningrad Dutch territory, I believe that Black is better advised to switch to a Nimzo/Dutch or Queen's Indian/Dutch hybrid against this move order. } 3... Nf6 { In order to understand the ensuing positions even better, you could also have a look to some lines in my Owen database. It could also help to check 4.e3 b6 in my Nimzoindian repertoire database. Both are published by Modern Chess. } 4. Bg5 { White applies the same method by pinning the knight on f6. This is likely to lead to simplifications, easing Black's play.. } ( 4. Bf4 { does not contribute to the fight for the centre. } 4... Bb4 5. Rc1 ( 5. Qc2 d6 6. e3 { Anticipating ...Ne4 and threatening Ne2 followed by a2-a3. } 6... Bxc3+ $1 7. Qxc3 Ne4 8. Qc2 Qe7 9. Nf3 Nc6 $11 { followed by ...e6-e5. } ) ( 5. e3 { , hoping for Nge2 allows } 5... Bxc3+ $1 6. bxc3 d6 7. Nf3 O-O 8. Be2 b6 9. O-O Bb7 $11 ) ( 5. Qb3 Nc6 6. e3 Bxc3+ 7. Qxc3 Ne4 8. Qc2 d6 $11 9. d5 exd5 10. cxd5 Ne7 $13 { Black's better development compensates for White's fragile space advantage. } ) 5... b6 6. Nf3 Bb7 7. e3 O-O 8. Be2 Ne4 $13 { With the possible idea of ...g7-g5. } 9. h4 $5 d6 10. Ng5 Bxc3+ 11. bxc3 Nxg5 ( 11... Qe7 $11 ) 12. Bxg5 ( 12. hxg5 $5 Bxg2 13. Rh2 $44 { White has all kinds of positional threats such as d4-d5, c4-c5, or doubling along the h-file. The bishop has to retreat to either e4 or c6, which are both vulnerable squares, since } 13... Bb7 $2 14. Bf3 $16 { would speed up White's queen's transfer to h3 or h5. } ) 12... Qe8 13. Bh5 Qd7 14. d5 Na6 $15 { Ipatov,A (2454) -Narciso Dublan,M (2553) Badalona 2009 (0-1, 34) } ) ( 4. f3 { is a premature display of territorial ambitions. } 4... d5 { The simplest. In the Stonewall structure, White does not usually weaken his square on e3 so early. As we will see, Black can play more actively than in a typical Stonewall. Instead of the solid ...c7-c6, he can display ambitions with ...c7-c5. } ( 4... Bb4 { is also possible, but not really a punishment for White's illogical plan. A typical line goes } 5. Bd2 $5 c5 6. e3 cxd4 7. exd4 O-O 8. a3 Bd6 9. Bd3 Nc6 10. Nge2 b6 11. b4 Bb7 { Black should be fine here, but his approach is a bit too hypermodern for me. } ) 5. Bg5 ( 5. e3 c5 6. Nh3 Nc6 7. dxc5 Bxc5 { Pashkin,N (1537) -Kontsevik,G (1979) Krasnodar Region-ch U16 2013 (1) 0-1 } 8. cxd5 exd5 9. Nf4 d4 10. exd4 Qe7+ $5 11. Qe2 Nxd4 12. Qxe7+ Kxe7 13. Bd3 Rd8 14. h4 Ne6 15. Nce2 Nh5 $11 ) ( 5. Bf4 c5 6. e3 Nc6 $11 ) 5... Be7 6. e3 ( 6. Qb3 dxc4 $14 7. Qxc4 a6 8. e4 b5 9. Qd3 O-O 10. O-O-O Nc6 $15 { Black is better developed and the white king is unsafe. } ) 6... O-O 7. Bd3 ( 7. Nh3 c5 $14 8. dxc5 Bxc5 9. cxd5 h6 $1 10. Bxf6 Qxf6 11. Qd2 Qe5 $13 ) 7... c5 8. Nge2 Nc6 $11 9. a3 ( 9. cxd5 Nxd5 10. Bxe7 Qxe7 $11 11. Qd2 $6 { Ortega, A (2240) -Sharp, D (2070) New York State-ch 124th 2002 (3) 1-0 Not wishing to weaken e3 by opening the e-file, but running into problems anyway. } 11... Nxe3 $1 12. Qxe3 cxd4 13. Nxd4 Qh4+ $15 ) ( 9. dxc5 Ne5 $5 10. cxd5 Bxc5 11. Bc2 Nf7 12. Bxf6 Qxf6 13. Qd2 e5 14. Na4 { Varonen,H (1912) -Donk,D FIN-NED email 2017 [22] 0-1 } 14... Bd6 $15 { Black has a perfect blockade and White has no perspectives for his minor pieces. Black could continue developing with ...Bd7, ...b7-b5, etc. } ) 9... cxd4 10. exd4 e5 11. O-O exd4 ( 11... e4 $5 ) ( 11... Be6 $5 ) 12. Bxf6 dxc3 13. Bxc3 Qb6+ 14. Kh1 d4 15. Bd2 Qxb2 16. Nf4 Qb6 17. Nd5 Qd8 18. Nxe7+ Qxe7 19. Re1 Qf7 $11 { Ivanisevic,I (2662) -Rombaldoni,A (2518) Bergamo op 14th 2015 (4) 1-0 White has certain compensation for the pawn, but Black is quite stable. } ) ( 4. a3 { is examined in Line 35. } ) ( 4. e3 { is the subject of Lines 36 and 37. } ) ( { For } 4. g3 { see Lines 38 and 39. } ) 4... Bb4 5. Rc1 ( 5. e3 h6 6. Bxf6 ( 6. Bh4 Bxc3+ 7. bxc3 d6 8. Nf3 b6 $11 { leaves the bishop on h4 a bit exposed. } ) 6... Bxc3+ $1 7. bxc3 Qxf6 8. Bd3 b6 9. Nh3 ( 9. Qf3 Nc6 10. e4 Bb7 $15 11. Ne2 { Georgiev,V (2579) -Marholev,D (2401) St Eufemia d'Aspromonte op 4th 2011 (3) 1/2-1/2 } 11... Na5 $17 ) 9... Bb7 10. O-O O-O $11 { With comfortable play for Black. } ) 5... b6 { Combining all Nimzowitsch' ideas. } 6. e3 Bb7 7. f3 { Preparing Bd3 followed by Nge2. } ( 7. Ne2 { is a bit one-sided. If Black does not cooperate to take on c3, White will face problems continuing his development. } 7... O-O 8. a3 ( 8. Nf4 h6 9. Bxf6 Qxf6 10. Be2 Bd6 11. Bf3 Bxf3 12. Qxf3 Nc6 13. O-O Bxf4 $5 14. Qxf4 Rac8 $11 ) 8... Be7 9. Nf4 c5 $1 { With the knight away from e2, the pawn on d4 is White's vulnerable spot. } ( 9... h6 $2 10. Bxf6 Bxf6 11. h4 $14 ) 10. Be2 cxd4 11. exd4 h6 $1 { After weakening the d4-square, Black can clear matters on the kingside. } 12. Bxf6 Bxf6 13. Ng6 ( 13. h4 Nc6 14. d5 Nd4 $15 ) 13... Re8 14. O-O Nc6 15. d5 Nd4 16. Bh5 Rc8 $11 { In the event of } 17. Nb5 ( 17. b3 exd5 18. Nxd5 Bxd5 19. cxd5 Rxc1 20. Qxc1 Nxb3 21. Qd1 Nd4 $13 ) ( 17. Nf4 Rf8 18. Ng6 Re8 19. Nf4 { Black is not forced to accept the draw by repetition. } 19... Rxc4 $5 20. Bxe8 Qxe8 { With fantastic compensation due to the hyperactive minor pieces. } ) 17... Nxb5 18. cxb5 Bxb2 $5 19. Rxc8 Qxc8 20. d6 Qc5 21. Ne7+ Rxe7 22. dxe7 Qxe7 23. Bf3 d5 $44 ) 7... h6 8. Bh4 g5 9. Bg3 Nc6 { [%cal Gd8e7,Gd7d6] } 10. Bd3 ( 10. d5 exd5 11. cxd5 Ne7 $15 { leaves White exposed in the centre. } 12. d6 Ned5 13. dxc7 Qe7 $15 ) 10... Bxc3+ ( 10... Qe7 11. Ne2 O-O-O 12. O-O Bxc3 13. Nxc3 f4 14. exf4 Nxd4 $13 ) 11. Rxc3 Qe7 12. Ne2 ( 12. Bxc7 d6 $17 ) 12... O-O-O 13. O-O Kb8 14. e4 fxe4 15. fxe4 h5 16. e5 Ng4 17. Be4 Rdf8 $11 { With excellent counterplay. } *
