1. d4 e6 2. c4 f5 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. a3 { This would be a useful move, preventing ...Bb4, if Black would be prepared,  only for the Dutch/Nimzo Indian or Dutch/Queen's Indian hybrids. Since our main hope is reaching a Leningrad Dutch structure, the last move only offers us a tempo for free. True, at a later stage the move could prove useful after b2-b4, but in the short term it absolves Black of real danger. } 4... g6 ( 4... d5 { does not seem entirely logical, as White has not obstructed his c1-bishop yet. } 5. Bg5 c6 6. e3 $14 { Mihailovs,J (2405) -Moskalenko,V (2565) Barcelona 2010 (1/2-1/2, 34) } ) 5. h4 { I have picked up this move as the main continuation because Black needs a bit of accuracy now. } ( 5. Bg5 { is supposed to be a dangerous system in the positions without ... a7-a6 and a2-a3. While the latter is useless, the former allows Black to challenge the bishop at once. } 5... h6 $1 6. Bxf6 Qxf6 7. e4 ( 7. e3 $14 d6 8. g4 { is an interesting plan. } 8... e5 $5 9. dxe5 dxe5 10. gxf5 Bxf5 11. Nge2 Nd7 12. Nd5 { White must play actively since otherwise Black would be better developed after 0-0-0. } 12... Qd6 13. Ng3 O-O-O 14. Nxf5 gxf5 15. Bh3 Kb8 16. Bxf5 Nc5 { Black has good compensation for the pawn. In order to avoid the worst of it, White should probably provoke simplifications with } 17. b4 c6 18. bxc5 Qxc5 19. Qb3 cxd5 20. cxd5 Qxd5 21. Qxd5 Rxd5 $11 { Black's queenside advantage compensates for the weakness on e4. } ) 7... d6 ( 7... Bg7 $5 8. e5 Qe7 9. f4 d6 10. Nf3 dxe5 11. dxe5 g5 12. g3 O-O 13. Bg2 Rd8 14. Qe2 Nc6 { Planning ...Nd4. probably after ...g5-g4. } 15. Qe3 $6 Na5 $36 { Now is one of the moments when a2-a3 proves a weakening move. } ) 8. Nf3 Bg7 9. Qc2 O-O 10. Bd3 $6 ( 10. O-O-O Nc6 11. exf5 Qxf5 12. Qxf5 Rxf5 13. Bd3 Rf4 14. Nb5 Bd7 15. Nxc7 Rc8 16. Nb5 d5 $13 17. c5 $2 e5 $17 ) 10... Nc6 11. Ne2 $6 g5 $17 { Anciaux,A (2282) -Glek, I (2419) BEL-ch Bruges 2023 (5) 0-1 } ) ( { Soon after seeing the game Salimova-Muzychuk, I had the following game: } 5. g3 { AFter this move, ...e7-e6 is clearly more useful than a2-a3. } 5... Bg7 6. Bg2 O-O 7. Nh3 d6 8. Nf4 c6 9. Qb3 { Hernandez Leon,A (2202) -Marin,M (2445) San Cristobal op 5th 2023 (8) 0-1 } ( 9. Nd3 Qe7 $11 ) 9... e5 10. dxe5 dxe5 11. c5+ Rf7 12. Ne6 Bxe6 13. Qxe6 e4 $15 14. O-O Nbd7 15. Rd1 Nd5 16. Nxd5 Nxc5 17. Nf6+ Qxf6 $17 ) ( 5. Bf4 Bg7 6. e3 O-O 7. Nf3 d6 8. Be2 { At this moment, the move ...e7-e6 is more useful than a2-a3. It prevents a central blockade based on d4-d5 and allows the queen's development to e7. } 8... Nc6 ( 8... h6 { The plan introduced by this move loses time and results in the weakening of the light squares. } 9. h3 g5 $2 { The illusion of playing against the f4-bishop proves too strong. } 10. Bh2 Nbd7 11. Qc2 b6 12. Rd1 Kh8 13. b4 Bb7 14. d5 $16 { Topalov,V (2772) -Vallejo Pons,F (2698) Olympiad-41 Tromsoe 2014 (3.1) 1-0 After the bishop has emerged on b7, this is just natural. For the time being, Black has indirect ways of defending the f5-pawn, but these are only temporary solutions while the core of the problem will persist. } ) ( { Or if Black wanted to develop his queen's bishop to b7, he should have done it without weakening the f5-pawn anyway: } 8... b6 9. O-O Bb7 ) 9. d5 ( 9. Qc2 Qe7 $11 { , preparing either ...e6-e5 or ...Nd8-f7. } ) 9... e5 $1 10. dxc6 exf4 11. cxb7 Bxb7 12. exf4 Ne4 $44 13. Rc1 ( 13. Nxe4 fxe4 $19 ) ( 13. Qc2 Nxc3 14. bxc3 Qe7 15. O-O Qe4 16. Qd2 Bh6 $11 17. g3 Bg7 $15 ) 13... Bxc3+ $5 14. bxc3 Qf6 15. Qc2 Rfe8 16. O-O Nxc3 $11 ) ( 5. e3 { is inoffensive. } 5... Bg7 6. Bd3 O-O 7. Nge2 ( 7. Nf3 b6 $5 8. O-O Bb7 9. b4 c5 $11 ) 7... d6 8. O-O e5 9. f3 { Sarana,A (2662) -Kamsky,G (2666) Titled Tuesday intern op 09th Aug Early blitz 2022 (11) 1-0 } 9... c6 10. b4 Be6 $11 ) 5... d6 $14 { Anticipating White's threat. } ( 5... Bg7 $6 6. h5 Nxh5 7. e4 $14 { Threatening Rxh5 with a strong attack. } 7... Nf6 8. e5 Ng8 9. Nf3 $18 { Vishnu, P (2476) -Sengupta, D (2527) FIDE World Cup AICF Qual rapid 2021 (3) 0-1 } ) 6. h5 ( 6. e3 Bg7 7. Be2 h6 8. Nh3 e5 $11 ) 6... Nxh5 7. e4 ( 7. Rxh5 gxh5 8. e4 Qf6 { leaves White with uncertain compensation for the exchange. } ) 7... Nf6 $1 { This is why ...d7-d6 was necessary. } ( 7... Qf6 $2 { does not work without the previous sacrifice on h5. } 8. exf5 exf5 9. Be2 Ng7 10. Nf3 $18 { with a huge advance in development. } ) 8. Bg5 fxe4 9. Nxe4 Be7 $11 { White has some compensation for the pawn, but not an advantage. } *
