1. d4 e6 2. c4 f5 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. e3 { This solid and flexible move should be treated with seriousness. } 4... b6 { I believe that this is the best way of staying within hyper-modern territory. } ( { I am a bit worried by } 4... g6 5. h4 ( 5. Bd3 { , preparing a quick opening of the centre may also be an issue. } ) 5... Qe7 ( 5... Bg7 $2 6. h5 $1 Nxh5 7. Rxh5 gxh5 8. Qxh5+ Kf8 9. Nf3 $14 ) 6. Be2 b6 ( 6... h6 7. Nh3 $16 ) 7. Bf3 ( 7. h5 g5 $11 ) ( 7. Nh3 Bb7 8. O-O Bg7 $11 ) 7... Nc6 8. Nh3 $14 { Black's position is a bit unnatural. } ) ( 4... Bb4 { is adequately met with } 5. Ne2 { folowed by a2-a3. The difference with respect to similar positions in the next Line is that White does not have an exposed bishop on g5. } ) ( 4... d5 { leads to a STonewall. Without the early commitment f2-f3, I do not feel that it suits our repertoire so well. } ) 5. Bd3 ( 5. a3 { is likely to transpose to 4.a3. } ) ( 5. d5 { leads to some sort of Owen structure. Instead of a2-a3, White has played e2-e3, which is not very useful for the control in the centre and also restricts the c1-bishop. Moreover, ...Bb4 is a latent threat and in some cases, White would have to play a2-a3 anyway. } 5... Bb7 6. Nge2 ( 6. a3 Bd6 $11 { is a comfortable Owen. } ) ( 6. Nf3 Bb4 $11 { is also comfortable for Black. } ) ( 6. dxe6 dxe6 7. Qxd8+ Kxd8 $15 { leaves White behind in development. } ) 6... Na6 7. g3 c6 8. Bg2 ( 8. dxe6 dxe6 9. Qxd8+ Rxd8 10. Bg2 e5 $15 ) 8... cxd5 9. cxd5 Nb4 10. Nf4 e5 11. a3 ( 11. Nfe2 e4 { wins the central pawn. } ) ( 11. Nd3 { Handke,F (2413) -Bauer,C (2517) Metz op 18th 2000 (6) 0-1 } 11... Nxd3+ 12. Qxd3 e4 13. Qd4 Qb8 14. b3 Bc5 15. Qd2 Ng4 $15 ) 11... exf4 12. axb4 fxg3 13. hxg3 ( 13. fxg3 Bxb4 14. O-O O-O 15. Rxf5 { Giorgadze,G-Romero Holmes,A (2465) Elgoibar 07th 1997 (4) 1-0 } 15... Qe8 16. Qb3 Qg6 $15 ) 13... Bxb4 14. Qc2 O-O 15. Qxf5 a5 16. Bd2 Qc7 17. O-O Rae8 18. Nb5 Qc5 19. Bxb4 Qxb4 $11 ) ( 5. Nh3 { is examined in the next line. } ) 5... Bb7 6. f3 ( 6. Nf3 Bb4 { It is hard to refrain from this move. } ( 6... g6 7. O-O Bg7 { should be also playable, but I am a bit put off by the fact that White can start his queenside attack with } 8. b4 { , without having spent a tempo on a2-a3. } ) 7. O-O ( 7. Bd2 Bxc3 8. Bxc3 Ne4 $11 ) 7... Bxc3 8. bxc3 c5 $11 ) 6... c5 { A logical reaction to White's weakening his centre. } ( 6... Bb4 7. Ne2 $14 ) 7. Nge2 ( 7. d5 exd5 8. cxd5 Nxd5 9. Nxd5 Bxd5 10. Bxf5 Bb7 11. Ne2 g6 12. Bc2 Qh4+ 13. Ng3 Nc6 14. Be4 O-O-O $15 { Del Rio de Angelis, S (2527) -Sutovsky, E (2628) Gibraltar Masters 15th 2017 (9) 0-1 } ) 7... Nc6 8. O-O ( 8. d5 Ne5 9. e4 fxe4 10. fxe4 Bd6 11. O-O O-O $15 { Siekanska,M (2029) -Bondar,D EU-ch U16 Girls 30th 2022 (4) 0-1 } ) 8... Bd6 9. d5 ( 9. b3 Qc7 10. h3 a6 11. Bb2 O-O $13 ) 9... Ne5 10. e4 O-O ( 10... fxe4 { runs into } 11. Nxe4 { Laznicka, V (2679) -Vallejo Pons, F (2698) Wch Rapid Dubai 2014 (3) 1-0 , but even this is bearable. } 11... Qc7 12. Nxd6+ Qxd6 13. Bf4 O-O 14. Nc3 exd5 15. cxd5 Rae8 $13 ) 11. exf5 exd5 12. cxd5 Nxd3 13. Qxd3 Qc7 { The position is very interesting but offers Black excellent chances for fighting for the initiative. } 14. h3 ( 14. Kh1 c4 15. Qd4 Qc5 16. Qxc5 Bxc5 17. Nf4 { Morley, P (2384) -Cuccumini, V (2192) Webchess op5 sf07 email 2014 1-0 } 17... Rae8 18. Bd2 b5 19. a3 a5 20. Nxb5 Nxd5 21. Nxd5 Bxd5 22. Bxa5 Bc6 23. a4 Rxf5 24. Bc3 Bxb5 25. axb5 d5 $11 ) 14... c4 15. Qd1 Bc5+ ( 15... b5 16. Kh1 a6 17. a3 Rae8 $44 ) ( 15... Rae8 $44 ) 16. Kh1 Qe5 17. g4 $2 ( 17. Qa4 Nxd5 18. Qxc4 Rxf5 19. Bd2 Rf7 $11 ) 17... Nxd5 18. Nxd5 Qxd5 19. Qxd5+ Bxd5 20. Bd2 Rae8 $17 { Kazhgaleyev,M (2573) -Vallejo Pons,F (2706) Moscow op-A 2015 (8) 0-1 } *
