1. d4 e6 2. c4 f5 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. e3 b6 5. Nh3 $5 { A flexible move, intending to prepare f2-f3 without running into a piece congestion as in the previous line. } 5... Bb7 6. f3 Nc6 $5 { Black is heading for Steinitz' setup. } ( 6... Bb4 { is ineffective, since Black does not have access to e4 after, say, } 7. Bd2 $14 ) ( 6... g6 { is another possible move order, but after } 7. Be2 ( 7. Nf4 $5 ) 7... Bg7 $6 { is premature. } ( 7... Nc6 { transposes below. } ) 8. e4 $14 fxe4 9. fxe4 Nxe4 $2 10. Nxe4 Bxe4 11. O-O $16 { The black king is stuck in the centre and the bishop on e4 is exposed. } ) 7. Be2 ( 7. Bd3 { Kostov,N (1631) -Kolev,N (1931) Sofia MGU op 205th 2018 (6) 1/2-1/ 2 removes the threat of e3-e4 and weakens the control on d4 in general. It also exposes the bishop. } 7... g5 $5 { The most exotic of the possible continuations. } ( 7... g6 8. O-O Bg7 9. a3 O-O 10. b4 Qe7 { followed by ...Nd8-f7. } ) ( 7... Qe7 8. O-O O-O-O $11 ) 8. e4 ( 8. Nxg5 Rg8 $17 ) ( 8. O-O Rg8 $13 ) 8... h6 9. e5 ( 9. exf5 Qe7 10. Be3 exf5 11. Kd2 f4 12. Bf2 O-O-O $11 ) ( 9. d5 Ne5 10. Be2 Bb4 11. f4 Nf7 12. exf5 exd5 $13 ) 9... Nh5 ( 9... Nxd4 $5 10. exf6 Qxf6 $44 ) 10. Be3 Qe7 11. g4 ( 11. O-O O-O-O $15 ) 11... Ng7 12. Qe2 O-O-O 13. O-O-O Kb8 14. Rhe1 Qf7 { Planning ...d7-d6. } 15. c5 Nb4 16. Kb1 Be7 $13 ) 7... g6 ( 7... g5 $2 8. e4 h6 9. d5 Ne5 10. f4 $16 ) 8. Nf4 ( 8. e4 { is adequately met with } 8... fxe4 9. fxe4 e5 $1 10. d5 Nd4 11. O-O Bg7 ) ( 8. O-O Bg7 9. a3 O-O { is a typical Owen position. In order to avoid repeating what I had said in the respective database, I only inserted a recent game of mine, starting with 1.c4 b6. } 10. Bd2 Qe7 11. Rc1 Nd8 12. Re1 Nf7 13. Bf1 c5 14. b4 d6 15. bxc5 bxc5 16. dxc5 dxc5 17. Nf2 Rad8 18. Qc2 Ne5 19. Be2 Rd7 20. Na4 Rc8 21. Bc3 $11 { Bischoff,K (2473) -Marin,M (2437) UKA Invitational Uhlmann 2023 (8.4) 1/2-1/2 } ) 8... Bg7 ( 8... Qe7 9. d5 Nd8 { runs into some problems. } 10. Nb5 d6 11. Qa4 Kf7 12. dxe6+ Nxe6 13. Nxe6 Kxe6 { This surely looks adventurous for Black. } ) ( 8... g5 9. Nd3 Qe7 10. O-O { leaves Black a bit more exposed. Since the white knight is not on h3 anymore, the threat ...g5-g4 is easily parried with f3-f4. } ) 9. d5 { The logical continuation. } ( 9. O-O O-O 10. Bd2 Qe7 11. Rc1 d6 $5 ( 11... Nd8 $6 12. b4 ) 12. a3 Nd8 $11 ) 9... exd5 10. cxd5 Ne5 { White has gained space in the centre, but has a relative weakness on e3 and his queen's bishop is passive. Besides, Black is well regrouped. } 11. d6 ( 11. O-O O-O $11 ) ( 11. Qb3 Nf7 12. Bd2 g5 13. Nd3 a5 $13 ) ( 11. h4 Nf7 12. Bd2 Qe7 $13 ) 11... cxd6 { WHite will have the better structure, but Black's better development will keep the balance even. } 12. Qxd6 ( 12. Nb5 Nf7 13. Bc4 ( 13. Nxd6+ Nxd6 14. Qxd6 Qe7 15. Qxe7+ Kxe7 16. Bd2 g5 17. Nd3 Rac8 $11 ) 13... d5 14. Nxd5 Bxd5 15. Bxd5 Nxd5 16. Qxd5 O-O 17. O-O Qe7 $11 ) 12... Nf7 13. Qa3 ( 13. Qd1 O-O 14. O-O Rc8 15. Nfd5 Nxd5 16. Nxd5 Re8 $11 17. Rb1 { hoping for b2-b3 and Bb2. } 17... Re6 $15 { with certain initiative to Black. } ) 13... g5 14. Nd3 Qe7 $11 *
