1. d4 e6 2. c4 f5 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. g3 Bb4 { There is no need to refrain from this move. The planned king's fianchetto (Bg2) will weaken the defence of the c4-pawn. It is worth mentioning that the fashionable Romanischin system in the Nimzo Indian is usually played via the 4.Nf3 c5 5.g3 move order. With the pawn on c7 yet, Black's centre is more flexible. } ( { Once again, I am a bit reluctant to play } 4... g6 5. Bg2 Bg7 6. d5 $5 ( 6. Nh3 d6 ) ( 6. e4 fxe4 7. Nxe4 Nxe4 8. Bxe4 d5 9. Bg2 dxc4 10. Be3 O-O 11. Ne2 Nd7 12. O-O Nb6 $11 ) 6... d6 ( 6... e5 7. d6 $16 ) 7. dxe6 Nc6 8. Nh3 Bxe6 9. O-O $14 ( 9. b3 Ne4 10. Nxe4 fxe4 11. Rb1 Bf5 $13 ) ( 9. Nd5 Ne4 10. O-O O-O 11. Rb1 a5 $11 { Deforel,J (2093) -Kurowski,A (2038) WC-2012-F-00004 1/2-1/2 } ) 9... Qd7 ( 9... O-O 10. Ng5 $14 ) ( 9... Bxc4 10. Qa4 Be6 11. Ng5 Bd7 12. Qb3 $16 ) ( 9... h6 10. Nf4 Bf7 11. e4 $14 ) 10. Nd5 ( 10. b3 Ne4 11. Nxe4 fxe4 12. Ng5 Bxa1 $19 ) ( 10. Qb3 Rb8 $14 ) 10... Ne4 11. Ng5 Nxg5 12. Bxg5 O-O 13. Qd2 Ne5 14. b3 c6 15. Nc3 $14 ) 5. Qc2 ( 5. Qb3 Nc6 6. Nf3 Ne4 { does not spare White the trouble of having double pawns. } 7. Bg2 O-O 8. O-O Bxc3 9. bxc3 b6 10. Nd2 Na5 { It appears that the queen is exposed on b3. } 11. Qc2 Nxd2 12. Bxd2 Rb8 13. c5 { Leonov,M (2268) -Golubka,P (2403) Tula 12 2010 (7) 0-1 } 13... Ba6 14. Rfe1 Nc4 15. Qa4 Qc8 16. Bf4 bxc5 $13 ) ( 5. Bd2 { is rather modest, too. } 5... O-O 6. Bg2 d6 7. Nf3 Nc6 8. O-O ( 8. a3 Bxc3 9. Bxc3 Ne4 10. Qc2 Qf6 11. O-O e5 $11 ) 8... e5 $11 ) ( 5. Bg2 { is examined in the next line. } ) 5... Nc6 6. Nf3 Ne4 { We have transposed to a famous game, coming via the 4.Nf3 Ne4 move order in the Nimzo Indian. } 7. Bg2 ( 7. Bd2 Nxd2 8. Qxd2 d6 $11 { is comfortable for Black. } 9. d5 Ne5 10. Nxe5 dxe5 $11 { does not change anything. } ) 7... Bxc3+ $14 ( 7... O-O $6 { was the move order chosen by Karpov. } 8. O-O Bxc3 9. bxc3 { The point is that } 9... b6 { is more problematic after the insertion of castles. It would still have been better than the game continuation. } ( 9... Na5 10. c5 d6 11. c4 b6 12. Bd2 Nxd2 13. Nxd2 d5 14. cxd5 exd5 15. e3 $16 { Kasparov,G (2700) -Karpov,A (2720) World-ch31-KK2 Kasparov-Karpov +5-3=16 1985 (19) 1-0 } ) 10. d5 Na5 11. dxe6 Bb7 $1 ( 11... dxe6 $2 12. Ng5 $16 Nxg5 13. Bxa8 c6 14. Rd1 $1 { This gain of tempo is not available without the mutual castles. } 14... Qe7 15. Bxg5 Qxg5 16. Qa4 $18 ) 12. Nd4 ( 12. exd7 Qxd7 { with good play due to the weakness on c4. } ) 12... Qe7 ( 12... Nxc4 13. Nxf5 $14 ) 13. exd7 ( 13. Nxf5 Qxe6 14. Nd4 Qe7 $44 ) 13... Nxc4 { Black's position is a bit shaky in these lines, but he may be OK. } ) 8. bxc3 b6 $1 { This is best done before castling. } 9. d5 ( 9. O-O Bb7 $11 ) 9... Na5 10. dxe6 dxe6 11. Ng5 Nxg5 12. Bxa8 c6 13. Bxg5 Qxg5 14. Qa4 Bd7 $13 { The last move was not available in the end of the similar line above. } *
