1. d4 e6 2. c4 f5 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. g3 Bb4 5. Bg2 { A principled continuation. White continues developing flexibly, hoping that his pressure along the long light diagonal and the bishops' pair in general will be more important than the queenside weaknesses. } 5... Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 d6 7. Nf3 ( 7. Nh3 $5 O-O 8. Nf4 ( 8. O-O Nc6 { preparing ...e6-e5 under optimal circumstances. } 9. d5 Na5 $11 10. Qa4 b6 11. dxe6 Bxe6 12. Bxa8 Qxa8 { with fantastic compensation for the exchange. } ) 8... Qe8 $14 { The best way of preparing ...Nc6, by clearing the d8-square and staying away from the a3-f8 diagonal. After a later ...Na5, the enemy queen will be deprived of the a4-square. } ( 8... Nc6 9. d5 $14 ) ( 8... Qe7 9. O-O Nc6 10. c5 dxc5 11. Ba3 $14 ) 9. O-O ( 9. c5 dxc5 10. Ba3 Ne4 11. Nd3 Nd7 12. dxc5 c6 $13 ) 9... Nc6 10. Ba3 ( 10. Qc2 b6 $5 11. Ba3 Bb7 12. c5 dxc5 13. dxc5 Rf7 $11 ) ( 10. d5 Nd8 11. dxe6 Nxe6 $11 ) 10... Na5 11. c5 Nc4 12. Bc1 d5 $11 { Folowed by ..b7-b6 soon. } ) ( { At this stage, } 7. Rb1 { is inoffensive. } 7... O-O $14 ( 7... Nc6 { is entirely playable, of course. } ) 8. Bxb7 ( 8. Rxb7 Bxb7 9. Bxb7 Nbd7 10. Bxa8 Qxa8 11. Nf3 Qc6 $11 ) 8... Bxb7 9. Rxb7 Nbd7 10. Rb3 Nb6 11. Qd3 c5 $11 { In these lines, Black is better developed and the weakness on c4 chronicle. } ) 7... O-O 8. O-O Nc6 9. d5 ( 9. Ba3 Ne4 ( 9... Re8 $5 10. c5 Na5 $14 11. Qa4 b6 $11 ) 10. Qd3 Re8 $1 { I feel that this is the most logical move, played many decades ago and never repeated afterward. Well, progress has its specific aspects... } 11. d5 ( 11. c5 Na5 { planning ...b7-b6 } 12. Bb4 Nc6 $11 ) 11... exd5 ( 11... Na5 $5 12. Bb4 c5 ) 12. cxd5 Ne5 13. Nxe5 Rxe5 { When going for this position, the grandmaster from the past had a good positional feeling. White has more space, but also some weaknesses and an imperfect regrouping. } 14. c4 Re7 $6 ( 14... Qe8 $1 15. f3 $2 Nxg3 16. hxg3 Re3 ) ( 14... b6 15. f3 Nc5 $11 ) 15. Rae1 ( 15. f3 $14 ) 15... b6 $11 16. Qd4 Qf8 17. f3 Nc5 18. e4 Qe8 $1 19. e5 Rxe5 20. Bb2 Qf7 21. f4 Rxe1 22. Rxe1 Bd7 23. Bf3 Re8 { Reshko,A-Gurgenidze,B URS-ch28 Semifinal 1960 1/2-1/2 } 24. Rxe8+ Bxe8 25. Bh5 Qe7 26. Bxe8 Qe1+ 27. Kg2 Qe2+ { with a perpetual. Had Black played ...b7-b6 and ...Re7 in the reversed move order, this would have been a perfect game, the same as the decision of agreeing to a draw. } ) ( 9. c5 dxc5 ( 9... Ne4 $14 10. cxd6 cxd6 11. c4 Na5 12. c5 b6 13. Ng5 d5 $11 ) 10. Ba3 Ne4 11. Qc2 Qe8 $1 { A fine move, removing the queen from the d-file and over-defending the knight on c6 in order to prepare ...b7-b6. } ( 11... Re8 $6 { is usually played, but this leaves Black under some pressure after } 12. Rad1 $14 ) ( 11... b6 12. Nd2 $18 ) 12. Nd2 ( 12. Rad1 b6 ) 12... Nxd2 13. Qxd2 b6 14. dxc5 Rf6 $1 ( 14... Rf7 $2 15. cxb6 axb6 16. Bxc6 Qxc6 17. Qd8+ Rf8 18. Qxf8# ) 15. Rad1 ( 15. cxb6 axb6 16. Bxc6 Qxc6 17. Qd8+ Kf7 $17 ) 15... Bb7 16. Qd7 Rf7 17. Qxe8+ Rxe8 18. Bb4 Ba8 $11 { Savegren,K (2435) -Peschardt,S (2430) Swiss Friends White email 2007 1/2-1/2 } ) ( 9. Rb1 e5 $11 ) 9... Na5 10. dxe6 Bxe6 11. Nd4 Bxc4 ( 11... Qd7 12. Nxe6 Qxe6 13. Qa4 b6 { This is not necessary, but it would be a pity not to play it! } ( 13... Nxc4 14. Bxb7 Rab8 ) 14. Bxa8 Rxa8 15. c5 { Otherwise, White might be a bit worse. } 15... dxc5 16. Bf4 Nc4 $13 { Black has entirely adequate compensation for the exchange, due to the control on light squares. } 17. Bxc7 ( 17. Qb3 c6 $11 ) 17... g5 { The bishop is in some danger due to the threat ...Ne8.. } 18. Rad1 ( 18. Qa6 Ne8 19. Bxb6 $1 Nxb6 20. a4 Nd6 21. a5 Nbc4 22. Rfd1 $13 ) 18... Nb2 19. Qc2 Nxd1 20. Rxd1 Nd5 21. Bd6 $11 ( 21. Bd8 Rxd8 22. c4 Rd7 23. cxd5 Rxd5 $17 ) 21... Nf6 ( 21... Qxd6 $2 22. Qxf5 $18 ) 22. Bc7 ( 22. a4 Rc8 { Threatening Ne4. } 23. f3 Rd8 $1 { AFter White has weakened his kingside, this is stronger than before. } 24. Bc7 Rxd1+ 25. Qxd1 Nd5 26. Bb8 Nxc3 $19 ) 22... Nd5 $11 ) 12. Nxf5 ( 12. Qa4 b6 13. Bxa8 Qxa8 $44 { Since we have seen this sacrifice a lot, now is the moment to explain its abstract essence. As mentioned above, White's hopes are connected with the strength of his bishops. This is why he agrees to have queenside weaknesses. In these lines with Bxa8, the bishop's pressure has resulted in a small material gain, which is just enough to compensate for the positional problems. We should also add that without his colleague the dark-squared bishop risks to become a passive piece. } ) 12... Qd7 13. Ne3 Be6 14. c4 Rae8 { The position remains interesting and it is worth following the game as it advances. } 15. Qd4 Bh3 16. Bd5+ Kh8 17. Rd1 Nc6 18. Qh4 Ne7 19. Bh1 c5 20. Bb2 Ng6 21. Qg5 Ne4 22. Bxe4 Rxe4 23. Qh6 Rf7 24. Rd3 Kg8 25. Qh5 Ne5 26. Bxe5 Rxe5 27. Qh4 ( 27. Qxe5 dxe5 28. Rxd7 Rxd7 29. f3 Be6 $11 ) 27... Bf5 28. Nxf5 $1 ( 28. Rd2 $2 Re4 29. Qh5 Rxe3 ( 29... Bg6 30. Qg5 Qe6 $17 ) 30. fxe3 Qe7 31. e4 Bxe4 32. Rf1 $2 ( 32. Qh4 $1 g5 33. Qh6 $13 ) 32... Bg6 $19 33. Rxf7 Qe3+ 34. Rf2 Bxh5 35. Rxd6 h6 { Beliavsky,A (2560) -Gulko,B (2530) URS-chT Cup 09th 1976 (2) 0-1 } ) 28... Rexf5 29. f3 Qe8 30. Kf1 ( 30. Re1 Rxf3 $17 ) 30... R5f6 $11 *

